WEBVTT

00:00:16.180 --> 00:00:21.120
Alice was beginning to get very tired of sitting by her sister on the bank and of having nothing

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:26.120
to do. Once or twice she peeped into the book her sister was reading, but it had no pictures

00:00:26.120 --> 00:00:30.440
or conversations in it. And what's the use of a book, thought Alice, without pictures

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:35.980
or conversation? So she was considering in her own mind, as well as she could, for the

00:00:35.980 --> 00:00:40.560
hot day made her feel very sleepy and stupid, whether the pleasure of making a daisy chain

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:45.040
would be worth the trouble of getting up and picking the daisies, when suddenly a white

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:51.240
rabbit with pink eyes ran close by her. There was nothing so very remarkable in that, nor

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:55.660
did Alice think it so very much out of the way to hear the rabbit say to itself, Oh dear,

00:00:55.660 --> 00:01:00.780
I shall be late. When she thought it over afterwards, it occurred to her that she ought

00:01:00.780 --> 00:01:05.140
to have wondered at this, but at the time it all seemed quite natural. But when the

00:01:05.140 --> 00:01:10.480
rabbit actually took a watch out of its waistcoat pocket and looked at it, and then hurried

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:15.360
on, Alice started to her feet, for it flashed across her mind that she had never before

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:19.680
seen a rabbit with either a waistcoat pocket or a watch to take out of it, and burning

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:25.020
with curiosity, she ran across the field after it, and fortunately was just in time to see

00:01:25.020 --> 00:01:29.760
it pop down a large rabbit hole under the hedge. In another moment, down went Alice

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:35.020
after it, never once considering how in the world she was to get out again. The rabbit

00:01:35.020 --> 00:01:39.540
hole went straight on like a tunnel for some way, and then dipped suddenly down, so suddenly

00:01:39.540 --> 00:01:43.400
that Alice had not a moment to think about stopping herself before she found herself

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:48.860
falling down a very deep well. Either the well was very deep, or she fell very slowly,

00:01:49.220 --> 00:01:53.480
for she had plenty of time as she went down to look about her and to wonder what was going

00:01:53.480 --> 00:01:58.340
to happen next. First, she tried to look down and make out what she was coming to,

00:01:58.580 --> 00:02:03.240
but it was too dark to see anything. Then she looked at the sides of the well, and noticed

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:08.480
that they were filled with cupboards and bookshelves. Here and there, she saw maps and pictures

00:02:08.480 --> 00:02:13.680
hung upon pegs. She took down a jar from one of the shelves as she passed. It was labelled

00:02:13.680 --> 00:02:18.680
orange marmalade, but to her great disappointment it was empty. She did not like to drop the

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:22.520
jar for fear of killing somebody, so she managed to put it into one of the cupboards as she

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:23.380
fell past it.

00:02:24.660 --> 00:02:29.060
Well, thought Alice to herself, after such a fall as this, I shall think nothing of tumbling

00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:34.160
downstairs. How brave they'll all think me at home. Why, I wouldn't say anything about

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:37.900
it even if I fell off the top of a house, which was very likely true.

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:45.720
Down, down, down. Would the fall never come to an end? I wonder how many miles I've fallen

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:50.400
by this time, she said aloud. I must be getting somewhere near the centre of the earth. Let

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:54.660
me see, that would be four thousand miles down, I think. For you see, Alice had learnt

00:02:54.660 --> 00:02:58.220
several things of this sort in her lessons in the schoolroom, and though this was not

00:02:58.220 --> 00:03:02.000
a very good opportunity for showing off her knowledge as there was no one to listen to

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.500
her, still it was good practice to say it over. Yes, that's about the right distance,

00:03:06.820 --> 00:03:12.080
but then I wonder what latitude or longitude I've got to. Alice had no idea what latitude

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:17.520
was, or longitude either, but thought they were nice grand words to say. Presently she

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:22.980
began again, I wonder if I shall fall right through the earth. How funny it'll seem to

00:03:22.980 --> 00:03:27.840
come out among the people that walk with their heads downward. The antipathies, I think.

00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:32.060
She was rather glad there was no one listening this time, as it didn't sound at all the

00:03:32.060 --> 00:03:37.080
right word. But I shall have to ask them what the name of the country is, you know. Please,

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:43.000
ma'am, is this New Zealand or Australia? And she tried to curtsy as she spoke. Fancy curtsying

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.260
as you're falling through the air. Do you think you could manage it? And what an ignorant

00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:52.040
little girl she'll think me for asking. No, it'll never do to ask. Perhaps I shall see

00:03:52.040 --> 00:03:57.860
it written up somewhere. Down, down, down. There was nothing else to do, so Alice soon

00:03:57.860 --> 00:04:04.060
began talking again. Dinah will miss me very much tonight, I should think. Dinah was the

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:09.300
cat. I hope they'll remember her saucer of milk at tea time. Dinah, my dear, I wish you

00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:13.100
were down here with me. There are no mice in the air, I'm afraid, but you might catch

00:04:13.100 --> 00:04:19.580
And that's very like a mouse, you know. But do cats eat bats, I wonder? And here Alice

00:04:19.580 --> 00:04:24.600
began to get rather sleepy and went on saying to herself in a dreamy sort of way, do cats

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:30.320
eat bats? Do cats eat bats? And sometimes, do bats eat cats? For you see, as she couldn't

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:35.100
answer either question, it didn't much matter which way she put it. She felt that she was

00:04:35.100 --> 00:04:39.420
dozing off and had just begun to dream that she was walking hand in hand with Dinah and

00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:45.360
saying to her very earnestly, now Dinah, tell me the truth, did you ever eat a bat? When

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:50.680
suddenly thump, thump, down she came upon a heap of sticks and dry leaves and the fall

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:56.600
was over. Alice was not a bit hurt and she jumped up on her feet in a moment. She looked

00:04:56.600 --> 00:05:01.340
up but it was all dark overhead. Before her was another long passage and the white rabbit

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:06.300
was still in sight hurrying down it. There was not a moment to be lost. Away went Alice

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:10.600
like the wind and was just in time to hear it say as it turned a corner, oh my ears

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:14.520
and whiskers, how late it's getting. She was close behind it when she turned the corner

00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:19.580
but the rabbit was no longer to be seen. She found herself in a long low hall which was

00:05:19.580 --> 00:05:24.000
lit up by a row of lamps hanging from the roof. There were doors all around the hall

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.140
but they were all locked and when Alice had been all the way down one side and up the

00:05:28.140 --> 00:05:32.920
other trying every door, she walked sadly down the middle wondering how she was ever

00:05:32.920 --> 00:05:38.720
to get out again. Suddenly she came upon a little three legged table all made of solid

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:44.140
glass. There was nothing on it except a tiny golden key and Alice's first thought was

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:48.440
that it might belong to one of the doors of the hall. But alas, either the locks were

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:53.380
too large or the key was too small but at any rate it would not open any of them. However,

00:05:53.480 --> 00:05:58.440
on the second time round she came upon a low curtain she had not noticed before and behind

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:03.360
it was a little door about 15 inches high. She tried the little golden key in the lock

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:09.380
and to her great delight it fitted. Alice opened the door and found it led into a small

00:06:09.380 --> 00:06:15.080
passage not much larger than a rat hole. She knelt down and looked along the passage into

00:06:15.080 --> 00:06:20.360
the loveliest garden you ever saw. How she longed to get out of that dark hall and wander

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:25.160
about among those beds of bright flowers and those cool fountains but she could not even

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:29.680
get her head through the doorway. And even if my head would go through thought poor Alice

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:34.180
it would be of very little use without my shoulders. Oh, how I wish I could shut up

00:06:34.180 --> 00:06:40.200
like a telescope. I think I could if I only know how to begin. For you see so many out

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:44.140
of the way things had happened lately that Alice had begun to think that very few things

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:48.940
indeed were really impossible. There seemed to be no use in waiting by the little door

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:53.580
so she went back to the table half hoping she might find another key on it or at any

00:06:53.580 --> 00:06:58.880
a book of rules for shutting people up like telescopes. This time she found a little bottle

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:04.180
on it which certainly was not here before said Alice. Around the neck of the bottle

00:07:04.180 --> 00:07:08.920
was a paper label with the words drink me beautifully printed on it in large letters.

00:07:09.280 --> 00:07:13.580
It was all very well to say drink me but the wise little Alice was not going to do that

00:07:13.580 --> 00:07:19.160
in a hurry. No, I'll look first she said and see whether it's marked poison or not for

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:23.300
she had read several nice little histories about children who'd gotten burnt and eaten

00:07:23.300 --> 00:07:28.000
up by wild beasts and other unpleasant things all because they would not remember the simple

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.800
rules their friends had taught them such as that a red hot poker will burn you if you

00:07:32.800 --> 00:07:36.720
hold it too long and that if you cut your finger very deeply with a knife it usually

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:41.120
bleeds and she had never forgotten that if you drink much from a bottle marked poison

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:46.740
it's almost certain to disagree with you sooner or later. However this bottle was not marked

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:52.840
poison so Alice ventured to taste it and finding it very nice it had in fact a sort of mixed

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:58.440
flavor of cherry tart, custard, pineapple, roast turkey, toffee and hot buttered toast.

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:06.140
She very soon finished it off. What a curious feeling said Alice. I must be shutting up

00:08:06.140 --> 00:08:11.660
like a telescope and so it was indeed. She was now only 10 inches high and her face brightened

00:08:11.660 --> 00:08:15.220
up at the thought that she was now the right size for going through the little door into

00:08:15.220 --> 00:08:20.140
that lovely garden. First however she waited for a few minutes to see if she was going

00:08:20.140 --> 00:08:25.340
to shrink any further. She felt a little nervous about this. For it might end you know, said

00:08:25.340 --> 00:08:30.360
Alice to herself, in my going out altogether like a candle. I wonder what I should be like

00:08:30.360 --> 00:08:35.040
then? And she tried to fancy what the flame of a candle is like after the candle is blown

00:08:35.040 --> 00:08:40.060
out for she could not remember having ever seen such a thing. After a while finding that

00:08:40.060 --> 00:08:44.860
nothing more happened she decided on going into the garden at once. But alas for poor

00:08:44.860 --> 00:08:49.540
Alice when she got to the door she found she'd forgotten the little golden key and when she

00:08:49.540 --> 00:08:54.140
went back to the table for it she found she could not possibly reach it. She could see

00:08:54.140 --> 00:08:58.340
it quite plainly through the glass and she tried her best to climb up one of the legs

00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:03.520
of the table but it was too slippery and when she had tired herself out with trying the

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:09.660
poor little thing sat down and cried. Come there's no use crying like that said Alice

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:15.200
to herself rather sharply. I advise you to leave off this minute. She generally gave

00:09:15.660 --> 00:09:20.740
good advice though she very seldom followed it and sometimes she scolded herself so severely

00:09:20.740 --> 00:09:25.060
as to bring tears into her eyes. She once remembered trying to box her own ears for

00:09:25.060 --> 00:09:29.320
having cheated herself in a game of croquet she was playing against herself. For this

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:34.860
curious child was fond of pretending to be two people. But it's no use now thought poor

00:09:34.860 --> 00:09:39.280
Alice to pretend to be two people why there's hardly enough of me to make one respectable

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:44.420
person. Soon her eye fell on a little glass box that was lying under the table. She opened

00:09:44.420 --> 00:09:50.220
it and found in it a very small cake on which the words eat me were beautifully marked in

00:09:50.220 --> 00:09:55.800
currents. Well I'll eat it said Alice and if it makes me grow larger I can reach the

00:09:55.800 --> 00:10:00.480
key and if it makes me grow smaller I can creep under the door so either way I'll get

00:10:00.480 --> 00:10:06.220
into the garden and I don't care which happens. She ate a little bit and said anxiously to

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:11.920
herself which way which way holding her hand on the top of her head to feel which way it

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:16.820
was growing and she was quite surprised to find that she remained the same size. To be

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:21.100
sure this generally happens when one eats cake but Alice had gotten so much into the

00:10:21.100 --> 00:10:25.300
way of expecting nothing but out of the way things to happen that it seemed quite dull

00:10:25.300 --> 00:10:30.960
and stupid for life to go on in the common way. So she set to work and very soon finished

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:39.940
off the cake.

00:10:56.004 --> 00:10:56.564
II.

00:10:58.204 --> 00:10:59.544
THE POOL OF TEARS

00:11:01.204 --> 00:11:03.344
Curiouser and curiouser cried Alice.

00:11:03.844 --> 00:11:08.444
She was so much surprised that for the moment she quite forgot how to speak good English.

00:11:09.004 --> 00:11:12.864
Now I'm opening out like their largest telescope that ever was.

00:11:13.164 --> 00:11:14.084
Good-bye, feet!

00:11:14.584 --> 00:11:18.824
For when she looked down at her feet, they seemed to be almost out of sight.

00:11:19.124 --> 00:11:20.864
They were getting so far off.

00:11:21.544 --> 00:11:23.084
Oh, my poor little feet!

00:11:23.384 --> 00:11:26.584
I wonder who will put on your shoes and stockings for you now, dears.

00:11:26.864 --> 00:11:29.164
I'm sure I shan't be able to.

00:11:29.484 --> 00:11:34.064
I shall be a great deal too far off to trouble myself about you.

00:11:34.764 --> 00:11:36.844
You must manage the best you can.

00:11:36.844 --> 00:11:42.624
But I must be kind to them, thought Alice, or perhaps they won't walk the way I want

00:11:42.624 --> 00:11:43.204
to go.

00:11:43.444 --> 00:11:44.164
Let me see.

00:11:44.284 --> 00:11:46.464
I'll give them a new pair of boots every Christmas.

00:11:47.684 --> 00:11:51.024
And she went on planning to herself how she should manage it.

00:11:51.284 --> 00:11:53.284
They must go by carrier, she thought.

00:11:53.644 --> 00:11:58.644
And how funny I'll seem, sending presents to one's own feet, and how odd the directions

00:11:58.644 --> 00:11:59.284
will look.

00:11:59.704 --> 00:12:05.344
Alice's right foot a squire, hearth rug near the fender with Alice's love.

00:12:05.344 --> 00:12:07.844
Oh dear, what nonsense I'm talking.

00:12:08.784 --> 00:12:12.044
Just then her head struck against the roof of the hall.

00:12:12.464 --> 00:12:17.544
In fact, she was now more than nine feet high, and she at once took up the little golden

00:12:17.544 --> 00:12:19.804
key and hurried off to the garden door.

00:12:20.844 --> 00:12:21.704
Poor Alice.

00:12:22.244 --> 00:12:28.844
It was as much as she could do lying down on one side to look through into the garden

00:12:28.844 --> 00:12:32.704
with one eye, but to get through was more hopeless than ever.

00:12:32.704 --> 00:12:35.344
She sat down and began to cry again.

00:12:36.044 --> 00:12:38.564
You ought to be ashamed of yourself, said Alice.

00:12:38.944 --> 00:12:42.424
A great girl like you, she might well say this.

00:12:42.804 --> 00:12:47.484
To go on crying in this way, stop this moment, I tell you.

00:12:47.744 --> 00:12:52.764
But she went on all the same, shedding gallons of tears, until there was a large pool all

00:12:52.764 --> 00:12:56.884
around her, about four inches deep, and reaching half down the hall.

00:12:57.784 --> 00:13:02.564
After a time she heard a little pattering of feet in the distance, and she hastily dried

00:13:02.564 --> 00:13:03.924
her eyes to see what was coming.

00:13:04.624 --> 00:13:09.324
It was the white rabbit returning, splendidly dressed with a pair of white kid gloves in

00:13:09.324 --> 00:13:11.524
one hand, and a large fan in the other.

00:13:11.964 --> 00:13:16.244
He came trotting along in a great hurry, muttering to himself as he came.

00:13:16.764 --> 00:13:19.004
Oh, the Duchess, the Duchess.

00:13:19.244 --> 00:13:22.264
Oh, won't she be savage if I've kept her waiting.

00:13:22.964 --> 00:13:26.584
Alice felt so desperate that she was ready to ask help of anyone.

00:13:27.044 --> 00:13:30.464
So when the rabbit came near her she began in a low timid voice.

00:13:30.944 --> 00:13:32.304
If you please, sir.

00:13:32.744 --> 00:13:37.324
The rabbit started violently, dropped the white kid gloves and the fan, and scurried

00:13:37.324 --> 00:13:40.664
away into the darkness, as hard as he could go.

00:13:41.824 --> 00:13:47.464
Alice took up the fan and gloves, and as the hall was very hot, she kept fanning herself

00:13:47.464 --> 00:13:49.704
all the time she went on talking.

00:13:50.184 --> 00:13:56.064
Dear, dear, how queer everything is today, and yesterday things went on just as usual.

00:13:56.484 --> 00:13:58.884
I wonder if I've been changed in the night.

00:13:59.164 --> 00:14:02.444
Let me think, was I the same when I got up this morning?

00:14:02.884 --> 00:14:05.904
I almost think I can remember feeling a little different.

00:14:06.304 --> 00:14:10.924
But if I'm not the same, the next question is, who in the world am I?

00:14:11.344 --> 00:14:13.364
Ah, that's the great puzzle.

00:14:13.704 --> 00:14:18.444
And she began thinking over all the children that she knew that were of the same age as

00:14:18.444 --> 00:14:21.484
herself, to see if she could have been changed for any of them.

00:14:22.104 --> 00:14:28.004
I'm sure I'm not Ada, she said, for her hair goes in such long ringlets, and mine doesn't

00:14:28.004 --> 00:14:29.604
go in ringlets at all.

00:14:30.004 --> 00:14:33.964
And I'm sure I can't be Mabel, for I know all sorts of things.

00:14:34.484 --> 00:14:41.124
And she, oh, she knows such a very little, besides she, she, and I'm I.

00:14:41.324 --> 00:14:44.124
And oh dear, how puzzling it all is.

00:14:44.564 --> 00:14:47.984
I'll try if I know all the things I used to know.

00:14:48.464 --> 00:14:55.544
Let me see, four times five is twelve, and four times six is thirteen, and four times

00:14:55.544 --> 00:15:00.584
seven is, oh dear, I shall never get to twenty at that rate.

00:15:01.204 --> 00:15:03.924
However, the multiplication table doesn't signify.

00:15:04.364 --> 00:15:05.684
Let's try geography.

00:15:06.624 --> 00:15:13.024
London is the capital of Paris, and Paris is the capital of Rome, and Rome, no, that's

00:15:13.024 --> 00:15:14.584
all wrong, I'm certain.

00:15:14.964 --> 00:15:16.704
I must have been changed for Mabel.

00:15:17.164 --> 00:15:19.484
I'll try and say, how doth the little?

00:15:19.724 --> 00:15:24.764
And she crossed her hands on her lap, as if she were saying lessons, and began repeated.

00:15:24.764 --> 00:15:29.284
But her voice sounded hoarse and strange, and the words did not come the same as they

00:15:29.284 --> 00:15:30.004
used to.

00:15:30.644 --> 00:15:37.244
How doth the little crocodile improve his shining tail, and pour the waters of the Nile

00:15:37.244 --> 00:15:39.264
on every golden scale?

00:15:39.624 --> 00:15:45.244
How cheerfully he seems to grin, how neatly spread his claws, and welcome little fishes

00:15:45.244 --> 00:15:47.444
in with gently smiling jaws.

00:15:48.244 --> 00:15:53.044
I'm sure those are not the right words, said poor Alice, and her eyes filled with tears

00:15:53.044 --> 00:15:54.584
as she went on.

00:15:54.784 --> 00:15:59.864
I must be Mabel after all, and I shall have to go and live in that pokey little house,

00:16:00.244 --> 00:16:05.004
and have next to no toys to play with, and oh, ever so many lessons to learn.

00:16:05.424 --> 00:16:07.244
No, I've made up my mind about it.

00:16:07.404 --> 00:16:09.824
If I'm Mabel, I'll stay down here.

00:16:10.304 --> 00:16:15.124
It'll be no use their putting their heads down and saying, come up again dear.

00:16:15.484 --> 00:16:18.924
I shall only look up and say, who am I then?

00:16:18.924 --> 00:16:23.804
Tell me that first, and then, if I like being that person, I'll come up.

00:16:24.024 --> 00:16:27.304
If not, I'll stay down here, till I'm somebody else.

00:16:27.724 --> 00:16:33.764
But oh dear, cried Alice, with a sudden burst of tears, I do wish they would put their heads

00:16:33.764 --> 00:16:34.124
down.

00:16:34.224 --> 00:16:37.444
I am so very tired of being all alone here.

00:16:37.984 --> 00:16:42.984
As she said this, she looked down at her hands, and was surprised to see that she had put

00:16:42.984 --> 00:16:46.824
on one of the rabbit's little white kid gloves while she was talking.

00:16:46.824 --> 00:16:49.084
How can I have done that?

00:16:49.084 --> 00:16:49.584
She thought.

00:16:49.824 --> 00:16:51.604
I must be growing small again.

00:16:52.084 --> 00:16:56.824
She got up and went to the table to measure herself by it, and found that, as nearly as

00:16:56.824 --> 00:17:01.784
she could guess, she was now about two feet high, and was going on shrinking rapidly.

00:17:02.224 --> 00:17:06.964
She soon found out that the cause of this was the fan that she was holding, and she

00:17:06.964 --> 00:17:10.804
dropped it hastily, just in time to avoid shrinking away altogether.

00:17:12.144 --> 00:17:17.644
That was a narrow escape, said Alice, a good deal frightened at the sudden change, but

00:17:17.644 --> 00:17:20.564
very glad to find herself still in existence.

00:17:21.084 --> 00:17:26.384
And now for the garden, and she ran with all speed back to the little door, but alas, the

00:17:26.384 --> 00:17:30.764
door was shut again, and the little golden key was lying on the glass table as before.

00:17:31.344 --> 00:17:37.484
And things are worse than ever, thought the poor child, for I never was so small as this

00:17:37.484 --> 00:17:38.444
before, never.

00:17:38.444 --> 00:17:42.244
And I declare, it's too bad that it is.

00:17:42.804 --> 00:17:46.524
As she said these words, her foot slipped, and in another moment, splash!

00:17:46.924 --> 00:17:48.844
She was up to her chin in salt water.

00:17:49.384 --> 00:17:52.584
Her first idea was that she had somehow fallen into the sea.

00:17:53.084 --> 00:17:56.904
And in that case, I can go back by railway, she said to herself.

00:17:57.544 --> 00:18:02.204
Alice had been to the seaside once in her life, and it could come to the general conclusion

00:18:02.204 --> 00:18:07.504
that wherever you go on the English coast, you find a number of bathing machines in the

00:18:07.504 --> 00:18:12.564
sea, some children digging in the sand with wooden spades, then a row of lodging houses

00:18:12.564 --> 00:18:14.504
and behind them a railway station.

00:18:15.104 --> 00:18:19.724
However, she soon made out that she was in a pool of tears, which she had wept when she

00:18:19.724 --> 00:18:21.024
was nine feet high.

00:18:21.564 --> 00:18:27.124
I wish I hadn't cried so much, said Alice, as she swam about trying to find her way out.

00:18:27.564 --> 00:18:32.104
I shall be punished for it now, I suppose, by being drowned in my own tears.

00:18:32.384 --> 00:18:35.324
That will be a queer thing, to be sure.

00:18:35.324 --> 00:18:37.624
However, everything is queer today.

00:18:38.584 --> 00:18:43.804
Just then she heard something splash about in the pool a little way off, and she swam

00:18:43.804 --> 00:18:45.544
nearer to make out what it was.

00:18:46.064 --> 00:18:51.564
At first she thought it must be a walrus or a papotamus, but then she remembered how small

00:18:51.564 --> 00:18:56.524
she was now, and she soon made out that it was only a mouse that had slipped in like

00:18:56.524 --> 00:18:57.144
herself.

00:18:58.244 --> 00:19:02.244
Would it be of any use now, thought Alice, to speak to this mouse?

00:19:02.244 --> 00:19:09.024
Everything is so out of the way down here that I should think very likely it can talk.

00:19:09.144 --> 00:19:11.484
At any rate, there's no harm in trying.

00:19:12.024 --> 00:19:15.924
So she began, Oh mouse, do you know the way out of this pool?

00:19:16.264 --> 00:19:19.224
I am very tired of swimming about here, oh mouse.

00:19:21.204 --> 00:19:24.104
Alice thought this must be the right way of speaking to a mouse.

00:19:24.604 --> 00:19:29.144
She had never done such a thing before, but she remembered having seen her brother's Latin

00:19:29.144 --> 00:19:33.764
grammar, a mouse of a mouse, to a mouse a mouse, oh mouse.

00:19:34.524 --> 00:19:39.964
The mouse looked at her rather inquisitively, and seemed to her to wink with one of its

00:19:39.964 --> 00:19:41.984
little eyes, but it said nothing.

00:19:43.084 --> 00:19:48.844
Perhaps it doesn't understand English, thought Alice, I dare say it's a French mouse, come

00:19:48.844 --> 00:19:50.744
over with William the Conqueror.

00:19:50.984 --> 00:19:56.284
With all her knowledge of history, Alice had no clear notion how long ago anything had

00:19:56.284 --> 00:19:56.724
happened.

00:19:57.204 --> 00:20:00.324
So she began again, Où est-ce, mon chien?

00:20:01.264 --> 00:20:03.884
Which was the first sentence in her French lesson book.

00:20:04.364 --> 00:20:08.304
The mouse gave a sudden leap out of the water, and seemed to quiver all over with fright.

00:20:08.824 --> 00:20:13.424
Oh, I beg your pardon, cried Alice hastily, afraid that she had hurt the poor animal's

00:20:13.424 --> 00:20:13.844
feelings.

00:20:14.264 --> 00:20:16.564
I quite forgot, you don't like cats.

00:20:17.604 --> 00:20:20.844
Not like cats, cried the mouse in a shrill, passionate voice.

00:20:21.144 --> 00:20:23.404
Would you like cats if you were me?

00:20:23.944 --> 00:20:28.784
Well, perhaps not, said Alice in a soothing tone, don't be angry about it.

00:20:29.004 --> 00:20:33.764
And yet, I wish I could show you our cat, Dinah, I think you'd take a fancy to cats

00:20:33.764 --> 00:20:35.124
if you could only see her.

00:20:35.484 --> 00:20:41.004
She's such a dear, quiet thing, Alice went on half to herself, as she swam lazily about

00:20:41.004 --> 00:20:41.664
in the pool.

00:20:42.084 --> 00:20:46.924
And she sits purring so nicely by the fire, licking her paws and washing her face, and

00:20:46.924 --> 00:20:51.724
she is such a nice, soft thing to nurse, and she's such a capital one for catching mice,

00:20:51.724 --> 00:20:56.564
Oh, I beg your pardon, cried Alice again, for this time the mouse was bristling all

00:20:56.564 --> 00:20:59.764
over, and she felt certain it must be really offended.

00:21:00.144 --> 00:21:03.124
We won't talk about her any more if you'd rather not.

00:21:03.644 --> 00:21:09.444
We indeed, cried the mouse, who was trembling down to the end of his tail, as if I would

00:21:09.444 --> 00:21:10.984
talk on such a subject.

00:21:11.364 --> 00:21:16.344
Our family always hated cats, nasty, low, vulgar things.

00:21:16.624 --> 00:21:19.064
Don't let me hear the name again.

00:21:19.064 --> 00:21:24.964
I won't indeed, said Alice, in a great hurry to change the subject of conversation.

00:21:25.424 --> 00:21:28.804
And you, are you fond of, of dogs?

00:21:29.704 --> 00:21:33.124
The mouse did not answer, so Alice went on eagerly.

00:21:33.344 --> 00:21:37.044
There is such a nice little dog near our house, I should like to show you.

00:21:37.344 --> 00:21:42.144
A little bright-eyed terrier, you know, with, oh, such long, curly brown hair, and it'll

00:21:42.144 --> 00:21:46.444
fetch things when you throw them, and it'll sit up and beg for its dinner, and all sorts

00:21:46.444 --> 00:21:46.884
of things.

00:21:46.884 --> 00:21:50.624
I can't remember half of them, and it belongs to a farmer, you know.

00:21:50.864 --> 00:21:54.304
And he says it's so useful, it's worth a hundred pounds.

00:21:54.744 --> 00:22:00.944
He says it kills all the rats, and, oh dear, cried Alice in a sorrowful tone, I'm afraid

00:22:00.944 --> 00:22:04.964
I'll be offended again, for the mouse was swimming away from her as hard as it could

00:22:04.964 --> 00:22:07.824
go and making quite a commotion in the pool as it went.

00:22:09.384 --> 00:22:14.304
So she called softly after it, Mouse dear, do come back again, and I won't talk about

00:22:14.304 --> 00:22:17.304
cats or dogs either, if you don't like them.

00:22:17.704 --> 00:22:21.644
When the mouse heard this, it turned round and swam slowly back to her.

00:22:21.964 --> 00:22:27.444
Its face was quite pale, with passion, Alice thought, and it said in a low trembling voice,

00:22:28.044 --> 00:22:33.384
Let us get to the shore, and then I'll tell you my history, and you'll understand why

00:22:33.384 --> 00:22:35.804
it is that I hate cats and dogs.

00:22:36.504 --> 00:22:40.984
It was high time to go, for the pool was getting quite crowded with birds and animals that

00:22:40.984 --> 00:22:42.064
had fallen into it.

00:22:42.064 --> 00:22:48.024
There was a duck, and a dodo, a lorry, and an eaglet, and several other curious creatures.

00:22:48.724 --> 00:22:51.724
Alice led the way, and the whole party swam to the shore.

00:23:32.049 --> 00:23:38.929
A Caucus Race and a Long Tale.

00:23:41.169 --> 00:23:48.229
They were indeed a queer-looking party that assembled on the bank.

00:23:49.209 --> 00:23:56.569
The birds with draggled feathers, the animals with their fur clinging close to them,

00:23:57.049 --> 00:24:02.969
and all dripping wet, cross, and uncomfortable.

00:24:03.969 --> 00:24:09.029
The first question, of course, was how to get dry again.

00:24:09.649 --> 00:24:18.489
They had a consultation about this, and after a few minutes it seemed quite natural to Alice

00:24:18.489 --> 00:24:27.209
to find herself talking familiarly with them as if she had known them all her life.

00:24:27.209 --> 00:24:36.209
Indeed, she had quite a long argument with the lorry, who at last turned sulky,

00:24:37.269 --> 00:24:43.809
and would only say, I am older than you and must know better.

00:24:44.889 --> 00:24:51.709
And this Alice would not allow without knowing how old it was.

00:24:51.709 --> 00:25:01.389
And, as the lorry positively refused to tell its age, there was no more to be said.

00:25:03.829 --> 00:25:10.829
At last the mouse, who seemed to be a person of authority among them, called out,

00:25:11.689 --> 00:25:19.049
sit down, all of you, and listen to me. I'll soon make you dry enough.

00:25:19.049 --> 00:25:27.489
They all sat down at once in a large ring with the mouse in the middle.

00:25:28.689 --> 00:25:38.129
Alice kept her eyes anxiously fixed on it, for she felt sure she would catch a bad cold

00:25:38.129 --> 00:25:42.049
if she did not get dry very soon.

00:25:43.349 --> 00:25:49.369
Ahem, said the mouse with an important air, are you all ready?

00:25:50.589 --> 00:25:57.329
This is the driest thing I know. Silence all around, if you please.

00:25:59.089 --> 00:26:07.709
William the Conqueror, whose cause was favored by the Pope, was soon submitted to by the English,

00:26:07.709 --> 00:26:16.449
who wanted leaders, and had been of late much accustomed to usurpation and conquest.

00:26:17.729 --> 00:26:23.149
Edmund and Moorcar, the earls of Mercia and North Umbria.

00:26:24.889 --> 00:26:34.009
Ug! said the lorry with a shiver. I beg your pardon, said the mouse, frowning, but very politely.

00:26:34.009 --> 00:26:40.529
Did you speak? Not I, said the lorry hastily.

00:26:42.189 --> 00:26:47.389
I thought you did, said the mouse. I proceed.

00:26:49.649 --> 00:26:56.689
Edmund and Moorcar, the earls of Mercia and North Umbria, declared for him,

00:26:56.689 --> 00:27:05.429
and even Stegand, the Patriotic Archbishop of Canterbury, found it advisable.

00:27:06.929 --> 00:27:09.289
Found what, said the duck?

00:27:10.709 --> 00:27:18.429
Found it, the mouse replied rather crossly. Of course you know what it means.

00:27:19.429 --> 00:27:27.109
I know what it means well enough when I find a thing, said the duck.

00:27:28.329 --> 00:27:37.349
It's generally a frog or a worm. The question is, what did the archbishop find?

00:27:38.809 --> 00:27:46.489
The mouse did not notice this question, but hurriedly went on.

00:27:47.669 --> 00:27:56.789
Found it advisable to go with Edgar Etheling to meet William and offer him the crown.

00:27:57.829 --> 00:28:05.089
William's conduct was at first moderate, but the insolence of his Normans.

00:28:06.069 --> 00:28:13.949
How are you getting on now, my dear? It continued, turning to Alice as it spoke.

00:28:15.029 --> 00:28:23.669
As wet as ever, said Alice in a melancholy tone, it doesn't seem to dry me at all.

00:28:26.269 --> 00:28:35.789
In that case, said the dodo solemnly, rising to its feet, I move that the meeting adjourn

00:28:35.789 --> 00:28:40.089
for the immediate adoption of more energetic remedies.

00:28:41.889 --> 00:28:49.049
Speak English, said the eaglet. I don't know the meaning of half those long words.

00:28:49.609 --> 00:28:54.529
And what's more, I don't believe you do either.

00:28:55.489 --> 00:28:59.169
And the eaglet bent down its head to hide a smile.

00:29:00.689 --> 00:29:04.169
Some of the other birds tittered audibly.

00:29:05.309 --> 00:29:12.629
What I was going to say, said the dodo in an offended tone,

00:29:13.669 --> 00:29:20.569
was that the best thing is to get us dry would be a caucus race.

00:29:22.389 --> 00:29:30.669
What is a caucus race, said Alice? Not that she wanted much to know,

00:29:30.669 --> 00:29:38.609
but the dodo had paused as if it thought that somebody ought to speak,

00:29:39.809 --> 00:29:44.209
and no one else seemed inclined to say anything.

00:29:45.849 --> 00:29:52.909
Why, said the dodo, the best way to explain it is to do it.

00:29:54.009 --> 00:29:59.009
And you might like to try the thing yourself some winter day.

00:29:59.009 --> 00:30:04.329
I will tell you how the dodo managed it.

00:30:05.249 --> 00:30:10.989
First, it marked out a race course in a sort of circle.

00:30:12.189 --> 00:30:15.509
The exact shape doesn't matter, it said.

00:30:16.649 --> 00:30:23.889
And then all the party were placed along the course, here and there.

00:30:24.709 --> 00:30:29.969
There was no one, two, three, and away,

00:30:31.029 --> 00:30:36.609
but they began running when they liked, and left off when they liked,

00:30:37.789 --> 00:30:42.209
so that it was not easy to know when the race was over.

00:30:43.029 --> 00:30:49.809
However, when they had been running half an hour or so, and were quite dry again,

00:30:49.809 --> 00:30:54.589
the dodo suddenly called out, the race is over!

00:30:55.609 --> 00:31:01.289
And they all crowded round it, panting and asking, but who has won?

00:31:02.929 --> 00:31:08.149
This question the dodo could not answer without a great deal of thought,

00:31:08.909 --> 00:31:15.809
and it sat for a long time with one finger pressed upon its forehead.

00:31:16.699 --> 00:31:22.349
The position in which you usually see Shakespeare in the pictures of him,

00:31:22.749 --> 00:31:25.129
while the rest waited in silence.

00:31:26.089 --> 00:31:33.869
At last the dodo said, everybody has won, and all must have prizes.

00:31:35.929 --> 00:31:38.489
But who is to give the prizes?

00:31:39.269 --> 00:31:42.289
Quite a chorus of voices asked.

00:31:42.289 --> 00:31:50.149
Why, she, of course, said the dodo, pointing to Alice with one finger,

00:31:50.949 --> 00:31:58.169
and the whole party at once crowded round her, calling out in a confused way,

00:31:58.709 --> 00:32:00.409
prizes, prizes!

00:32:02.149 --> 00:32:10.569
Alice had no idea what to do, and in despair she put her hand in her pocket,

00:32:10.569 --> 00:32:15.029
and pulled out a box of comfits.

00:32:15.609 --> 00:32:22.869
Luckily the salt water had not got into it, and handed them round as prizes.

00:32:23.929 --> 00:32:29.069
There was exactly one apiece all round.

00:32:31.789 --> 00:32:37.169
But she must have a prize herself, you know, said the mouse.

00:32:37.169 --> 00:32:42.229
Of course the dodo replied very gravely.

00:32:43.389 --> 00:32:45.429
What else have you got in your pocket?

00:32:45.729 --> 00:32:48.069
He went on, turning to Alice.

00:32:49.449 --> 00:32:52.589
Only a thimble, said Alice sadly.

00:32:53.729 --> 00:32:56.309
Hand it over here, said the dodo.

00:32:57.929 --> 00:33:05.629
Then they all crowded round her once more, while the dodo solemnly presented

00:33:05.629 --> 00:33:12.649
the thimble, saying, We beg your acceptance of this elegant thimble.

00:33:13.129 --> 00:33:20.389
And, when it had finished this short speech, they all cheered.

00:33:22.349 --> 00:33:28.669
Alice thought the whole thing very absurd, but they all looked so grave

00:33:28.669 --> 00:33:35.449
that she did not dare to laugh, and as she could not think of anything to say,

00:33:36.409 --> 00:33:43.289
she simply bowed and took the thimble, looking as solemn as she could.

00:33:44.869 --> 00:33:47.449
The next thing was to eat the comfits.

00:33:48.509 --> 00:33:54.709
This caused some noise and confusion, as the large birds complained

00:33:54.709 --> 00:34:00.249
that they could not taste theirs, and the small ones choked

00:34:00.249 --> 00:34:03.189
and had to be petted on the back.

00:34:04.109 --> 00:34:10.049
However, it was over at last, and they sat down again in a ring

00:34:10.709 --> 00:34:14.229
and begged the mouse to tell them something more.

00:34:16.009 --> 00:34:21.549
You promised to tell me your history, you know, said Alice,

00:34:21.549 --> 00:34:28.429
and why it is you hate C and D, she added in a whisper,

00:34:29.369 --> 00:34:32.789
half afraid that it would be offended again.

00:34:34.449 --> 00:34:42.149
Mine is a long and a sad tale, said the mouse, turning to Alice and sighing.

00:34:43.089 --> 00:34:51.489
It is a long tale, certainly, said Alice, looking down with wonder at the mouse's tale,

00:34:52.489 --> 00:34:55.289
but why do you call it sad?

00:34:56.429 --> 00:35:01.629
And she kept on puzzling about it while the mouse was speaking,

00:35:02.369 --> 00:35:07.729
so that her idea of the tale was something like this.

00:35:08.729 --> 00:35:16.189
Here the words are written on the page one to four on a line,

00:35:17.049 --> 00:35:23.009
and the lines are offset, so they snake down the page in a wavy fashion.

00:35:24.109 --> 00:35:25.329
And here's what they say.

00:35:27.369 --> 00:35:32.649
Fury said to a mouse that he met in the house,

00:35:33.549 --> 00:35:39.769
Let us both go to law, I will prosecute you.

00:35:40.609 --> 00:35:45.869
Come, I'll take no denial, we must have a trial,

00:35:46.769 --> 00:35:51.129
for really this morning I've nothing to do.

00:35:52.569 --> 00:35:58.109
Said the mouse to the cur, such a trial, dear sir,

00:35:58.109 --> 00:36:03.949
with no jury or judge would be wasting our breath.

00:36:05.989 --> 00:36:10.849
I'll be judge, I'll be jury, said cunning old fury,

00:36:11.429 --> 00:36:17.289
I'll try the whole cause and condemn you to death.

00:36:18.889 --> 00:36:21.549
And there's where the snaky text ends.

00:36:21.549 --> 00:36:22.749
Continuing.

00:36:24.689 --> 00:36:28.469
You are not attending, said the mouse to Alice severely.

00:36:29.369 --> 00:36:31.109
What are you thinking of?

00:36:32.389 --> 00:36:36.189
I beg your pardon, said Alice, very humbly.

00:36:37.789 --> 00:36:42.149
You had got to the fifth bend, I think.

00:36:43.429 --> 00:36:47.949
I had not, cried the mouse, sharply and very angrily.

00:36:48.769 --> 00:36:54.029
I'm not, said Alice, always ready to make herself useful,

00:36:54.749 --> 00:36:56.809
and looking anxiously about her.

00:36:57.789 --> 00:37:00.949
Oh, do let me help to undo it.

00:37:02.209 --> 00:37:05.169
I shall do nothing of the sort, said the mouse,

00:37:05.749 --> 00:37:07.329
getting up and walking away.

00:37:08.089 --> 00:37:11.649
You insult me by talking such nonsense.

00:37:12.869 --> 00:37:15.589
I didn't mean it, pleaded poor Alice,

00:37:15.589 --> 00:37:19.469
but you're so easily offended, you know.

00:37:20.729 --> 00:37:23.749
The mouse only growled in reply.

00:37:25.329 --> 00:37:30.869
Please come back and finish your story, Alice called after it,

00:37:31.429 --> 00:37:33.629
and the others all joined in chorus.

00:37:34.449 --> 00:37:36.009
Yes, please do.

00:37:37.229 --> 00:37:40.949
But the mouse only shook its head impatiently,

00:37:41.289 --> 00:37:42.609
and walked a little quicker.

00:37:43.829 --> 00:37:46.889
What a pity it wouldn't stay, sighed the lorry,

00:37:47.449 --> 00:37:50.289
as soon as it was quite out of sight,

00:37:50.909 --> 00:37:55.909
and an old crab took the opportunity of saying to her daughter,

00:37:56.609 --> 00:38:03.189
Ah, my dear, let this be a lesson to you never to lose your temper.

00:38:04.509 --> 00:38:08.929
Hold your tongue, ma, said the young crab a little snappishly.

00:38:08.929 --> 00:38:12.409
You're enough to try the patience of an oyster.

00:38:14.809 --> 00:38:19.969
Oh, I wish I had our Dinah here, I know I do, said Alice aloud,

00:38:20.729 --> 00:38:22.589
addressing nobody in particular.

00:38:23.369 --> 00:38:25.309
She'd soon fetch it back.

00:38:26.989 --> 00:38:32.549
And who is Dinah, if I might venture to ask the question, said the lorry.

00:38:33.789 --> 00:38:40.209
Alice replied eagerly, for she was always ready to talk about her pet.

00:38:41.449 --> 00:38:48.529
Dinah's our cat, and she's such a capital one for catching mice you can't think.

00:38:49.249 --> 00:38:52.449
And oh, I wish you could see her after the birds.

00:38:53.069 --> 00:38:57.549
Why, she'll eat a little bird as soon as look at it.

00:38:58.949 --> 00:39:04.469
This speech caused a remarkable sensation among the party.

00:39:05.509 --> 00:39:08.009
Some of the birds hurried off at once.

00:39:08.749 --> 00:39:14.289
One old magpie began wrapping itself up very carefully, remarking,

00:39:14.809 --> 00:39:16.869
I really must be getting home.

00:39:17.509 --> 00:39:20.329
The night air doesn't suit my throat.

00:39:21.429 --> 00:39:25.609
And the canary called out in a trembling voice to its children,

00:39:26.449 --> 00:39:31.829
Come away, my dears, it's high time you were all in bed.

00:39:33.149 --> 00:39:40.549
On various pretexts, they all moved off, and Alice was soon left alone.

00:39:42.969 --> 00:39:48.809
Oh, I wish I hadn't mentioned Dinah, she said to herself in a melancholy tone.

00:39:48.809 --> 00:39:56.969
Nobody seems to like her down here, and I'm sure she's the best cat in the world.

00:39:57.889 --> 00:40:03.409
Oh, my dear Dinah, I wonder if I shall ever see you anymore.

00:40:04.369 --> 00:40:11.949
And here poor Alice began to cry again, for she felt very lonely and low-spirited.

00:40:11.949 --> 00:40:20.089
In a little while, however, she again heard a little pattering of footsteps in the distance,

00:40:20.689 --> 00:40:27.749
and she looked up eagerly, half hoping that the mouse had changed his mind

00:40:27.749 --> 00:40:32.069
and was coming back to finish his story.

00:41:22.585 --> 00:41:30.105
trotting slowly back again and looking anxiously about as it went, as if it had lost something.

00:41:30.745 --> 00:41:37.425
And she heard it muttering to itself. The Duchess, the Duchess, oh my dear paws,

00:41:37.845 --> 00:41:44.465
oh my fur and whiskers, she'll get me executed as sure as ferrets are ferrets.

00:41:44.805 --> 00:41:53.345
Where can I have dropped them, I wonder? Alice guessed in a moment that it was looking for the

00:41:53.345 --> 00:42:00.245
and the pair of white kid gloves. And she very good naturedly began hunting about for them,

00:42:01.085 --> 00:42:07.305
but they were nowhere to be seen. Everything seemed to have changed since her swim in the pool

00:42:07.305 --> 00:42:13.485
and the great hall with the glass table and the little door had vanished completely.

00:42:16.125 --> 00:42:22.725
Very soon, the rabbit noticed Alice as she went hunting about and called out to her in

00:42:22.725 --> 00:42:29.445
angry tone. Why Marianne, what are you doing out here? Run home this moment and fetch me a

00:42:29.445 --> 00:42:36.885
pair of gloves and a fan quick now. And Alice was so much frightened that she ran off at once in

00:42:36.885 --> 00:42:42.025
the direction it pointed to without trying to explain the mistake it had made.

00:42:44.745 --> 00:42:48.825
He took me for his housemaid, she said to herself as she ran.

00:42:49.385 --> 00:42:52.045
How surprised he'll be when he finds out who I am,

00:42:52.565 --> 00:42:57.145
but I'd better take him his fan and gloves, that is if I can find them.

00:42:58.825 --> 00:43:04.885
As she said this, she came upon a neat little house on the door of which was a bright brass

00:43:04.885 --> 00:43:13.805
plate with the name W. Rabbit engraved upon it. She went in without knocking and hurried upstairs

00:43:13.805 --> 00:43:18.585
in great fear lest she should meet the real Marianne and be

00:43:19.105 --> 00:43:22.505
turned out of the house before she had found the fan and gloves.

00:43:24.685 --> 00:43:30.905
How queer it seems, Alice said to herself, to be going messages for a rabbit.

00:43:31.605 --> 00:43:34.925
I suppose Diana will be sending me out all messages next.

00:43:36.565 --> 00:43:39.665
And she began faxing the sort of thing that would happen.

00:43:40.265 --> 00:43:43.745
Miss Alice, come here directly and get ready for your walk.

00:43:45.165 --> 00:43:49.185
Coming in a minute, nurse, but I've got to see that the mouse doesn't get out.

00:43:50.365 --> 00:43:56.405
Only I don't think, Alice went on, that they'd let Diana stop in the house if it began ordering

00:43:56.405 --> 00:44:05.045
people about like that. By this time she had found her way into a tidy little room with a table in

00:44:05.045 --> 00:44:13.225
the window and on it, as she had hoped, a fan and two or three pairs of tiny white kid gloves.

00:44:14.385 --> 00:44:20.225
She took up the fan and a pair of the gloves and was just going to leave the room when her eyes

00:44:20.225 --> 00:44:27.405
fell upon a little bottle that stood near the looking glass. There was no label this time with

00:44:27.405 --> 00:44:33.285
the words, drink me, but nevertheless she uncorked it and put it to her lips.

00:44:34.285 --> 00:44:40.985
I know something interesting is sure to happen, she said to herself, whenever I eat or drink

00:44:40.985 --> 00:44:46.565
anything. So I'll just see what this bottle does. I do hope it'll make me grow large again,

00:44:46.625 --> 00:44:49.885
for really I'm quite tired of being such a tiny little thing.

00:44:52.305 --> 00:44:59.985
It did so indeed and much sooner than she had expected. Before she had drunk half the bottle,

00:44:59.985 --> 00:45:07.285
she found her head pressing against the ceiling and had to stoop to save her neck from being broken.

00:45:09.245 --> 00:45:14.605
She hastily put down the bottle, saying to herself, that's quite enough. I hope I shan't

00:45:14.605 --> 00:45:20.745
grow any more, as it is I can't get out of the door. I do wish I hadn't drunk quite so much.

00:45:23.025 --> 00:45:32.625
Alas, it was too late to wish that. She went on growing and growing and very soon had to kneel

00:45:32.625 --> 00:45:39.125
down on the floor. In another minute, there was not even room for this and she tried the effect

00:45:39.125 --> 00:45:45.465
of lying down with one elbow against the door and the other arm curled round her head. Still,

00:45:45.465 --> 00:45:53.085
she went on growing and as a last resource, she put one arm out the window and one foot off the

00:45:53.085 --> 00:46:00.435
chimney and said to herself, now I can do no more whatever happens. What will become of me?

00:46:02.685 --> 00:46:10.105
Luckily for Alice, the little magic bottle had now had its full effect and she grew no larger.

00:46:11.205 --> 00:46:17.885
Still, it was very uncomfortable and as there seemed to be no sort of chance of her ever getting

00:46:17.885 --> 00:46:26.805
out of the room again, no wonder she felt unhappy. It was much pleasanter at home,

00:46:27.085 --> 00:46:33.505
thought poor Alice, when one wasn't always growing larger and smaller and being ordered about by mice

00:46:33.505 --> 00:46:39.505
and rabbits. I almost wish it hadn't gone down that rabbit hole and yet,

00:46:40.185 --> 00:46:48.645
and yet it's rather curious, you know, this sort of life. I do wonder what can have happened to me.

00:46:49.545 --> 00:46:54.025
When I used to read fairy tales, I fancied that kind of thing never happened

00:46:54.025 --> 00:46:59.345
and now here I am in the middle of one. There ought to be a book written about me,

00:46:59.345 --> 00:47:03.645
that there ought and when I grow up, I'll write one.

00:47:04.685 --> 00:47:11.925
But I'm grown up now, she added in a sorrowful tone. At least there's no room to grow up anymore here.

00:47:14.605 --> 00:47:21.065
But then, thought Alice, shall I never get any older than I am now?

00:47:22.105 --> 00:47:25.645
That'll be a comfort one way, never to be an old woman,

00:47:25.645 --> 00:47:31.735
but then always to have lessons to learn. Oh, I shouldn't like that.

00:47:34.465 --> 00:47:40.265
Oh, you foolish Alice, she answered herself. How can you learn lessons in here? Why,

00:47:40.305 --> 00:47:44.085
there's hardly room for you and no room at all for any lesson books.

00:47:45.745 --> 00:47:52.705
And so she went on, taking first one side, then the other and making quite a conversation of it

00:47:52.705 --> 00:47:57.985
altogether. But after a few minutes, she heard a voice outside and stopped to listen.

00:48:00.465 --> 00:48:04.345
Marianne, Marianne, said the voice, fetch me my gloves this moment.

00:48:05.645 --> 00:48:11.325
Then came a little pattering of feet on the stairs. Alice knew it was the rabbit coming

00:48:11.325 --> 00:48:16.745
to look for her and she trembled till she shook the house, quite forgetting that she

00:48:16.745 --> 00:48:22.305
was now about a thousand times as large as the rabbit and had no reason to be afraid of it.

00:48:24.205 --> 00:48:32.065
Presently, the rabbit came up to the door and tried to open it. But as the door opened inwards

00:48:32.065 --> 00:48:41.045
and Alice's elbow was pressed hard against it, that attempt proved a failure. Alice heard it say to

00:48:41.045 --> 00:48:51.525
itself, then I'll go round and get in at the window. That you won't, thought Alice. And after

00:48:51.525 --> 00:48:58.085
waiting till she fancied, she heard the rabbit just under the window. She suddenly spread out

00:48:58.085 --> 00:49:04.365
her hand and made a snatch in the air. She did not get hold of anything, but she heard a little

00:49:04.365 --> 00:49:11.445
shriek and a fall and a crash of broken glass from which she concluded that it was just possible it

00:49:11.445 --> 00:49:20.765
had fallen into a cucumber frame or something of the sort. Next came an angry voice, the rabbit's

00:49:21.405 --> 00:49:29.965
pat. Pat, where are you? And then the voice she had never heard before. Sure then I'm here

00:49:29.965 --> 00:49:38.745
digging for apples, your honor. Digging for apples indeed, said the rabbit angrily. Here,

00:49:38.965 --> 00:49:47.445
come and help me out of this. Sounds of more broken glass. Now tell me Pat, what's that in the window?

00:49:48.745 --> 00:49:58.005
Sure, it's an arm, your honor. He pronounced it arm. An arm, you goose, whoever saw one that size,

00:49:58.345 --> 00:50:04.865
why it fills the whole window. Sure, it does, your honor, but it's an arm for all that.

00:50:06.765 --> 00:50:10.165
Well, it's got no business there at any rate, go and take it away.

00:50:11.845 --> 00:50:18.825
There was a long silence after this and others could only hear whispers now and then, such as

00:50:19.425 --> 00:50:26.865
sure, I don't like it, your honor, at all, at all. Do as I tell you, you coward. And at last she

00:50:26.865 --> 00:50:33.445
spread out her hand again and made another snatch in the air. This time there were two little shrieks

00:50:33.445 --> 00:50:40.245
and more sounds of breaking glass. What a number of cucumber frames there must be,

00:50:40.405 --> 00:50:46.545
thought Alice. I wonder what they'll do next. As for pulling me out of the window,

00:50:46.885 --> 00:50:51.705
I only wish they could. Sure, I don't want to stay in here any longer.

00:50:54.505 --> 00:51:02.125
She waited for some time without hearing anything more. At last came a rumbling of little cartwheels

00:51:02.125 --> 00:51:08.105
and the sound of a good many voices all talking together. She made out the words.

00:51:09.305 --> 00:51:15.825
Where's the other ladder? Why, I hadn't thought to bring but one. Bill's got the other. Bill,

00:51:16.065 --> 00:51:21.645
fetch it here, lad. Here, put them up at the corner. No, tie them together first,

00:51:21.665 --> 00:51:27.365
they don't reach half high enough yet. Oh, they'll do well enough, don't be particular.

00:51:28.045 --> 00:51:35.565
Here, Bill, catch hold of this rope. Will the roof break? Mind that loose slut.

00:51:36.345 --> 00:51:44.345
Oh, it's coming down. Heads below. A loud crush. Now, who did that? It was Bill, I fancy.

00:51:45.385 --> 00:51:53.625
Who's to go down the chimney? Nay, I shan't. You do it. That I won't think. Bill's to go down.

00:51:53.625 --> 00:51:56.405
Here, Bill, the master says you're to go down the chimney.

00:51:59.385 --> 00:52:05.945
Oh, so Bill's got to come down the chimney, has he? Said Alastair herself.

00:52:06.985 --> 00:52:13.065
Sure, they seem to put everything upon Bill. I wouldn't be in Bill's place for a good deal.

00:52:13.325 --> 00:52:18.465
This fireplace is narrow, to be sure, but I think I can kick a little.

00:52:20.505 --> 00:52:27.845
She drew her foot as far down the chimney as she could and waited till she heard a little animal.

00:52:28.225 --> 00:52:34.265
She couldn't guess of what sort it was, scratching and scrambling about in the

00:52:34.265 --> 00:52:44.065
chimney close above her, then saying to herself, this is Bill. She gave one sharp kick and waited

00:52:44.065 --> 00:52:50.705
to see what would happen next. The first thing she heard was a general chorus of,

00:52:51.045 --> 00:52:56.685
there goes Bill. Then the rabbit's voice along, catch him, you by the hedge.

00:52:58.085 --> 00:53:02.465
Then silence and then another confusion of voices.

00:53:04.585 --> 00:53:10.605
Hold up his head. Brandy now, don't choke him. How was it, old fella? What happened to you?

00:53:10.605 --> 00:53:12.425
Tell us all about it.

00:53:15.625 --> 00:53:21.985
Last came a little feeble, squeaking voice. That's Bill, thought Alice.

00:53:24.005 --> 00:53:30.925
Well, I hardly know no more. Thank you. I'm better now, but I'm a deal too flustered to tell you.

00:53:31.365 --> 00:53:36.805
All I know is something comes at me like a jack in the box and up I goes like a skyrocket.

00:53:38.385 --> 00:53:41.385
So you did, old fella, said the others.

00:53:43.705 --> 00:53:50.925
We must burn the house down, said the rabbit's voice and Alice called out as loud as she could.

00:53:52.065 --> 00:53:54.865
If you do, I'll set diner at you.

00:53:57.385 --> 00:54:02.585
There was a deadly silence instantly and Alice thought to herself,

00:54:03.465 --> 00:54:09.645
I wonder what they will do next. If they had any sense, they'd take the roof off.

00:54:11.365 --> 00:54:14.965
After a minute or two, they began moving about again

00:54:14.965 --> 00:54:19.865
and Alice heard the rabbit say, a barrel full will do to begin with.

00:54:22.625 --> 00:54:29.685
A barrel full of what, thought Alice, but she had not long to doubt for the next moment,

00:54:29.685 --> 00:54:35.745
a shower of little pebbles came rattling in at the window and some of them hit her in the face.

00:54:37.325 --> 00:54:41.025
I'll put a stop to this, she said to herself and shouted out,

00:54:41.465 --> 00:54:48.025
you'd better not do that again, which produced another dead silence.

00:54:50.325 --> 00:54:56.445
Alice noted with some surprise that the pebbles were all turning into little kegs as they lay on

00:54:56.445 --> 00:54:59.785
the floor and a bright idea came into her head.

00:55:01.865 --> 00:55:08.125
If I eat one of these kegs, she thought, it's sure to make some change in my size

00:55:08.125 --> 00:55:14.145
and as it can't possibly make me larger, it must make me smaller, I suppose.

00:55:15.925 --> 00:55:21.985
So she swallowed one of the kegs and was delighted to find that she began shrinking directly.

00:55:22.845 --> 00:55:25.765
As soon as she was small enough to get through the door,

00:55:25.965 --> 00:55:31.505
she ran out of the house and found quite a crowd of little animals and birds waiting outside.

00:55:33.045 --> 00:55:38.845
The poor little lizard, Bill, was in the middle being held up by two guinea pigs

00:55:38.845 --> 00:55:41.485
who were giving it something out of a bottle.

00:55:42.665 --> 00:55:45.945
They all made a rush at Alice the moment she appeared,

00:55:46.245 --> 00:55:51.145
but she ran off as hard as she could and soon found herself safe in a thick wood.

00:55:52.905 --> 00:55:59.325
The first thing I've got to do, said Alice to herself as she wandered about in the wood,

00:55:59.985 --> 00:56:06.825
is to grow to my right size again and the second thing is to find my way into that lovely garden.

00:56:07.425 --> 00:56:10.225
I think that that would be the best plan.

00:56:12.665 --> 00:56:19.345
It sounded an excellent plan, no doubt, and very neatly and simply arranged.

00:56:20.035 --> 00:56:26.275
The only difficulty was that she had not got the smallest idea how to set about it

00:56:26.825 --> 00:56:30.805
and while she was peering about anxiously among the trees,

00:56:31.225 --> 00:56:36.585
a little sharp bark just over her head made her look up in a great hurry.

00:56:38.965 --> 00:56:47.325
An enormous puppy was looking down at her with large round eyes and feebly stretching out one

00:56:47.325 --> 00:56:49.285
paw trying to touch her.

00:56:51.605 --> 00:56:58.345
Poor little thing, said Alice in a coaxing tone and she tried hard to whistle to it,

00:56:58.525 --> 00:57:03.065
but she was terribly frightened all the time at the thought that it might be hungry,

00:57:03.505 --> 00:57:07.725
in which case it would be very likely to eat her up in spite of all her coaxing.

00:57:10.585 --> 00:57:16.205
Hardly knowing what she did, she picked up a little bit of stick and held it up to the puppy,

00:57:16.205 --> 00:57:22.005
whereupon the puppy jumped into the air off all its feet at once with a yelp of delight

00:57:22.005 --> 00:57:25.775
and rushed at the stick and made believe to worry it.

00:57:26.785 --> 00:57:33.225
Then Alice dodged behind a great thistle to keep herself from being run over and the moment she

00:57:33.225 --> 00:57:39.265
appeared on the other side the puppy made another rush at the stick and tumbled head over heels in

00:57:39.265 --> 00:57:46.185
its hurry to get hold of it. Then Alice, thinking it was very like having a game of play with a

00:57:46.185 --> 00:57:53.305
cart horse and expecting every moment to be trampled under its feet, ran round the thistle

00:57:53.305 --> 00:57:59.845
again. Then the puppy began a series of short charges at the stick, running a very little way

00:57:59.845 --> 00:58:08.105
forwards each time and a long way back, embarking hoarsely all the while till at last it sat down

00:58:08.105 --> 00:58:15.765
a good way off, panting with its tongue hanging out of its mouth and its great eyes half shut.

00:58:18.485 --> 00:58:25.065
This seemed to Alice a good opportunity for making her escape, so she set off at once

00:58:25.065 --> 00:58:32.525
and ran till she was quite tired and out of breath and till the puppy's bark sounded quite faint in

00:58:32.525 --> 00:58:41.705
the distance. And yet what a dear little puppy it was, said Alice, as she leaned against a

00:58:41.705 --> 00:58:48.365
cup to rest herself and found herself with one of the leaves. I should have liked teaching it

00:58:48.365 --> 00:58:56.605
tricks very much if if I'd only been the right size to do it. Oh dear, I'd nearly forgotten that

00:58:56.605 --> 00:59:05.145
I've got to grow up again. Let me see, how is this to be managed? I suppose I ought to eat or drink

00:59:05.145 --> 00:59:13.475
something or other, but the great question is what? The great question certainly was

00:59:13.985 --> 00:59:22.285
what? Alice looked all round her at the flowers and the blades of grass, but she did not see

00:59:22.285 --> 00:59:27.565
anything that looked like the right thing to eat or drink under the circumstances.

00:59:28.865 --> 00:59:37.265
There was a large mushroom growing near her, about the same height as herself, and when she had looked

00:59:37.265 --> 00:59:45.165
under it and on both sides of it and behind it, it occurred to her that she might as well look and

00:59:45.165 --> 00:59:55.245
see what was on top of it. She stretched herself up on tiptoe and peeped over the edge of the

00:59:55.245 --> 01:00:04.225
mushroom, and her eyes immediately met those of a large caterpillar that was sitting on the top

01:00:04.225 --> 01:00:14.745
with its arms folded, quietly smoking a long hookah and taking not the smallest notice of her

01:00:14.745 --> 01:00:16.745
or of anything else.

01:01:01.165 --> 01:01:05.485
The Caterpillar and Alice looked at each other for some time in silence.

01:01:06.265 --> 01:01:11.885
At last the Caterpillar took the hookah out of its mouth and addressed her in a languid, sleepy voice.

01:01:12.985 --> 01:01:15.745
Who are you? said the Caterpillar.

01:01:17.085 --> 01:01:20.065
This was not an encouraging opening for a conversation.

01:01:21.225 --> 01:01:23.665
Alice replied rather shyly.

01:01:24.005 --> 01:01:30.045
I hardly know sir, just at present. At least I know who I was when I got up this morning.

01:01:30.285 --> 01:01:33.505
But I think I must have been changed several times since then.

01:01:34.905 --> 01:01:40.025
What do you mean by that? said the Caterpillar sternly. Explain yourself.

01:01:41.585 --> 01:01:47.145
I can't explain myself, I'm afraid, sir, said Alice. Because I'm not myself, you see.

01:01:48.225 --> 01:01:50.265
I don't see, said the Caterpillar.

01:01:51.945 --> 01:01:56.005
I'm afraid I can't put it more clearly, Alice replied very politely.

01:01:56.005 --> 01:02:02.385
For I can't understand it myself to begin with, and being so many different sizes in a day is very confusing.

01:02:03.725 --> 01:02:05.585
It isn't, said the Caterpillar.

01:02:07.405 --> 01:02:10.445
Well, perhaps you haven't found it so yet, said Alice.

01:02:11.085 --> 01:02:14.825
But when you have to turn into a chrysalis, you will some day, you know.

01:02:15.085 --> 01:02:19.845
And then after that into a butterfly, I should think you'll feel it a little queer, won't you?

01:02:20.865 --> 01:02:22.505
Not a bit, said the Caterpillar.

01:02:23.625 --> 01:02:30.505
Well, perhaps your feelings may be different, said Alice. All I know is it would feel very queer to me.

01:02:31.665 --> 01:02:36.085
You, said the Caterpillar contemptuously, who are you?

01:02:37.165 --> 01:02:40.285
Which brought them back again to the beginning of the conversation.

01:02:41.565 --> 01:02:48.595
Alice felt a little irritated at the Caterpillar's making such very short remarks, and she drew herself up and said, very gravely,

01:02:49.175 --> 01:02:52.375
I think you ought to tell me who you are first.

01:02:53.535 --> 01:02:55.315
Why, said the Caterpillar.

01:02:56.755 --> 01:03:03.655
Here was another puzzling question, and as Alice could not think of any good reason, and as the Caterpillar seemed to be in a very

01:03:03.655 --> 01:03:06.135
unpleasant state of mind, she turned away.

01:03:07.555 --> 01:03:12.275
Come back, the Caterpillar called after her. I've something important to say.

01:03:13.635 --> 01:03:17.795
This sounded promising, certainly. Alice turned and came back again.

01:03:19.275 --> 01:03:21.735
Keep your temper, said the Caterpillar.

01:03:23.515 --> 01:03:27.295
Is that all, said Alice, swallowing down her anger as well as she could?

01:03:28.775 --> 01:03:30.715
No, said the Caterpillar.

01:03:33.235 --> 01:03:39.615
Alice thought she might as well wait, as she had nothing else to do, and perhaps after all it might tell her something worth hearing.

01:03:40.475 --> 01:03:48.195
For some minutes it puffed away without speaking, but at last it unfolded its arms, took the hookah out of its mouth again, and said,

01:03:48.755 --> 01:03:51.475
So you think you're changed, do you?

01:03:52.615 --> 01:04:00.395
I'm afraid I am, sir, said Alice. I can't remember things as I used, and I don't keep the same size for ten minutes together.

01:04:02.315 --> 01:04:04.915
Can't remember what things, said the Caterpillar.

01:04:06.075 --> 01:04:13.075
Well, I've tried to say how doth the little busy bee, but it all came different, Alice replied in a very melancholy voice.

01:04:14.775 --> 01:04:17.995
Repeat, your old father William, said the Caterpillar.

01:04:19.475 --> 01:04:21.575
Alice folded her hands and began,

01:04:22.735 --> 01:04:32.035
You are old, father William, the young man said, and your hair has become very white, and yet you incessantly stand on your head. Do you think at your age it is right?

01:04:33.095 --> 01:04:41.915
In my youth, father William replied to his son, I feared it might injure the brain, but now that I'm perfectly sure I have none, why I do it again and again.

01:04:42.695 --> 01:04:52.655
You are old, said the youth, as I mentioned before, and have grown most uncommonly fat, yet you turned a back somersault in at the door. Pray, what is the reason of that?

01:04:53.735 --> 01:05:02.435
In my youth, said the Sage, as he shook his grey locks, I kept all my limbs very supple by the use of this ointment, one shilling the box. Allow me to sell you a couple?

01:05:03.855 --> 01:05:13.655
You are old, said the youth, and your jaws are too weak for anything tougher than suet, yet you finished the goose with the bones in the beak. Pray, how did you manage to do it?

01:05:14.615 --> 01:05:23.915
In my youth, said his father, I took to the law and argued each case with my wife, and the muscular strength which it gave to my jaw has lasted the rest of my life.

01:05:25.015 --> 01:05:34.355
You are old, said the youth, one would hardly suppose that your eye was as steady as ever, yet you balanced an eel on the end of your nose. What made you so awfully clever?

01:05:35.455 --> 01:05:44.335
I have answered three questions, and that is enough, said his father. Don't give yourself airs. Do you think I can listen all day to such stuff? Be off, or I'll kick you down stairs.

01:05:46.295 --> 01:05:48.875
That is not said right, said the Caterpillar.

01:05:50.295 --> 01:05:55.775
Not quite right, I'm afraid, said Alice, timidly. Some of the words have got altered.

01:05:57.675 --> 01:06:04.035
It is wrong from beginning to end, said the Caterpillar decidedly, and there was silence for some minutes.

01:06:05.715 --> 01:06:07.515
The Caterpillar was the first to speak.

01:06:08.835 --> 01:06:11.375
What size do you want to be? it asked.

01:06:12.815 --> 01:06:19.795
Oh, I'm not particular as to size, Alice hastily replied. Only one doesn't like changing so often, you know.

01:06:21.055 --> 01:06:23.335
I don't know, said the Caterpillar.

01:06:24.995 --> 01:06:31.715
Alice said nothing. She had never been so much contradicted in her life before, and she felt that she was losing her temper.

01:06:33.855 --> 01:06:36.435
Are you content now, said the Caterpillar?

01:06:37.835 --> 01:06:45.235
Well, I should like to be a little larger, sir, if you wouldn't mind, said Alice. Three inches is such a wretched height to be.

01:06:46.375 --> 01:06:53.975
It is a very good height indeed, said the Caterpillar angrily, rearing itself upright as it spoke. It was exactly three inches high.

01:06:55.095 --> 01:07:03.255
But I'm not used to it, pleaded poor Alice in a piteous tone, and she thought to herself, I wish the creatures wouldn't be so easily offended.

01:07:04.915 --> 01:07:11.855
You'll get used to it in time, said the Caterpillar, and it put the hookah into its mouth and began smoking again.

01:07:13.195 --> 01:07:16.915
This time Alice waited patiently until it chose to speak again.

01:07:17.855 --> 01:07:23.895
In a minute or two, the Caterpillar took the hookah out of its mouth and yawned once or twice and shook itself.

01:07:24.915 --> 01:07:30.255
Then it got down off the mushroom and crawled away in the grass, merely remarking as it went.

01:07:30.975 --> 01:07:34.835
One side will make you grow taller, and the other side will make you grow shorter.

01:07:36.715 --> 01:07:40.375
One side of what? The other side of what? thought Alice to herself.

01:07:41.755 --> 01:07:48.655
Of the mushroom, said the Caterpillar, just as if she had asked it aloud, and in another moment it was out of sight.

01:07:50.795 --> 01:07:59.955
Alice remained looking thoughtfully at the mushroom for a minute, trying to make out which were the two sides of it, and as it was perfectly round, she found this a very difficult question.

01:08:00.835 --> 01:08:07.575
However, at last she stretched her arms round it as far as they would go, and broke off a bit of the edge with each hand.

01:08:08.995 --> 01:08:15.135
And now, which is which? she said to herself, and nibbled a little of the right hand bit to try the effect.

01:08:16.075 --> 01:08:20.355
The next moment she felt a violent blow underneath her chin. It had struck her foot.

01:08:21.755 --> 01:08:28.475
She was a good deal frightened by this very sudden change, but she felt that there was no time to be lost as she was shrinking rapidly.

01:08:28.475 --> 01:08:31.675
So she set to work at once to eat some of the other bit.

01:08:32.595 --> 01:08:41.955
Her chin was pressed so closely against her foot that there was hardly room to open her mouth, but she did it at last and managed to swallow a morsel of the left hand bit.

01:08:44.315 --> 01:08:53.415
Come, my head's free at last, said Alice in a tone of delight, which changed into alarm in another moment, when she found that her shoulders were nowhere to be found.

01:08:53.415 --> 01:09:03.775
All she could see, when she looked down, was an immense length of neck, which seemed to rise like a stalk out of a sea of green leaves that lay far below her.

01:09:04.915 --> 01:09:13.795
What can all that green stuff be? said Alice. And where have my shoulders got to? And oh, my poor hands, how is it I can't see you?

01:09:14.475 --> 01:09:21.635
She was moving them about as she spoke, but no results seemed to follow, except a little shaking among the distant green leaves.

01:09:23.055 --> 01:09:34.295
As there seemed to be no chance of getting her hands up to her head, she tried to get her head down to them, and was delighted to find that her neck would bend about easily in any direction like a serpent.

01:09:35.355 --> 01:09:49.255
She had just succeeded in curving it down into a graceful zigzag and was going to dive in among the leaves, which she found to be nothing but the tops of the trees under which she had been wandering, when a sharp hiss made her draw back in a hurry.

01:09:49.255 --> 01:09:54.495
A large pigeon had flown into her face and was beating her violently with its wings.

01:09:55.575 --> 01:09:57.155
Serpent, screamed the pigeon.

01:09:58.435 --> 01:10:01.675
I'm not a serpent, said Alice indignantly. Let me alone.

01:10:02.635 --> 01:10:11.835
Serpent, I say again, repeated the pigeon, but in a more subdued tone, and added with a kind of sob. I've tried every way and nothing seems to suit them.

01:10:13.455 --> 01:10:16.435
I haven't the least idea what you're talking about, said Alice.

01:10:17.175 --> 01:10:26.395
I've tried the roots of trees, and I've tried banks, and I've tried hedges, the pigeon went on without attending to her. But those serpents, there's no pleasing them.

01:10:28.195 --> 01:10:34.895
Alice was more and more puzzled, but she thought there was no use in saying anything more till the pigeon had finished.

01:10:36.215 --> 01:10:45.695
As if it wasn't trouble enough hatching the eggs, said the pigeon, but I must be on the lookout for serpents night and day. Why I haven't had a wink of sleep these three weeks.

01:10:47.115 --> 01:10:51.395
I'm very sorry you've been annoyed, said Alice, who was beginning to see its meaning.

01:10:52.575 --> 01:10:58.375
And just as I'd taken the highest tree in the wood, continued the pigeon, raising its voice to a shriek.

01:10:58.615 --> 01:11:05.515
And just as I was thinking I should be free of them at last, they must needs come wriggling down from the sky. Ug, serpent.

01:11:06.955 --> 01:11:11.835
But I'm not a serpent, I tell you, said Alice. I'm a, I'm a.

01:11:11.835 --> 01:11:16.615
Well, what are you, said the pigeon? I can see you're trying to invent something.

01:11:18.055 --> 01:11:24.535
I, I'm a little girl, said Alice, rather doubtfully, as she remembered the number of changes she had gone through that day.

01:11:25.635 --> 01:11:30.035
A likely story indeed, said the pigeon, in a tone of the deepest contempt.

01:11:30.635 --> 01:11:41.135
I've seen a good many little girls in my time, but never one with such a neck as that. No, no, you're a serpent, and there's no use denying it. I suppose you'll be telling me next that you have never tasted an egg.

01:11:42.295 --> 01:11:50.275
I have tasted eggs certainly, said Alice, who was a very truthful child. But little girls eat eggs quite as much as serpents do, you know.

01:11:51.875 --> 01:11:57.915
I don't believe it, said the pigeon. But if they do, why then they're a kind of serpent, that's all I can say.

01:11:59.715 --> 01:12:06.735
This was such a new idea to Alice, that she was quite silent for a minute or two, which gave the pigeon the opportunity of adding,

01:12:06.735 --> 01:12:12.935
You're looking for eggs, I know that well enough. And what does it matter to me whether you're a little girl or a serpent?

01:12:14.295 --> 01:12:23.375
It matters a good deal to me, said Alice hastily. But I'm not looking for eggs as it happens. And if I was, I shouldn't want yours. I don't like them raw.

01:12:24.535 --> 01:12:29.955
Well, be off then, said the pigeon, in a sulky tone, as it settled down again into its nest.

01:12:30.975 --> 01:12:40.295
Alice crouched down among the trees as well as she could, for her neck kept getting entangled among the branches, and every now and then she had to stop and untwist it.

01:12:40.675 --> 01:12:50.295
After a while, she remembered that she still held the pieces of mushroom in her hands, and she set to work very carefully, nibbling first at one and then at the other,

01:12:50.515 --> 01:12:56.995
and growing sometimes taller and sometimes shorter, until she had succeeded in bringing herself down to her usual height.

01:12:58.395 --> 01:13:08.955
It was so long since she had been anything near the right size that it felt quite strange at first, but she got used to it in a few minutes and began talking to herself as usual.

01:13:09.975 --> 01:13:17.315
Come, there's half my plan done now. How puzzling all these changes are. I'm never sure what I'm going to be from one minute to another.

01:13:17.895 --> 01:13:24.995
However, I've got back to my right size. The next thing is to get into that beautiful garden. How is that to be done, I wonder?

01:13:26.075 --> 01:13:32.175
As she said this, she came suddenly upon an open place, with a little house in it about four feet high.

01:13:33.575 --> 01:13:40.095
Whoever lives there, thought Alice, it'll never do to come upon them this size. Why, I should frighten them out of their wits.

01:13:41.215 --> 01:13:49.095
So she began nibbling at the right hand bit again, and did not venture to go near the house until she had brought herself down to nine inches high.

01:13:55.015 --> 01:13:58.395
28th, 2005, in Longmont, Colorado.

01:14:12.554 --> 01:14:14.794
This reading by Raza Shah.

01:14:15.334 --> 01:14:18.494
Alice's Adventures in Wonderland by Lewis Carroll

01:14:18.494 --> 01:14:20.554
Pig and Pepper

01:14:21.954 --> 01:14:28.374
For a minute or two she stood looking at the house and wondering what to do next, when suddenly a footman in livery came running out of the wood.

01:14:28.374 --> 01:14:36.254
She considered him a footman because he was in livery, otherwise judging by his face only she would have called him a fish, and rapped loudly at the door with his knuckles.

01:14:36.694 --> 01:14:45.354
It was opened by another footman in livery with a round face and large eyes like a frog, and both footmen, Alice noticed, had powdered hair and curls all over their head.

01:14:45.794 --> 01:14:49.974
She felt very curious to know what it was all about and crept a little way out of the wood to listen.

01:14:49.974 --> 01:15:01.454
The fish footman began by producing from under his arm a great letter, nearly as large as himself, and this he handed over to the other saying in a solemn tone, for the duchess an invitation from the queen to play croquet.

01:15:02.134 --> 01:15:09.694
The frog footman repeated in the same solemn tone only changing the order of the words a little, from the queen an invitation for the duchess to play croquet.

01:15:10.514 --> 01:15:13.394
Then they both bowed and their curls got entangled together.

01:15:13.914 --> 01:15:18.634
Alice laughed so much at this that she had to run back into the wood for fear of their hearing her.

01:15:19.034 --> 01:15:25.574
And when she next peeped out, the fish footman was gone and the other was sitting on the ground near the door staring stupidly up into the sky.

01:15:26.634 --> 01:15:28.474
Alice went timidly up to the door and knocked.

01:15:29.114 --> 01:15:33.174
There's no sort of use in knocking, said the footman, and that for two reasons.

01:15:33.594 --> 01:15:40.254
First, because I am on the same side of the door as you, secondly, because they're making such a noise inside that no one could possibly hear you.

01:15:40.254 --> 01:15:50.014
And certainly there was a most extraordinary noise going on within, a constant howling and sneezing, and every now and then a great crash as if a dish or a kettle had been broken to pieces.

01:15:50.654 --> 01:15:52.834
Please then, said Alice, how am I to get in?

01:15:53.294 --> 01:15:57.314
There might be some sense in your knocking, the footman went on without attending to her.

01:15:57.774 --> 01:16:03.214
If we had a door between us, for instance, if you were inside you might knock and I could let you out, you know.

01:16:03.654 --> 01:16:08.494
He was looking up into the sky all the time he was speaking, and this, Alice thought decidedly uncivil.

01:16:08.494 --> 01:16:11.074
But perhaps he can't help it, she said to herself.

01:16:11.334 --> 01:16:16.434
His eyes are so very nearly at the top of his head, but at any rate he might answer questions.

01:16:17.194 --> 01:16:19.134
How am I to get in? she repeated aloud.

01:16:20.374 --> 01:16:23.434
I shall sit here, the footman remarked, till tomorrow.

01:16:24.254 --> 01:16:28.994
At this moment the door of the house opened and a large plate came skimming out straight for the footman's head.

01:16:29.694 --> 01:16:33.594
It just grazed his nose and broke to pieces against one of the trees behind him.

01:16:34.174 --> 01:16:39.374
Or next day maybe, the footman continued in the same tone exactly as if nothing had happened.

01:16:40.234 --> 01:16:43.274
How am I to get in? asked Alice in a louder tone.

01:16:43.954 --> 01:16:46.274
Are you to get in at all? said the footman.

01:16:46.514 --> 01:16:48.134
That's the first question, you know.

01:16:48.754 --> 01:16:51.854
It was no doubt, only Alice did not like to be told so.

01:16:52.234 --> 01:16:54.314
It's really dreadful, she muttered to herself.

01:16:54.594 --> 01:16:57.794
The way all these creatures argue, it's enough to drive one crazy.

01:16:58.334 --> 01:17:03.094
The footman seemed to think this a good opportunity for repeating his remark with variations.

01:17:03.794 --> 01:17:05.474
I shall sit here, he said.

01:17:05.934 --> 01:17:07.534
On and off for days and days.

01:17:07.734 --> 01:17:09.374
But what am I to do? said Alice.

01:17:09.754 --> 01:17:12.334
Anything you like, said the footman and began whistling.

01:17:13.094 --> 01:17:15.694
Oh, there's no use in talking to him, said Alice desperately.

01:17:15.974 --> 01:17:17.374
He's perfectly idiotic.

01:17:17.634 --> 01:17:19.314
And then opened the door and went in.

01:17:19.934 --> 01:17:24.254
The door led right into a large kitchen which was full of smoke from one end to the other.

01:17:24.254 --> 01:17:27.774
The duchess was sitting on a three-legged stool in the middle, nursing a baby.

01:17:28.294 --> 01:17:32.454
The cook was leaning over the fire, stirring a large cauldron which seemed to be full of soup.

01:17:33.174 --> 01:17:38.214
There's certainly too much pepper in that soup, Alice said to herself, as well as she could for sneezing.

01:17:38.494 --> 01:17:40.554
There certainly was too much of it in the air.

01:17:40.894 --> 01:17:46.454
Even the duchess sneezed occasionally, and as for the baby, it was sneezing and howling alternately without a moment's pause.

01:17:46.834 --> 01:17:53.114
The only two creatures in the kitchen that did not sneeze were the cook and the large cat which was laying on the hearth and grinning from ear to ear.

01:17:54.114 --> 01:18:02.654
Please, would you tell me, said Alice a little timidly, for she was not quite sure whether it was good manners for her to speak first, why your cat grins like that?

01:18:03.454 --> 01:18:07.054
It's a Cheshire cat, said the duchess, and that's why, pig!

01:18:07.594 --> 01:18:15.614
She said the last word with such sudden violence that Alice quite jumped, but she saw in another moment that it was addressed to the baby and not to her.

01:18:15.954 --> 01:18:17.754
So she took courage and went on again.

01:18:17.754 --> 01:18:23.114
I didn't know that Cheshire cats always grinned. In fact, I didn't know that cats could grin.

01:18:23.634 --> 01:18:26.114
They all can, said the duchess, and most of them do.

01:18:26.874 --> 01:18:31.734
I don't know any that do, said Alice very politely, feeling quite pleased to have gotten into a conversation.

01:18:32.254 --> 01:18:35.254
You don't know much, said the duchess, and that's a fact!

01:18:36.174 --> 01:18:41.714
Alice did not like at all the tone of this remark and thought it would be as well to introduce some other subject of conversation.

01:18:41.714 --> 01:18:51.034
While she was trying to fix on one, the cook took the cauldron of soup off the fire and at once set to work throwing everything within her reach at the duchess and the baby.

01:18:51.674 --> 01:18:56.254
The fire irons came first, then followed a shower of saucepans, plates, and dishes.

01:18:56.654 --> 01:19:04.214
The duchess took no notice of them even when they hit her, and the baby was howling so much already that it was quite impossible to say whether the blows hurt it or not.

01:19:05.194 --> 01:19:10.134
Oh, please mind what you're doing, cried Alex, jumping up and down in agony of terror.

01:19:10.134 --> 01:19:16.514
Oh, there goes his precious nose, as an unusually large saucepan flew by and very nearly carried it off.

01:19:16.954 --> 01:19:23.214
If everybody minded their own business, said the duchess in a hoarse growl, the world would go around a deal faster than it does.

01:19:23.614 --> 01:19:29.634
Which would not be an advantage, said Alice, who felt very glad to get an opportunity of showing off a little of her knowledge.

01:19:29.774 --> 01:19:32.274
Just think of what work it would make of her the day and night.

01:19:32.674 --> 01:19:36.074
You see, the earth takes 24 hours to turn around on its axis.

01:19:36.074 --> 01:19:39.754
Talking of axis, said the duchess, chop off her head.

01:19:40.414 --> 01:19:46.794
Alice glanced rather anxiously at the cook to see if she meant to take the hint, but the cook was busily stirring the soup and seemed not to be listening.

01:19:47.154 --> 01:19:48.054
She went on again.

01:19:48.634 --> 01:19:51.254
24 hours, I think, or is it 12?

01:19:51.634 --> 01:19:55.254
Oh, don't bother me, said the duchess, I never could abide figures.

01:19:55.734 --> 01:20:02.654
And with this she began nursing the child again, singing a sort of lullaby to it as she did so, and giving a violent shake at the end of every line.

01:20:02.654 --> 01:20:07.574
Speak roughly to your little boy, and beat him when he sneezes.

01:20:07.914 --> 01:20:12.094
He only does it to annoy, because he knows it teases.

01:20:12.674 --> 01:20:15.394
And then the chorus in which the cook and the baby joined.

01:20:15.954 --> 01:20:17.434
Wow, wow, wow!

01:20:18.114 --> 01:20:25.694
While the duchess sang the second verse of the song, she kept tossing the baby violently up and down, and the poor little thing howled so that Alice could hardly hear the words.

01:20:26.154 --> 01:20:30.534
I speak severely to my boy, and beat him when he sneezes.

01:20:30.534 --> 01:20:35.034
For he can thoroughly enjoy the pepper when he pleases.

01:20:35.414 --> 01:20:36.654
Wow, wow, wow!

01:20:37.394 --> 01:20:42.174
Here, you might nurse it a bit if you like, the duchess said to Alice, flinging the baby at her as she spoke.

01:20:42.774 --> 01:20:45.354
I must go and get ready to play croquet with the queen.

01:20:45.654 --> 01:20:50.354
And she hurried out of the room, and the cook threw a frying pan after her as she went, but just missed her.

01:20:50.934 --> 01:20:56.954
Alice caught the baby with some difficulty, as it was a queer-shaped little creature, and held out its arms and legs in all directions.

01:20:56.954 --> 01:21:10.214
Just like a starfish, thought Alice, the poor little thing was snorting like a steam engine when she caught it, and kept doubling itself up and straightening itself out again so that altogether for the first minute or two, it was as much as she could do to hold it.

01:21:10.634 --> 01:21:22.374
As soon as she had made out the proper way of nursing it, which was to twist it up in a sort of knot and then keep tight hold of its rear end and left foot so as to prevent its undoing itself, she carried it into the open air.

01:21:22.374 --> 01:21:29.314
If I don't take this child away from me, thought Alice, they're sure to kill it in a day or two. Wouldn't it be murder to leave it behind?

01:21:29.694 --> 01:21:34.894
She said the last words out loud, and the little thing grunted in reply. It had left off sneezing by this time.

01:21:35.234 --> 01:21:39.434
Don't grunt, said Alice, that's not at all a proper way of expressing yourself.

01:21:39.614 --> 01:21:44.134
The baby grunted again, and Alice looked very anxiously into its face to see what was the matter with it.

01:21:44.134 --> 01:21:49.854
There could be no doubt that it had a very turned-up nose, which was more like a snout than a real nose.

01:21:50.374 --> 01:21:55.814
Also, its eyes were getting extremely small for a baby. Altogether, Alice did not like the look of the thing at all.

01:21:56.414 --> 01:22:01.534
But perhaps it's only sobbing, she thought, and looked into its eyes again to see if there were any tears.

01:22:02.514 --> 01:22:03.854
No, there were no tears.

01:22:04.374 --> 01:22:08.934
If you're going to turn into a pig, my dear, said Alice seriously, I've got nothing more to do with you.

01:22:08.934 --> 01:22:15.774
Mind now, the poor little thing sobbed again, or grunted, it was impossible to say which, and then went on for some while in silence.

01:22:16.674 --> 01:22:20.914
Alice was just beginning to think to herself, now, what am I supposed to do with this creature when I get home?

01:22:21.234 --> 01:22:25.314
When it grunted again so violently that she looked down into its face with some alarm.

01:22:26.554 --> 01:22:30.494
This time, there could be no mistake about it. It was neither more or less than a pig.

01:22:31.274 --> 01:22:34.534
And she felt that it would be quite absurd for her to carry it any further.

01:22:34.534 --> 01:22:39.614
So she let the little creature down and felt quite relieved to see it trot away quietly into the woods.

01:22:40.234 --> 01:22:44.134
If it had grown up, she said to herself, it would have made a dreadfully ugly child.

01:22:44.454 --> 01:22:46.714
But it makes a rather handsome pig, I think.

01:22:46.994 --> 01:22:50.794
And she began thinking of her other children she knew who might do very well as pigs.

01:22:51.274 --> 01:22:55.114
And was just saying to herself, if one only knew the right way to change them.

01:22:55.394 --> 01:23:00.354
When she was a little startled by seeing the Cheshire Cat sitting on the bow of a tree just a few yards off.

01:23:00.354 --> 01:23:02.994
The cat only grinned when it saw Alice.

01:23:03.454 --> 01:23:05.034
And it looked good-natured, she thought.

01:23:05.214 --> 01:23:07.734
Still, it had very long claws and a great many teeth.

01:23:07.954 --> 01:23:10.494
So she felt that it ought to be treated with respect.

01:23:11.374 --> 01:23:13.634
Cheshire Puss, she began rather timidly.

01:23:13.634 --> 01:23:16.474
And she did not at all know whether it would like the name.

01:23:16.574 --> 01:23:18.494
However, it only grinned a little wider.

01:23:18.874 --> 01:23:20.734
Come, it's please so far, thought Alice.

01:23:20.874 --> 01:23:21.794
And she went on.

01:23:22.234 --> 01:23:25.314
Would you tell me, please, which way I ought to go from here?

01:23:26.654 --> 01:23:30.934
That depends a good deal on where you want to go, said the cat.

01:23:31.474 --> 01:23:33.234
I don't much care where, said Alice.

01:23:33.774 --> 01:23:37.434
Then it doesn't matter which way you go, said the cat.

01:23:38.014 --> 01:23:41.314
So as long as I go somewhere, Alice added with explanation.

01:23:42.034 --> 01:23:44.714
Oh, you're sure to do that, said the cat.

01:23:45.074 --> 01:23:47.194
If only you walk long enough.

01:23:47.594 --> 01:23:49.534
Alice felt that this could not be denied.

01:23:49.714 --> 01:23:50.994
So she tried another question.

01:23:51.434 --> 01:23:53.374
What sort of people live about here?

01:23:53.374 --> 01:23:59.594
In that direction, the cat said, waving its right paw around, lives a hatter.

01:24:00.014 --> 01:24:04.374
And in that direction, waving the other paw, lives a march hare.

01:24:04.694 --> 01:24:06.894
Visit either you like. They're both mad.

01:24:07.114 --> 01:24:10.354
But I don't want to go among mad people, Alice remarked.

01:24:10.754 --> 01:24:12.934
Oh, you can't help that, said the cat.

01:24:13.174 --> 01:24:15.894
We're all mad here. I'm mad. You're mad.

01:24:16.254 --> 01:24:18.214
How do you know I'm mad, said Alice?

01:24:18.714 --> 01:24:21.914
You must be, said the cat, or you wouldn't have come here.

01:24:21.914 --> 01:24:25.934
Alice didn't think that proved it at all. However, she went on.

01:24:26.354 --> 01:24:27.694
And how do you know that you're mad?

01:24:28.234 --> 01:24:32.534
To begin with, said the cat, a dog's not mad. You grant that?

01:24:32.934 --> 01:24:34.554
I suppose so, said Alice.

01:24:35.354 --> 01:24:37.014
Well then, the cat went on.

01:24:37.294 --> 01:24:41.974
You see, a dog growls when it's angry, and wags its tail when it's pleased.

01:24:42.214 --> 01:24:46.994
Now, I growl when I'm pleased, and wag my tail when I'm angry.

01:24:47.214 --> 01:24:48.434
Therefore, I'm mad.

01:24:49.114 --> 01:24:51.774
I call it purring, not growling, said Alice.

01:24:52.334 --> 01:24:54.314
Call it what you like, said the cat.

01:24:54.714 --> 01:24:56.794
Do you play croquet with the queen today?

01:24:57.574 --> 01:25:00.894
I should like it very much, said Alice, but I haven't been invited yet.

01:25:01.554 --> 01:25:04.494
You'll see me there, said the cat, and vanished.

01:25:05.394 --> 01:25:09.474
Alice was not much surprised at this. She was getting so well used to the queer things happening.

01:25:10.254 --> 01:25:13.934
While she was still looking at the place where it had been, it suddenly appeared again.

01:25:14.414 --> 01:25:20.574
By the by, what became of the baby, said the cat. I'd nearly forgotten to ask.

01:25:20.894 --> 01:25:26.974
It turned into a pig, Alice answered very quietly, just as if the cat had come back in a natural way.

01:25:27.514 --> 01:25:30.794
I thought it would, said the cat, and vanished again.

01:25:31.174 --> 01:25:34.854
Alice waited a little, half expecting to see it again, but it did not appear.

01:25:35.374 --> 01:25:39.674
After a minute or two, she walked on in the direction in which the March Hare was said to live.

01:25:39.674 --> 01:25:42.254
I've seen hatters before, she said to herself.

01:25:42.654 --> 01:25:48.554
The March Hare will be much more interesting, and perhaps, as this is May, it won't be raving mad.

01:25:48.694 --> 01:25:51.074
At least, not so mad as it was in March.

01:25:51.674 --> 01:25:55.794
As she said this, she looked up, and there was the cat again, sitting on the branch of a tree.

01:25:56.794 --> 01:26:00.294
Did you say pig or fig, said the cat?

01:26:00.654 --> 01:26:06.054
I said pig, replied Alice, and I wished that you wouldn't keep appearing and vanishing so suddenly.

01:26:06.494 --> 01:26:07.954
You make one quite giddy.

01:26:09.034 --> 01:26:13.714
Alright, said the cat, and this time it vanished quite slowly, beginning with the end of the tail,

01:26:13.954 --> 01:26:17.354
and ending with the grin, which remained some time after the rest of it had gone.

01:26:17.854 --> 01:26:23.154
Well, I've often seen a cat without a grin, thought Alice, but a grin without a cat?

01:26:23.514 --> 01:26:26.414
It's the most curious thing I ever saw in all my life.

01:26:27.054 --> 01:26:31.154
She had not gone much further before she came inside of the house of the March Hare.

01:26:31.814 --> 01:26:36.934
She thought it must be the right house, because the chimneys were shaped like ears, and the roof was stashed with fur.

01:26:36.934 --> 01:26:43.354
It was such a large house that she did not like to go nearer till she had nibbled some more of the left-hand bit of mushroom,

01:26:43.834 --> 01:26:45.994
and she raised herself about two feet high.

01:26:46.674 --> 01:26:49.894
Even then she walked up towards it rather timidly, saying to herself,

01:26:50.654 --> 01:26:55.614
Suppose it should be raving mad after all. I almost wish I'd gone to the hatter instead.

01:27:28.764 --> 01:27:34.704
There was a table set out under a tree in front of the house, and the March Hare and

01:27:34.704 --> 01:27:41.004
the Hatter were having tea at it. A door-mouse was sitting between them, fast asleep, and

01:27:41.004 --> 01:27:45.644
the other two were using it as a cushion, resting their elbows on it, and talking over

01:27:45.644 --> 01:27:46.244
its head.

01:27:47.164 --> 01:27:53.324
Very uncomfortable for the door-mouse, thought Alice. Only, as it's asleep, I suppose it

01:27:53.324 --> 01:27:53.924
doesn't mind.

01:27:55.464 --> 01:28:01.144
The table was a large one, but the three were all crowded together at one corner of it.

01:28:01.844 --> 01:28:05.504
No room, no room, they cried out when they saw Alice coming.

01:28:06.484 --> 01:28:13.124
There's plenty of room, said Alice indignantly, and she sat down in a large arm-chair at one

01:28:13.124 --> 01:28:13.864
end of the table.

01:28:14.904 --> 01:28:19.424
Have some wine, the March Hare said, in an encouraging tone.

01:28:20.364 --> 01:28:24.084
Alice looked all round the table, but there was nothing on it but tea.

01:28:24.984 --> 01:28:27.684
I don't see any wine, she remarked.

01:28:28.124 --> 01:28:30.244
There isn't any, said the March Hare.

01:28:31.444 --> 01:28:35.884
Then it wasn't very civil of you to offer it, said Alice angrily.

01:28:36.604 --> 01:28:41.384
It wasn't very civil of you to sit down without being invited, said the March Hare.

01:28:42.284 --> 01:28:47.744
I didn't know it was your table, said Alice. It's laid for a great many more than three.

01:28:49.004 --> 01:28:51.864
Your hare wants cutting, said the Hatter.

01:28:52.944 --> 01:28:58.144
He had been looking at Alice for some time with great curiosity, and this was his first speech.

01:28:59.484 --> 01:29:06.844
You should learn not to make personal remarks, Alice said, with some severity. It's very rude.

01:29:08.864 --> 01:29:13.484
The Hatter opened his eyes very wide on hearing this, but all he said was,

01:29:13.484 --> 01:29:17.704
Why is a raven like a writing-desk?

01:29:18.684 --> 01:29:23.484
Come, we shall have some fun now, thought Alice. I'm glad they've begun asking riddles.

01:29:24.404 --> 01:29:27.364
I believe I can guess that, she added aloud.

01:29:28.984 --> 01:29:32.984
Do you mean that you think you can find out the answer to it, said the March Hare?

01:29:34.444 --> 01:29:36.424
Exactly so, said Alice.

01:29:37.764 --> 01:29:41.404
Then you should say what you mean, the March Hare went on.

01:29:42.724 --> 01:29:51.004
I do, Alice hastily replied. At least, at least I mean what I say. That's the same thing, you know.

01:29:52.084 --> 01:29:54.844
Not the same thing a bit, said the Hatter.

01:29:55.764 --> 01:30:02.904
You might just as well say that I see what I eat is the same thing as I eat what I see.

01:30:04.084 --> 01:30:13.864
You might just as well say, added the March Hare, that I like what I get is the same thing as I get what I like.

01:30:15.164 --> 01:30:20.864
You might just as well say, added the Dormouse, who seemed to be talking in his sleep,

01:30:21.484 --> 01:30:27.484
that I breathe when I sleep is the same thing as I sleep when I breathe.

01:30:28.764 --> 01:30:32.224
It is the same thing with you, said the Hatter.

01:30:32.924 --> 01:30:37.504
And here the conversation dropped, and the party sat silent for a minute,

01:30:37.684 --> 01:30:43.544
while Alice thought over all she could remember about ravens and writing desks, which wasn't much.

01:30:44.804 --> 01:30:47.144
The Hatter was the first to break the silence.

01:30:48.164 --> 01:30:52.024
What day of the month is it? he said, turning to Alice.

01:30:52.024 --> 01:31:00.524
He had taken his watch out of his pocket, and was looking at it uneasily, shaking it every now and then, and holding it to his ear.

01:31:02.244 --> 01:31:04.644
Alice considered a little, and then said,

01:31:05.484 --> 01:31:06.324
The fourth.

01:31:07.884 --> 01:31:10.464
Two days wrong, sighed the Hatter.

01:31:11.184 --> 01:31:16.624
I told you butter wouldn't suit the works, he added, looking angrily at the March Hare.

01:31:17.604 --> 01:31:21.744
It was the best butter, the March Hare meekly replied.

01:31:22.964 --> 01:31:27.104
Yes, but some crumbs must have got in as well, the Hatter grumbled.

01:31:27.644 --> 01:31:30.044
You shouldn't have put it in with the bread knife.

01:31:31.784 --> 01:31:35.304
The March Hare took the watch, and looked at it gloomily.

01:31:35.664 --> 01:31:42.564
Then he dipped it into his cup of tea, and looked at it again, but he could think of nothing better to say than his first remark.

01:31:43.304 --> 01:31:45.804
It was the best butter, you know.

01:31:47.524 --> 01:31:50.504
Alice had been looking over his shoulder with some curiosity.

01:31:51.744 --> 01:31:53.694
What a funny watch, she remarked.

01:31:54.384 --> 01:31:58.184
It tells the day of the month, and doesn't tell what o'clock it is.

01:31:59.284 --> 01:32:01.624
Why should it? muttered the Hatter.

01:32:02.224 --> 01:32:04.604
Does your watch tell you what year it is?

01:32:05.344 --> 01:32:09.044
Of course not, Alice replied very readily.

01:32:09.624 --> 01:32:13.524
But that's because it stays the same year for such a long time together.

01:32:14.704 --> 01:32:18.384
Which is just the case with mine, said the Hatter.

01:32:19.784 --> 01:32:21.644
Alice felt dreadfully puzzled.

01:32:22.124 --> 01:32:27.784
The Hatter's remark seemed to have no sort of meaning in it, and yet it was certainly English.

01:32:28.824 --> 01:32:33.644
I don't quite understand you, she said, as politely as she could.

01:32:35.284 --> 01:32:41.864
The Dormouse is asleep again, said the Hatter, and he poured a little hot tea upon its nose.

01:32:43.164 --> 01:32:47.404
The Dormouse shook its head impatiently, and said, without opening its eyes,

01:32:48.004 --> 01:32:52.104
Of course, of course, just what I was going to remark myself.

01:32:53.784 --> 01:32:58.644
Have you guessed the riddle yet? the Hatter said, turning to Alice again.

01:32:59.624 --> 01:33:04.044
No, I give it up, Alice replied. What's the answer?

01:33:05.264 --> 01:33:08.024
I haven't the slightest idea, said the Hatter.

01:33:09.244 --> 01:33:11.244
Nor I, said the March Hare.

01:33:12.764 --> 01:33:14.104
Alice sighed wearily.

01:33:15.284 --> 01:33:18.984
I think you might do something better with the time, she said,

01:33:19.564 --> 01:33:22.624
Than waste it in asking riddles that have no answers.

01:33:23.764 --> 01:33:27.764
If you knew time as well as I do, said the Hatter,

01:33:28.244 --> 01:33:31.764
You wouldn't talk about wasting it. It's him.

01:33:33.384 --> 01:33:35.784
I don't know what you mean, said Alice.

01:33:36.864 --> 01:33:41.524
Of course you don't, the Hatter said, tossing his head contemptuously.

01:33:42.124 --> 01:33:44.784
I dare say you never even spoke to time.

01:33:46.244 --> 01:33:49.704
Perhaps not, Alice cautiously replied.

01:33:49.704 --> 01:33:53.484
But I know I have to beat time when I learn music.

01:33:54.704 --> 01:33:59.604
Ah, that accounts for it, said the Hatter. He won't stand beating.

01:34:00.244 --> 01:34:05.824
Now, if you only kept on good terms with him, he'd do almost anything you liked with the clock.

01:34:06.384 --> 01:34:11.924
For instance, suppose it were nine o'clock in the morning, just time to begin lessons.

01:34:12.444 --> 01:34:17.424
You'd only have to whisper a hint to time, and round goes the clock in a twinkling.

01:34:17.424 --> 01:34:20.164
Half-past one, time for dinner.

01:34:21.564 --> 01:34:26.044
I only wish it was, the March Hare said to itself in a whisper.

01:34:27.604 --> 01:34:31.224
That would be grand, certainly, said Alice thoughtfully.

01:34:32.064 --> 01:34:35.344
But then I shouldn't be hungry for it, you know.

01:34:36.384 --> 01:34:43.144
Not at first, perhaps, said the Hatter, but you could keep it to half-past one as long as you liked.

01:34:44.364 --> 01:34:47.804
Is that the way you manage? Alice asked.

01:34:49.104 --> 01:34:50.964
The Hatter shook his head mournfully.

01:34:51.804 --> 01:34:58.424
Not I, he replied. We quarrelled last March, just before he went mad, you know.

01:34:59.044 --> 01:35:01.544
Pointing with his teaspoon at the March Hare.

01:35:02.284 --> 01:35:06.604
It was at the great concert given by the Queen of Hearts, and I had to sing

01:35:07.364 --> 01:35:12.144
Twinkle, twinkle, little bat, how I wonder what you're at.

01:35:13.244 --> 01:35:14.664
You know the song, perhaps.

01:35:15.564 --> 01:35:18.104
I've heard something like it, said Alice.

01:35:18.824 --> 01:35:23.224
It goes on, you know, the Hatter continued, in this way.

01:35:24.964 --> 01:35:31.184
Up above the world you fly, like a tea-tray in the sky, twinkle, twinkle.

01:35:32.324 --> 01:35:36.524
Here the Dormouse shook itself and began singing in its sleep.

01:35:37.364 --> 01:35:39.984
Twinkle, twinkle, twinkle, twinkle.

01:35:40.544 --> 01:35:44.304
And went on so long that they had to pinch it to make it stop.

01:35:46.024 --> 01:35:49.804
Well, I'd hardly finished the first verse, said the Hatter,

01:35:50.524 --> 01:35:53.164
when the Queen jumped up and balled out.

01:35:53.584 --> 01:35:56.704
He's murdering the time, off with his head.

01:35:58.224 --> 01:36:01.624
How dreadfully savage, exclaimed Alice.

01:36:02.744 --> 01:36:06.944
And ever since that, the Hatter went on in a mournful tone.

01:36:07.664 --> 01:36:09.544
He won't do a thing, I ask.

01:36:09.964 --> 01:36:11.864
It's always six o'clock now.

01:36:12.984 --> 01:36:15.404
A bright idea came into Alice's head.

01:36:16.404 --> 01:36:20.744
Is that the reason so many tea-things are put out here? she asked.

01:36:22.224 --> 01:36:25.324
Yes, that's it, said the Hatter with a sigh.

01:36:25.324 --> 01:36:30.844
It's always tea-time, and we've no time to wash the things between whiles.

01:36:32.084 --> 01:36:35.784
Then you keep moving round, I suppose, said Alice.

01:36:37.244 --> 01:36:41.724
Exactly so, said the Hatter, as the things get used up.

01:36:42.824 --> 01:36:47.964
But what happens when you come to the beginning again? Alice ventured to ask.

01:36:49.484 --> 01:36:53.504
Suppose we change the subject, the March Hare interrupted, yawning.

01:36:53.504 --> 01:36:58.084
I'm getting tired of this. I vote the young lady tells us a story.

01:36:59.404 --> 01:37:04.384
I'm afraid I don't know one, said Alice, rather alarmed at the proposal.

01:37:05.684 --> 01:37:09.964
Then the door-mouse shall, they both cried, wake up, door-mouse!

01:37:10.444 --> 01:37:12.824
And they pinched it on both sides at once.

01:37:14.304 --> 01:37:16.924
The door-mouse slowly opened his eyes.

01:37:17.804 --> 01:37:22.284
I wasn't asleep, he said, in a hoarse, feeble voice.

01:37:22.284 --> 01:37:25.704
I heard every word you fellows were saying.

01:37:27.144 --> 01:37:29.404
Tell us a story, said the March Hare.

01:37:30.604 --> 01:37:32.864
Yes, please do, pleaded Alice.

01:37:33.984 --> 01:37:38.704
And be quick about it, added the Hatter, or you'll be asleep again before it's done.

01:37:40.164 --> 01:37:42.584
Once upon a time there were three little sisters.

01:37:43.444 --> 01:37:45.744
The door-mouse began in a great hurry.

01:37:46.684 --> 01:37:50.444
And their names were Elsie, Lacey, and Tilly.

01:37:50.964 --> 01:37:53.244
And they lived at the bottom of a well.

01:37:54.604 --> 01:38:01.124
What did they live on, said Alice, who always took a great interest in questions of eating and drinking.

01:38:02.704 --> 01:38:08.324
They lived on treacle, said the door-mouse, after thinking a minute or two.

01:38:09.524 --> 01:38:13.684
They couldn't have done that, you know, Alice gently remarked.

01:38:13.684 --> 01:38:15.204
They'd have been ill.

01:38:16.384 --> 01:38:20.264
So they were, said the door-mouse, very ill.

01:38:22.024 --> 01:38:30.524
Alice tried to fancy to herself what such an extraordinary way of living would be like, but it puzzled her too much, so she went on.

01:38:31.884 --> 01:38:34.364
But why did they live at the bottom of a well?

01:38:35.704 --> 01:38:39.784
Take some more tea, the March Hare said to Alice very earnestly.

01:38:39.784 --> 01:38:45.304
I've had nothing yet, Alice replied in an offended tone.

01:38:45.984 --> 01:38:47.524
So I can't take more.

01:38:48.724 --> 01:38:50.984
You mean you can't take less, said the Hatter.

01:38:51.384 --> 01:38:54.124
It's very easy to take more than nothing.

01:38:56.144 --> 01:38:58.884
Nobody asked your opinion, said Alice.

01:39:00.004 --> 01:39:04.484
Who's making personal remarks now, the Hatter asked triumphantly.

01:39:06.144 --> 01:39:15.984
Alice did not quite know what to say to this, so she helped herself to some tea and bread and butter, and then turned to the door-mouse and repeated her question.

01:39:16.984 --> 01:39:19.184
Why did they live at the bottom of a well?

01:39:20.624 --> 01:39:24.764
The door-mouse again took a minute or two to think about it, and then said,

01:39:25.804 --> 01:39:27.184
It was a treacle well.

01:39:28.224 --> 01:39:39.964
There's no such thing, Alice was beginning very angrily, but the Hatter and the March Hare went shh, shh, and the door-mouse sulkily remarked,

01:39:40.284 --> 01:39:44.124
If you can't be civil, you'd better finish the story for yourself.

01:39:45.384 --> 01:39:49.104
No, please go on, Alice said very humbly.

01:39:49.684 --> 01:39:51.124
I won't interrupt again.

01:39:51.364 --> 01:39:53.024
I dare say there may be one.

01:39:54.104 --> 01:39:57.044
One indeed, said the door-mouse indignantly.

01:39:57.884 --> 01:39:59.744
However, he consented to go on.

01:40:00.784 --> 01:40:05.424
And so these three little sisters, they were learning to draw, you know.

01:40:06.344 --> 01:40:10.584
What did they draw, said Alice, quite forgetting her promise.

01:40:12.024 --> 01:40:16.604
Treacle, said the door-mouse, without considering at all this time.

01:40:17.544 --> 01:40:20.424
I want a clean cup, interrupted the Hatter.

01:40:20.964 --> 01:40:22.644
Let's all move one place on.

01:40:23.744 --> 01:40:27.604
He moved on as he spoke, and the door-mouse followed him.

01:40:27.944 --> 01:40:33.984
The March Hare moved into the door-mouse's place, and Alice rather unwillingly took the place of the March Hare.

01:40:35.344 --> 01:40:41.584
The Hatter was the only one who got any advantage from the change, and Alice was a good deal worse off than before,

01:40:41.584 --> 01:40:45.644
as the March Hare had just upset the milk-jug into his plate.

01:40:47.484 --> 01:40:52.184
Alice did not wish to offend the door-mouse again, so she began very cautiously.

01:40:53.264 --> 01:40:57.644
But I don't understand, where did they draw the treacle from?

01:40:59.084 --> 01:41:02.864
You can draw water out of a water-well, said the Hatter.

01:41:03.664 --> 01:41:07.724
So I should think you could draw treacle out of a treacle-well, eh, stupid?

01:41:08.604 --> 01:41:15.884
But they were in the well, Alice said to the door-mouse, not choosing to notice this last remark.

01:41:17.164 --> 01:41:20.864
Of course they were, said the door-mouse, well in.

01:41:22.364 --> 01:41:29.544
This answer so confused poor Alice that she let the door-mouse go on for some time without interrupting it.

01:41:30.604 --> 01:41:38.424
They were learning to draw, the door-mouse went on, yawning and rubbing its eyes, for it was getting very sleepy.

01:41:39.164 --> 01:41:44.664
And they drew all manner of things, everything that begins with an M.

01:41:46.124 --> 01:41:48.464
Why with an M? said Alice.

01:41:49.664 --> 01:41:51.524
Why not? said the March Hare.

01:41:52.904 --> 01:41:53.884
Alice was silent.

01:41:54.604 --> 01:41:59.864
The door-mouse had closed its eyes by this time, and was going off into a doze.

01:42:00.124 --> 01:42:05.324
But on being pinched by the Hatter, it woke up again with a little shriek, and went on.

01:42:06.224 --> 01:42:15.304
That begins with an M, such as mousetraps, and the moon, and memory, and muchness.

01:42:16.064 --> 01:42:18.944
You know you say things are much of a muchness.

01:42:18.944 --> 01:42:22.804
Did you ever see such a thing as a drawing of a muchness?

01:42:24.264 --> 01:42:28.744
Really, now you ask me, said Alice, very much confused.

01:42:29.524 --> 01:42:30.504
I don't think.

01:42:31.944 --> 01:42:34.724
Then you shouldn't talk, said the Hatter.

01:42:36.404 --> 01:42:39.604
This piece of rudeness was more than Alice could bear.

01:42:40.164 --> 01:42:42.864
She got up in great disgust and walked off.

01:42:42.864 --> 01:42:49.184
The door-mouse fell asleep instantly, and neither of the others took the least notice of her going,

01:42:49.604 --> 01:42:54.124
though she looked back once or twice, half hoping that they would call after her.

01:42:55.184 --> 01:42:59.704
The last time she saw them, they were trying to put the door-mouse into the teapot.

01:43:00.964 --> 01:43:07.064
At any rate, I'll never go there again, said Alice, as she picked her way through the wood.

01:43:07.444 --> 01:43:11.944
It's the stupidest tea-party I ever was at in all my life.

01:43:13.324 --> 01:43:19.164
Just as she said this, she noticed that one of the trees had a door leading right into it.

01:43:20.184 --> 01:43:24.604
That's very curious, she thought, but everything's curious to-day.

01:43:25.024 --> 01:43:27.024
I think I may as well go in at once.

01:43:28.104 --> 01:43:29.524
And in she went.

01:43:31.484 --> 01:43:36.544
Once more she found herself in the long hall, and close to the little glass table.

01:43:37.484 --> 01:43:40.984
Now I'll manage better this time, she said to herself,

01:43:41.664 --> 01:43:47.204
and began by taking the little golden key and unlocking the door that led into the garden.

01:43:48.704 --> 01:43:51.124
Then she went to work nibbling at the mushroom.

01:43:51.604 --> 01:43:55.724
She had kept a piece of it in her pocket, till she was about a foot high.

01:43:56.204 --> 01:44:04.024
Then she walked down the little passage, and then she found herself at last in the beautiful garden,

01:44:04.024 --> 01:44:08.644
among the bright flower beds and the cool fountains.

01:44:40.756 --> 01:44:42.256
The Queen's Croquet Ground

01:44:43.916 --> 01:44:46.976
A large rose tree stood near the entrance of the garden.

01:44:47.256 --> 01:44:51.816
The roses growing on it were white, but there were three gardeners at it, busily painting

01:44:51.816 --> 01:44:52.456
them red.

01:44:53.016 --> 01:44:57.616
Alice thought this a very curious thing, and she went nearer to watch them, and just as

01:44:57.616 --> 01:44:59.636
she came up to them she heard one of them say,

01:44:59.916 --> 01:45:03.556
Look out now, five, don't go splashing paint all over me like that.

01:45:04.116 --> 01:45:07.096
I couldn't help it, said five in a sulky tone.

01:45:07.516 --> 01:45:08.816
Seven jogged my elbow.

01:45:09.576 --> 01:45:11.096
On which seven looked up and said,

01:45:11.376 --> 01:45:13.936
That's right, five, always lay the blame on others.

01:45:14.856 --> 01:45:16.936
You'd better not talk, said five.

01:45:17.496 --> 01:45:21.136
I heard the Queen say only yesterday you deserve to be beheaded.

01:45:21.956 --> 01:45:25.256
What for? said the one who had spoken first.

01:45:25.976 --> 01:45:28.616
That's none of your business, too, said seven.

01:45:29.496 --> 01:45:35.296
Yes, it is his business, said five, and I'll tell him it was for bringing the cook tulip

01:45:35.296 --> 01:45:36.696
roots instead of onions.

01:45:37.536 --> 01:45:40.336
Seven flung down his brush and had just begun,

01:45:40.836 --> 01:45:43.436
Well, of all the unjust things!

01:45:43.856 --> 01:45:48.476
When his eye chanced to fall upon Alice as she stood watching them, and he checked himself

01:45:48.476 --> 01:45:48.996
suddenly.

01:45:48.996 --> 01:45:52.476
The others looked round also, and all of them bowed low.

01:45:53.516 --> 01:45:56.656
Would you tell me, said Alice a little timidly,

01:45:56.996 --> 01:45:58.616
Why are you painting those roses?

01:46:00.236 --> 01:46:02.676
Five and seven said nothing, but looked at two.

01:46:03.316 --> 01:46:04.996
Two began in a low voice.

01:46:05.756 --> 01:46:11.556
Why, the fact is, you see, Miss, this here ought to have been a red rose tree,

01:46:11.856 --> 01:46:15.676
and we put a white one in by mistake, and if the Queen was to find out,

01:46:15.816 --> 01:46:17.956
we should all have our heads cut off, you know.

01:46:17.956 --> 01:46:21.486
So you see, Miss, we're doing our best before she comes to—

01:46:22.156 --> 01:46:26.136
At this moment, five, who had been anxiously looking across the garden,

01:46:26.496 --> 01:46:28.336
called out, The Queen! The Queen!

01:46:28.876 --> 01:46:32.656
And the three gardeners instantly threw themselves flat upon their faces.

01:46:33.496 --> 01:46:37.776
There was a sound of many footsteps, and Alice looked round, eager to see the Queen.

01:46:39.496 --> 01:46:41.876
First came ten soldiers carrying clubs.

01:46:42.316 --> 01:46:45.476
They were all shaped like the three gardeners, oblong and flat,

01:46:45.596 --> 01:46:47.116
with their hands and feet at the corners.

01:46:47.756 --> 01:46:49.356
Next the ten courtiers.

01:46:49.656 --> 01:46:51.656
These were ornamented all over with diamonds,

01:46:51.956 --> 01:46:54.296
and walked two and two, as the soldiers did.

01:46:54.956 --> 01:46:56.776
After these came the royal children.

01:46:57.036 --> 01:47:00.456
There were ten of them, and the little deers came jumping merrily along,

01:47:00.536 --> 01:47:01.756
hand in hand, in couples.

01:47:02.236 --> 01:47:03.936
They were all ornamented with hearts.

01:47:04.576 --> 01:47:07.276
Next came the guests, mostly kings and queens,

01:47:07.496 --> 01:47:09.876
and among them Alice recognized the white rabbit.

01:47:10.156 --> 01:47:12.256
It was talking in a hurried, nervous manner,

01:47:12.516 --> 01:47:16.256
smiling at everything that was said, and went by without noticing her.

01:47:17.116 --> 01:47:21.776
Then followed the knave of hearts, carrying the king's crown on a crimson velvet cushion,

01:47:22.156 --> 01:47:25.876
and last of all this grand procession came the king and queen of hearts.

01:47:27.216 --> 01:47:31.396
Alice was rather doubtful whether she ought not lie down on her face like the three gardeners,

01:47:31.596 --> 01:47:34.916
but she could not remember ever having heard of such a rule at processions.

01:47:35.316 --> 01:47:38.496
And besides, what would be the use of a procession, thought she,

01:47:38.676 --> 01:47:42.056
if people all had to lie down upon their faces so they couldn't see it?

01:47:42.656 --> 01:47:45.176
So she stood still where she was, and waited.

01:47:46.316 --> 01:47:49.896
When the procession came opposite to Alice, they all stopped and looked at her,

01:47:49.956 --> 01:47:51.176
and the queen said severely,

01:47:51.596 --> 01:47:52.776
Who is this?

01:47:53.456 --> 01:47:56.816
She said it to the knave of hearts, who only bowed and smiled in reply.

01:47:57.756 --> 01:48:00.736
Idiot, said the queen, tossing her head impatiently,

01:48:00.956 --> 01:48:02.396
and turning to Alice, she went on,

01:48:02.556 --> 01:48:03.556
What's your name, child?

01:48:04.616 --> 01:48:08.456
My name is Alice, so please your majesty, said Alice very politely,

01:48:08.676 --> 01:48:09.936
but she added to herself,

01:48:10.196 --> 01:48:13.236
Why, they're only a pack of cards after all, I needn't be afraid of them.

01:48:13.956 --> 01:48:14.936
And who are these?

01:48:15.176 --> 01:48:19.536
said the queen, pointing to the three gardeners who were lying round the rose tree,

01:48:19.876 --> 01:48:22.036
for, you see, as they were all lying on their faces,

01:48:22.156 --> 01:48:24.756
and the pattern on their backs was the same as the rest of the pack,

01:48:25.076 --> 01:48:27.876
she could not tell whether they were gardeners, or soldiers,

01:48:28.036 --> 01:48:29.856
or courtiers, or three of her own children.

01:48:30.856 --> 01:48:34.336
How should I know? said Alice, surprised at her own courage.

01:48:34.656 --> 01:48:35.816
It's no business of mine.

01:48:37.056 --> 01:48:38.976
The queen turned crimson with fury,

01:48:39.296 --> 01:48:42.116
and after glaring at her for a moment like a wild beast,

01:48:42.416 --> 01:48:43.996
screamed, Off with her head, off!

01:48:44.876 --> 01:48:49.316
Nonsense! said Alice, very loudly and decidedly, and the queen was silent.

01:48:50.096 --> 01:48:53.036
The king laid his hand upon her arm, and timidly said,

01:48:53.516 --> 01:48:55.836
Consider, my dear, she is only a child.

01:48:56.876 --> 01:48:59.836
The queen turned angrily away from him, and said to the knave,

01:49:00.016 --> 01:49:00.776
Turn them over!

01:49:01.516 --> 01:49:04.616
The knave did so very carefully, with one foot.

01:49:05.736 --> 01:49:08.996
Get up! said the queen, in a shrill, loud voice,

01:49:09.216 --> 01:49:11.296
and the three gardeners instantly jumped up,

01:49:11.296 --> 01:49:14.916
and began bowing to the king, the queen, the royal children, and everybody else.

01:49:15.576 --> 01:49:17.556
Leave off that! screamed the queen.

01:49:17.796 --> 01:49:18.956
You make me giddy!

01:49:19.296 --> 01:49:21.996
And then, turning to the rose tree, she went on,

01:49:22.156 --> 01:49:23.736
What have you been doing here?

01:49:24.356 --> 01:49:27.776
May it please your majesty? said two, in a very humble tone,

01:49:27.836 --> 01:49:29.536
going down on one knee as he spoke.

01:49:30.216 --> 01:49:30.936
We were trying.

01:49:31.556 --> 01:49:35.556
I see! said the queen, who had meanwhile been examining the roses.

01:49:36.116 --> 01:49:36.896
Off with their heads!

01:49:37.496 --> 01:49:40.576
And the procession moved on, three of the soldiers remaining behind

01:49:40.576 --> 01:49:44.316
to execute the unfortunate gardeners, who ran to Alice for protection.

01:49:45.176 --> 01:49:47.196
You shan't be beheaded! said Alice,

01:49:47.216 --> 01:49:49.716
and she put them into a large flower pot that stood near.

01:49:50.256 --> 01:49:53.336
The three soldiers wandered about for a minute or two looking for them,

01:49:53.416 --> 01:49:55.616
and then quietly marched off after the others.

01:49:56.696 --> 01:49:58.796
Are their heads off? shouted the queen.

01:49:59.656 --> 01:50:01.476
Their heads are gone, if it please your majesty!

01:50:01.716 --> 01:50:03.236
The soldiers shouted in reply.

01:50:03.996 --> 01:50:05.796
That's right! shouted the queen.

01:50:06.356 --> 01:50:07.256
Can you play croquet?

01:50:07.756 --> 01:50:10.116
The soldiers were silent and looked at Alice,

01:50:10.216 --> 01:50:12.256
as the question was evidently meant for her.

01:50:12.976 --> 01:50:14.576
Yes! shouted Alice.

01:50:14.856 --> 01:50:18.196
Come on, then! roared the queen, and Alice joined the procession,

01:50:18.456 --> 01:50:20.396
wondering very much what would happen next.

01:50:21.476 --> 01:50:24.816
It's a very fine day! said a timid voice at her side.

01:50:25.356 --> 01:50:29.176
She was walking by the white rabbit, who was peeping anxiously into her face.

01:50:29.896 --> 01:50:31.236
Very! said Alice.

01:50:31.276 --> 01:50:32.176
Where's the Duchess?

01:50:33.376 --> 01:50:35.776
said the rabbit, in a low, hurried tone.

01:50:35.776 --> 01:50:38.456
He looked anxiously over his shoulder as he spoke,

01:50:38.736 --> 01:50:41.796
and then raised himself upon tiptoe, put his mouth close to her ear,

01:50:41.896 --> 01:50:44.756
and whispered, She's under sentence of execution.

01:50:45.996 --> 01:50:47.436
What for? said Alice.

01:50:48.176 --> 01:50:51.076
Did you say, What a pity? the rabbit asked.

01:50:51.756 --> 01:50:53.296
No, I didn't! said Alice.

01:50:53.416 --> 01:50:54.536
I don't think it's at all a pity.

01:50:54.916 --> 01:50:56.116
I said, What for?

01:50:56.856 --> 01:50:58.476
She boxed the queen's ears!

01:50:59.016 --> 01:50:59.996
The rabbit began.

01:51:00.716 --> 01:51:02.476
Alice gave a little scream of laughter.

01:51:02.936 --> 01:51:05.756
Oh, hush! the rabbit whispered in a frightened tone.

01:51:05.776 --> 01:51:07.316
The queen will hear you!

01:51:07.516 --> 01:51:10.276
You see, she came rather late, and the queen said,

01:51:10.596 --> 01:51:14.056
Get to your places! shouted the queen in a voice of thunder,

01:51:14.516 --> 01:51:18.496
and people began running about in all directions, tumbling up against each other.

01:51:18.836 --> 01:51:21.876
However, they got settled down in a minute or two, and the game began.

01:51:23.576 --> 01:51:26.636
Alice thought she'd never seen such a curious croquet ground in her life.

01:51:26.816 --> 01:51:28.396
It was all ridges and furrows.

01:51:28.696 --> 01:51:31.596
The balls were live hedgehogs, the mallets live flamingos,

01:51:31.716 --> 01:51:33.696
and the soldiers had to double themselves up

01:51:33.696 --> 01:51:36.116
and to stand on their hands and feet to make the arches.

01:51:36.856 --> 01:51:40.656
The chief difficulty Alice found at first was in managing her flamingo.

01:51:40.876 --> 01:51:44.476
She succeeded in getting its body tucked away comfortably enough under her arm,

01:51:44.516 --> 01:51:45.696
with its legs hanging down.

01:51:45.996 --> 01:51:49.276
But generally, just as she got its neck nicely straightened out,

01:51:49.356 --> 01:51:51.336
and was going to give the hedgehog a blow with its head,

01:51:51.376 --> 01:51:54.076
it would twist itself round and look up in her face,

01:51:54.336 --> 01:51:58.056
with such a puzzled expression that she could not help bursting out laughing.

01:51:58.316 --> 01:52:01.476
And when she got its head down, and she was going to begin again,

01:52:01.476 --> 01:52:04.676
it was very provoking to find that the hedgehog had unrolled itself

01:52:04.676 --> 01:52:06.396
and was in the act of crawling away.

01:52:07.056 --> 01:52:09.836
Besides all this, there was generally a ridge or furrow in the way

01:52:09.836 --> 01:52:11.916
wherever she wanted to send the hedgehog to.

01:52:12.156 --> 01:52:14.356
And as the doubled-up soldiers were always getting up

01:52:14.356 --> 01:52:16.176
and walking off to other parts of the ground,

01:52:16.876 --> 01:52:20.316
Alice soon came to the conclusion that it was a very difficult game indeed.

01:52:21.176 --> 01:52:23.876
The players all played at once, without waiting for turns,

01:52:24.216 --> 01:52:27.396
quarreling all the while, and fighting for the hedgehogs.

01:52:27.396 --> 01:52:30.496
And in a very short time, the queen was in a furious fashion,

01:52:30.496 --> 01:52:32.396
and went stamping about and shouting,

01:52:32.596 --> 01:52:36.076
off with his head, off with her head, about once in a minute.

01:52:37.136 --> 01:52:38.796
Alice began to feel very uneasy.

01:52:39.116 --> 01:52:41.956
To be sure, she had not as yet had any dispute with the queen,

01:52:42.396 --> 01:52:45.756
but she knew that it might happen any minute, and then, thought she,

01:52:46.116 --> 01:52:47.176
what would become of me?

01:52:47.216 --> 01:52:49.216
They're dreadfully fond of beheading people here.

01:52:49.476 --> 01:52:51.776
The great wonder is that there's anyone left alive.

01:52:52.516 --> 01:52:54.856
She was looking about for some way of escape,

01:52:54.936 --> 01:52:57.536
and wondering whether she could get away without being seen,

01:52:57.856 --> 01:53:00.076
when she noticed a curious appearance in the air.

01:53:00.076 --> 01:53:04.156
It puzzled her very much at first, but after watching it a minute or two,

01:53:04.296 --> 01:53:06.936
she made it out to be a grin, and she said to herself,

01:53:07.476 --> 01:53:08.716
it's the Cheshire Cat.

01:53:09.056 --> 01:53:10.776
Now I shall have somebody to talk to.

01:53:11.176 --> 01:53:13.096
How are you getting on? said the cat,

01:53:13.256 --> 01:53:15.376
as soon as there was mouth enough for it to speak with.

01:53:16.216 --> 01:53:18.816
Alice waited till the eyes appeared, and then nodded.

01:53:19.596 --> 01:53:21.376
It's no use speaking to it, she thought,

01:53:21.416 --> 01:53:23.616
till its years have come, or at least one of them.

01:53:24.216 --> 01:53:26.096
In another minute, the whole head appeared,

01:53:26.416 --> 01:53:29.656
and then Alice put down her flamingo, and began an account of the game,

01:53:29.656 --> 01:53:32.556
feeling very glad she had someone to listen to her.

01:53:33.216 --> 01:53:35.756
The cat seemed to think that there was enough of it now in sight,

01:53:35.916 --> 01:53:37.016
and no more of it appeared.

01:53:38.136 --> 01:53:41.056
I don't think they play at all fairly, Alice began,

01:53:41.236 --> 01:53:42.716
in rather a complaining tone.

01:53:43.136 --> 01:53:46.256
And they all quarrel so dreadfully one can't hear oneself speak.

01:53:46.556 --> 01:53:48.836
And they don't seem to have any rules in particular,

01:53:49.176 --> 01:53:51.476
at least if there are, nobody attends to them.

01:53:51.796 --> 01:53:55.596
And you have no idea how confusing it is, all the things being alive.

01:53:55.896 --> 01:53:58.776
For instance, there's the arch I've got to go through next,

01:53:58.776 --> 01:54:00.736
walking about at the other end of the ground.

01:54:00.936 --> 01:54:03.156
And I should have crocaded the queen's hedgehog just now,

01:54:03.156 --> 01:54:05.176
only it ran away when it saw mine coming.

01:54:06.096 --> 01:54:09.556
How do you like the queen? said the cat in a low voice.

01:54:10.536 --> 01:54:12.616
Not at all, said Alice.

01:54:12.996 --> 01:54:14.616
She's so extremely.

01:54:15.296 --> 01:54:18.436
Just then she noticed that the queen was close behind her, listening,

01:54:18.776 --> 01:54:20.976
so she went on, likely to win,

01:54:21.256 --> 01:54:23.436
that it's hardly worthwhile finishing the game.

01:54:24.296 --> 01:54:26.356
The queen smiled and passed on.

01:54:26.356 --> 01:54:29.256
Who are you talking to? said the king,

01:54:29.336 --> 01:54:32.496
going up to Alice and looking at the cat's head with great curiosity.

01:54:33.596 --> 01:54:36.176
It's a friend of mine, a Cheshire cat, said Alice.

01:54:36.236 --> 01:54:37.716
Allow me to introduce it.

01:54:38.316 --> 01:54:40.556
I don't like the look of it at all, said the king.

01:54:40.916 --> 01:54:42.916
However, it may kiss my hand if it likes.

01:54:43.776 --> 01:54:46.256
And rather not, the cat remarked.

01:54:46.396 --> 01:54:48.376
Don't be impertinent, said the king.

01:54:48.596 --> 01:54:52.196
And don't look at me like that, he got behind Alice as he spoke.

01:54:52.916 --> 01:54:55.056
A cat may look at a king, said Alice.

01:54:55.056 --> 01:54:58.016
I've read that in some book, but I don't remember where.

01:54:58.936 --> 01:55:02.176
Well, it must be removed, said the king very decidedly,

01:55:02.256 --> 01:55:04.376
and he called the queen, who was passing at the moment.

01:55:04.796 --> 01:55:07.116
My dear, I wish you would have this cat removed.

01:55:08.196 --> 01:55:11.476
The queen had only one way of settling all difficulties, great or small.

01:55:11.796 --> 01:55:14.656
Off with his head, she said, without even looking round.

01:55:15.316 --> 01:55:19.516
I'll fetch the executioner myself, said the king eagerly, and he hurried off.

01:55:21.156 --> 01:55:24.296
Alice thought she might as well go back and see how the game was going on,

01:55:24.296 --> 01:55:27.316
as she heard the queen's voice in the distance screaming with passion.

01:55:27.776 --> 01:55:30.656
She'd already heard her sentence three of the players to be executed

01:55:30.656 --> 01:55:33.996
for having missed their turns, and she did not like the look of things at all,

01:55:34.056 --> 01:55:37.616
as the game was in such confusion that she never knew whether it was her turn or not.

01:55:37.956 --> 01:55:39.596
So she went in search of her hedgehog.

01:55:40.216 --> 01:55:42.756
The hedgehog was engaged in a fight with another hedgehog,

01:55:42.956 --> 01:55:46.716
which seemed to Alice an excellent opportunity for croqueting one of them with the other.

01:55:46.936 --> 01:55:50.896
The only difficulty was that her flamingo was gone across to the other side of the garden,

01:55:50.896 --> 01:55:54.736
where Alice could see it trying in a helpless sort of way to fly up into a tree.

01:55:55.576 --> 01:55:58.016
By the time she had caught the flamingo and brought it back,

01:55:58.156 --> 01:56:00.676
the fight was over and both the hedgehogs were out of sight.

01:56:01.456 --> 01:56:06.016
But it doesn't matter much, thought Alice, as all the arches are gone from this side of the ground.

01:56:06.496 --> 01:56:09.336
So she tucked it away under her arm that it might not escape again,

01:56:09.556 --> 01:56:11.996
and went back for a little more conversation with her friend.

01:56:12.896 --> 01:56:16.736
When she got back to the Cheshire Cat, she was surprised to find quite a large crowd

01:56:16.736 --> 01:56:17.796
collected around it.

01:56:18.036 --> 01:56:21.436
There was a dispute going on between the executioner, the king, and the queen,

01:56:21.696 --> 01:56:26.116
who were all talking at once, while all the rest were quite silent and looked very uncomfortable.

01:56:27.096 --> 01:56:31.116
The moment Alice appeared, she was appealed to by all three to settle the question,

01:56:31.296 --> 01:56:34.756
and they repeated their arguments to her, though as they all spoke at once,

01:56:34.836 --> 01:56:37.716
she found it very hard indeed to make out exactly what they said.

01:56:38.316 --> 01:56:43.316
The executioner's argument was you couldn't cut off a head unless there was a body to cut it off from.

01:56:43.316 --> 01:56:48.376
That he had never had to do such a thing before, and he wasn't going to begin at his time of life.

01:56:48.996 --> 01:56:52.756
The king's argument was that anything that had a head could be beheaded,

01:56:52.816 --> 01:56:54.456
and that you weren't to talk nonsense.

01:56:55.376 --> 01:56:59.316
The queen's argument was that if something wasn't done about it in less than no time,

01:56:59.396 --> 01:57:01.696
she had everybody executed all around.

01:57:02.536 --> 01:57:05.876
It was this last remark that had made the whole party look so grave and anxious.

01:57:07.096 --> 01:57:09.496
Alice could think of nothing else to say, but

01:57:09.496 --> 01:57:12.676
it belongs to the duchess, you better ask her about it.

01:57:12.676 --> 01:57:15.916
She's in prison, the queen said to the executioner.

01:57:16.076 --> 01:57:16.856
Fetch her here.

01:57:17.116 --> 01:57:19.136
And the executioner went off like an arrow.

01:57:19.836 --> 01:57:22.616
The cat's head began fading away the moment he was gone,

01:57:22.656 --> 01:57:26.396
and by the time he had come back with the duchess, it had entirely disappeared.

01:57:26.696 --> 01:57:30.816
So the king and the executioner ran wildly up and down looking for it,

01:57:30.836 --> 01:57:33.176
while the rest of the party went back to the game.

01:58:07.928 --> 01:58:09.668
THE MOCK TURTLE'S STORY

01:58:10.588 --> 01:58:22.188
"'You can't think how glad I am to see you again, you dear old thing,' said the Duchess, as she tucked her arm affectionately into Alice's, and they walked off together.

01:58:23.688 --> 01:58:33.608
Alice was very glad to find her in such a pleasant temper, and thought to herself that perhaps it was only the pepper that had made her so savage when they met in the kitchen.

01:58:34.328 --> 01:58:43.888
When I'm a Duchess—she said to herself, not in a very hopeful tone, though—I won't have any pepper in my kitchen at all.

01:58:44.418 --> 01:59:05.048
Soup does very well without—maybe it's always pepper that makes people hot-tempered—she went on, very much pleased at having found out a new kind of rule—and vinegar that makes them sour, and chamomile that makes them bitter, and barley-sugar and such things that make children sweet-tempered.

01:59:05.448 --> 01:59:10.928
I only wish people knew that. Then they wouldn't be so stingy about it, you know.'

01:59:10.928 --> 01:59:18.028
She had quite forgotten the Duchess by this time, and was a little startled when she heard her voice close to her ear.

01:59:18.708 --> 01:59:27.768
"'You're thinking about something, my dear, and that makes you forget to talk. I can't tell you just now what the moral of that is, but I shall remember it in a bit.'

01:59:28.708 --> 01:59:31.988
"'Perhaps it hasn't one,' Alice ventured to remark.

01:59:32.808 --> 01:59:38.948
"'Ta-ta, child,' said the Duchess. Everything's got a moral. If only you can find it.'

01:59:38.948 --> 01:59:42.948
And she squeezed herself up closer to Alice's side as she spoke.

01:59:43.968 --> 02:00:02.008
Alice did not much like keeping so close to her—first, because the Duchess was very ugly, and secondly, because she was exactly the right height to rest her chin upon Alice's shoulder, and it was an uncomfortably sharp chin. However, she did not like to be rude, so she bored as well as she could.

02:00:02.868 --> 02:00:08.908
"'The game's going on rather better now,' she said, by way of keeping up the conversation a little.

02:00:08.908 --> 02:00:17.928
"'Tis so,' said the Duchess. And the moral of that is—'Oh, tis love, tis love that makes the world go round.'

02:00:17.928 --> 02:00:20.688
"'Somebody said,' Alice whispered,

02:00:20.748 --> 02:00:25.028
"'that it's done by everybody minding their own business.'

02:00:25.028 --> 02:00:33.488
"'Ah, well, it means much the same thing,' said the Duchess, digging her sharp little chin into Alice's shoulder as she added,

02:00:33.488 --> 02:00:40.448
"'and the moral of that is, take care of the sense, and the sounds will take care of themselves.'

02:00:40.448 --> 02:00:45.228
"'How fun she is at finding morals in things,' Alice thought to herself.

02:00:46.148 --> 02:00:52.128
"'I dare say you're wondering why I don't put my arm round your waist,' the Duchess said after a pause.

02:00:52.448 --> 02:00:58.328
"'The reason is that I'm doubtful about the temper of your flamingo. Shall I try the experiment?'

02:00:59.688 --> 02:01:07.348
"'He might bite,' Alice cautiously replied, not feeling at all anxious to have the experiment tried.

02:01:08.028 --> 02:01:16.748
"'Very true,' said the Duchess. Flamingos and mustard both bite, and the moral of that is, birds of a feather flock together.

02:01:17.388 --> 02:01:21.588
"'Only mustard isn't a bird,' Alice remarked.

02:01:21.688 --> 02:01:26.728
"'Right as usual,' said the Duchess. What a clear way you have of putting things.

02:01:27.488 --> 02:01:30.208
"'It's a mineral, I think,' said Alice.

02:01:30.928 --> 02:01:35.988
"'Of course it is,' said the Duchess, who seemed ready to agree to everything that Alice said.

02:01:36.348 --> 02:01:44.768
"'There's a large mustard mine near here, and the moral of that is, the more there is of mine, the less there is of yours.'

02:01:44.768 --> 02:01:50.108
"'Oh, I know,' exclaimed Alice, who had not attended to this last remark.

02:01:50.408 --> 02:01:54.948
"'It's a vegetable. It doesn't look like one, but it is.'

02:01:54.948 --> 02:02:02.368
"'I quite agree with you,' said the Duchess. And the moral of that is, be what you would seem to be.

02:02:02.848 --> 02:02:17.788
"'Or, if you'd like it put more simply, never imagine yourself not to be otherwise than what it might appear to others that what you were or might have been was not otherwise than what you had been would have appeared to them to be otherwise.'

02:02:19.668 --> 02:02:25.448
"'I think I should understand that better,' Alice said very politely.

02:02:25.868 --> 02:02:31.308
"'If I had it written down. But I can't quite follow it as you say it.'

02:02:31.308 --> 02:02:37.168
"'That's nothing to what I could say if I chose,' the Duchess replied, in a pleased tone.

02:02:37.668 --> 02:02:42.188
"'Pray, don't trouble yourself to say it any longer than that,' said Alice.

02:02:42.208 --> 02:02:45.128
"'Oh, don't talk about trouble,' said the Duchess.

02:02:45.128 --> 02:02:47.968
"'I make you a present of everything I've said as yet.'

02:02:48.548 --> 02:02:50.948
"'A cheap sort of present,' thought Alice.

02:02:51.228 --> 02:02:54.088
"'I'm glad they don't give birthday presents like that.'

02:02:54.088 --> 02:02:56.628
But she did not venture to say it out loud.

02:02:57.688 --> 02:03:02.288
"'Thinking again?' the Duchess asked, with another dig of her sharp little chin.

02:03:02.848 --> 02:03:08.508
"'I've a right to think,' said Alice sharply, for she was beginning to feel a little worried.

02:03:08.788 --> 02:03:13.148
"'Just about as much right,' said the Duchess, as pigs have to fly.

02:03:13.868 --> 02:03:15.428
"'And the moral...'

02:03:15.888 --> 02:03:20.108
"'But here, to Alice's great surprise, the Duchess's voice died away,

02:03:20.308 --> 02:03:22.968
"'even in the middle of her favorite word, moral.

02:03:23.008 --> 02:03:26.188
"'And the arm that was linked into hers began to tremble.

02:03:26.508 --> 02:03:29.908
"'Alice looked up, and there stood the Queen in front of them,

02:03:29.908 --> 02:03:33.008
"'with her arms folded, frowning like a thunderstorm.

02:03:33.808 --> 02:03:39.608
"'A fine day, Your Majesty,' the Duchess began in a low, weak voice.

02:03:40.308 --> 02:03:46.588
"'Now I give you fair warning,' shouted the Queen, stamping on the ground as she spoke.

02:03:47.048 --> 02:03:51.988
"'Either you or your head must be off, and that in about half no time.

02:03:52.428 --> 02:03:53.988
"'Take your choice!'

02:03:53.988 --> 02:03:57.068
The Duchess took her choice and was gone in a moment.

02:03:57.208 --> 02:04:00.808
"'Let's go on with the game,' the Queen said to Alice.

02:04:01.448 --> 02:04:04.088
"'And Alice was too much frightened to say a word,

02:04:04.248 --> 02:04:06.868
"'but slowly followed her back to the croquet ground.

02:04:07.628 --> 02:04:11.248
"'The other guests had taken advantage of the Queen's absence

02:04:11.248 --> 02:04:12.908
"'and were resting in the shade.

02:04:13.388 --> 02:04:16.728
"'However, the moment they saw her, they hurried back to the game,

02:04:16.728 --> 02:04:20.948
"'the Queen merely remarking that a moment's delay would cost them their lives.

02:04:21.888 --> 02:04:25.348
"'All the time they were playing, the Queen never left off quarreling

02:04:25.348 --> 02:04:27.048
"'with the other players and shouting,

02:04:27.168 --> 02:04:29.088
"'Off with his head!' or,

02:04:29.268 --> 02:04:31.168
"'Off with her head!'

02:04:31.168 --> 02:04:34.648
"'Those whom she sentenced were taken into custody by the soldiers,

02:04:34.648 --> 02:04:38.528
"'who, of course, had to leave off being archers to do this,

02:04:38.528 --> 02:04:42.328
"'so that by the end of half an hour or so there were no archers left,

02:04:42.328 --> 02:04:46.268
"'and all the players except the King, the Queen, and Alice

02:04:46.268 --> 02:04:49.488
"'were in custody and under sentence of execution.'

02:04:50.088 --> 02:04:54.248
"'Then the Queen left off, quite out of breath, and said to Alice,

02:04:54.548 --> 02:04:56.868
"'Have you seen the mock turtle yet?'

02:04:56.868 --> 02:04:58.548
"'No,' said Alice.

02:04:58.848 --> 02:05:01.548
"'I don't even know what a mock turtle is.

02:05:01.968 --> 02:05:04.568
"'It's the thing mock turtle soup is made from.

02:05:05.868 --> 02:05:09.328
"'I never saw one or heard of one,' said Alice.

02:05:09.868 --> 02:05:11.988
"'Come on, then,' said the Queen,

02:05:12.248 --> 02:05:14.388
"'and he shall tell you his history.'

02:05:14.388 --> 02:05:18.028
"'As they walked off together, Alice heard the King say in a low voice

02:05:18.028 --> 02:05:19.268
"'to the company generally,

02:05:19.268 --> 02:05:21.348
"'You are all pardoned.'

02:05:21.348 --> 02:05:24.328
"'Come, that's a good thing,' she said to herself,

02:05:24.588 --> 02:05:27.708
"'for she had felt quite unhappy at the number of executions

02:05:27.708 --> 02:05:28.688
"'the Queen had ordered.

02:05:29.428 --> 02:05:33.908
"'They very soon came upon a griffin lying fast asleep in the sun,

02:05:33.908 --> 02:05:37.828
"'if you don't know what a griffin is, look at the picture.'

02:05:37.828 --> 02:05:40.148
"'Up, lazy thing,' said the Queen,

02:05:40.388 --> 02:05:42.768
"'and take this young lady to see the mock turtle

02:05:42.768 --> 02:05:44.188
"'and to hear his history.

02:05:44.648 --> 02:05:48.768
"'I must go back and see after some executions I have ordered.'

02:05:48.768 --> 02:05:51.868
"'And she walked off, leaving Alice alone with the griffin.

02:05:52.048 --> 02:05:54.588
"'Alice did not quite like the look of the creature,

02:05:54.628 --> 02:05:57.288
"'but on the whole she thought it would be quite as safe

02:05:57.288 --> 02:06:00.408
"'to stay with it as to go after that savage Queen.

02:06:00.668 --> 02:06:01.788
"'So she waited.

02:06:02.788 --> 02:06:05.108
"'The griffin sat up and rubbed its eyes.

02:06:05.308 --> 02:06:07.748
"'Then it watched the Queen till she was out of sight.

02:06:08.108 --> 02:06:09.128
"'Then it chuckled.

02:06:09.428 --> 02:06:12.808
"'What fun,' said the griffin, half to itself, half to Alice.

02:06:13.088 --> 02:06:15.448
"'What is the fun?' said Alice.

02:06:16.168 --> 02:06:18.068
"'Why, she,' said the griffin.

02:06:18.168 --> 02:06:19.568
"'It's all her fancy, that.

02:06:19.748 --> 02:06:21.808
"'They never execute nobody, you know.

02:06:22.108 --> 02:06:23.728
"'Come on.'

02:06:23.728 --> 02:06:26.568
"'Everybody says come on here,' thought Alice,

02:06:26.728 --> 02:06:28.408
"'as she went slowly after it.

02:06:28.408 --> 02:06:31.208
"'I never was so ordered about in all my life.

02:06:31.208 --> 02:06:31.668
"'Never.

02:06:32.148 --> 02:06:34.848
"'They had not gone far before they saw the Mock Turtle

02:06:34.848 --> 02:06:37.148
"'in the distance, sitting sad and lonely

02:06:37.148 --> 02:06:38.408
"'on a little ledge of rock.

02:06:38.648 --> 02:06:41.688
"'And as they came nearer, Alice could hear him

02:06:41.688 --> 02:06:43.568
"'sighing as if his heart would break.

02:06:43.828 --> 02:06:45.448
"'She pitied him deeply.

02:06:46.028 --> 02:06:49.208
"'What is his sorrow?' she asked the griffin.

02:06:49.208 --> 02:06:51.348
"'And the griffin answered, very nearly

02:06:51.348 --> 02:06:52.968
"'in the same words as before.

02:06:53.488 --> 02:06:55.188
"'It's all his fancy, that.

02:06:55.328 --> 02:06:57.408
"'He hasn't got no sorrow, you know.

02:06:57.688 --> 02:06:59.488
"'Come on.'

02:06:59.488 --> 02:07:01.248
"'So they went up to the Mock Turtle,

02:07:01.308 --> 02:07:03.528
"'who looked at them with large eyes

02:07:03.528 --> 02:07:05.908
"'full of tears, but said nothing.

02:07:06.688 --> 02:07:09.328
"'This here young lady,' said the griffin,

02:07:09.328 --> 02:07:11.748
"'she wants for to know your history, she do.

02:07:12.588 --> 02:07:15.348
"'I'll tell it her,' said the Mock Turtle

02:07:15.348 --> 02:07:16.908
"'in a deep hollow tone.

02:07:17.048 --> 02:07:18.768
"'Sit down, both of you,

02:07:18.768 --> 02:07:21.448
"'and don't speak a word till I've finished.'

02:07:21.448 --> 02:07:22.688
"'So they sat down,

02:07:22.728 --> 02:07:24.528
"'and nobody spoke for some minutes.

02:07:24.928 --> 02:07:26.168
"'Alice thought to herself,

02:07:26.188 --> 02:07:28.348
"'I don't see how he can even finish

02:07:28.348 --> 02:07:29.408
"'if he doesn't begin.

02:07:29.408 --> 02:07:31.148
"'But she waited patiently.

02:07:31.968 --> 02:07:33.508
"'Once,' said the Mock Turtle

02:07:33.508 --> 02:07:35.408
"'at last, with a deep sigh,

02:07:35.428 --> 02:07:37.468
"'I was a real turtle.

02:07:38.488 --> 02:07:39.988
"'These words were followed

02:07:39.988 --> 02:07:41.468
"'by a very long silence

02:07:41.468 --> 02:07:43.458
"'broken only by an occasional exclamation

02:07:43.968 --> 02:07:46.248
"'of her from the griffin

02:07:46.248 --> 02:07:48.228
"'and the constant heavy sobbing

02:07:48.228 --> 02:07:49.188
"'of the Mock Turtle.

02:07:49.468 --> 02:07:51.628
"'Alice was very nearly getting up

02:07:51.628 --> 02:07:53.628
"'and saying, thank you, sir,

02:07:53.628 --> 02:07:55.558
"'for your interesting story.

02:07:56.588 --> 02:07:58.268
"'But she could not help thinking

02:07:58.268 --> 02:07:59.808
"'there must be more to come,

02:07:59.808 --> 02:08:02.228
"'so she sat still and said nothing.

02:08:03.548 --> 02:08:05.048
"'When we were little,'

02:08:05.048 --> 02:08:07.088
"'the Mock Turtle went on at last,

02:08:07.188 --> 02:08:09.228
"'more calmly, though still sobbing

02:08:09.228 --> 02:08:10.388
"'a little now and then,

02:08:10.668 --> 02:08:12.968
"'we went to school in the sea.

02:08:13.348 --> 02:08:15.548
"'The master was an old turtle.

02:08:15.808 --> 02:08:18.188
"'We used to call him Tortoise.'

02:08:18.188 --> 02:08:20.088
"'Why did you call him Tortoise

02:08:20.088 --> 02:08:21.328
"'if he wasn't one?'

02:08:21.328 --> 02:08:22.368
"'Alice asked.

02:08:22.768 --> 02:08:24.528
"'We called him Tortoise

02:08:24.528 --> 02:08:26.368
"'because he taught us,'

02:08:26.368 --> 02:08:28.188
"'said the Mock Turtle angrily.

02:08:28.248 --> 02:08:30.308
"'Really, you are very dull.

02:08:30.788 --> 02:08:32.748
"'You ought to be ashamed of yourself

02:08:32.748 --> 02:08:34.468
"'for asking such a simple question,'

02:08:35.268 --> 02:08:36.288
"'added the griffin.

02:08:36.388 --> 02:08:38.048
"'And then they both sat silent

02:08:38.048 --> 02:08:39.548
"'and looked at poor Alice

02:08:39.548 --> 02:08:41.508
"'who felt ready to sink into the earth.

02:08:42.068 --> 02:08:44.548
"'At last the griffin said to the Mock Turtle,

02:08:45.268 --> 02:08:46.748
"'Drive on, old fellow,

02:08:46.788 --> 02:08:48.708
"'don't be all day about it.'

02:08:48.708 --> 02:08:51.428
"'And he went on in these words,

02:08:51.428 --> 02:08:54.388
"'Yes, we went to school in the sea,

02:08:54.388 --> 02:08:55.888
"'though you mayn't believe it.

02:08:55.888 --> 02:08:58.188
"'I never said I didn't,'

02:08:58.188 --> 02:08:59.268
"'interrupted Alice.

02:09:00.288 --> 02:09:02.668
"'You did,' said the Mock Turtle.

02:09:02.948 --> 02:09:04.048
"'Hold your tongue,'

02:09:04.048 --> 02:09:05.088
"'added the griffin,

02:09:05.108 --> 02:09:06.728
"'before Alice could speak again.

02:09:07.108 --> 02:09:08.708
"'The Mock Turtle went on.

02:09:08.708 --> 02:09:11.128
"'We had the best of educations.

02:09:11.168 --> 02:09:13.938
"'In fact, we went to school every day.'

02:09:14.808 --> 02:09:16.788
"'I've been to a day school, too,'

02:09:16.788 --> 02:09:17.408
"'said Alice.

02:09:17.548 --> 02:09:20.348
"'You needn't be so proud as all that.'

02:09:20.348 --> 02:09:21.888
"'With extras?'

02:09:22.428 --> 02:09:23.488
"'asked the Mock Turtle

02:09:23.488 --> 02:09:24.608
"'a little anxiously.

02:09:24.788 --> 02:09:26.028
"'Yes,' said Alice,

02:09:26.128 --> 02:09:28.408
"'we learned French and music.'

02:09:29.748 --> 02:09:31.028
"'And washing?'

02:09:31.028 --> 02:09:32.068
"'said the Mock Turtle.

02:09:32.788 --> 02:09:35.448
"'Certainly not,' said Alice indignantly.

02:09:36.288 --> 02:09:37.768
"'Ah, then yours

02:09:37.768 --> 02:09:39.968
"'wasn't a really good school,'

02:09:39.968 --> 02:09:41.008
"'said the Mock Turtle

02:09:41.008 --> 02:09:42.348
"'in a tone of great relief.

02:09:42.548 --> 02:09:43.968
"'Now at hours,

02:09:44.268 --> 02:09:46.168
"'they had at the end of the bill

02:09:46.168 --> 02:09:48.408
"'French, music,

02:09:48.588 --> 02:09:51.908
"'and washing extra.'

02:09:51.908 --> 02:09:54.188
"'You couldn't have wanted it much,'

02:09:54.188 --> 02:09:56.468
"'said Alice, living at the bottom of the sea.

02:09:57.678 --> 02:09:59.888
"'I couldn't afford to learn it,'

02:09:59.888 --> 02:10:01.728
"'said the Mock Turtle with a sigh.

02:10:01.988 --> 02:10:05.748
"'I only took the regular course.'

02:10:05.748 --> 02:10:07.688
"'What was that?' inquired Alice.

02:10:08.608 --> 02:10:10.808
"'Reeling and writhing, of course,

02:10:10.808 --> 02:10:12.088
"'to begin with,'

02:10:12.088 --> 02:10:13.528
"'the Mock Turtle replied.

02:10:13.828 --> 02:10:15.588
"'And then the different branches

02:10:15.588 --> 02:10:17.828
"'of arithmetic, ambition,

02:10:18.588 --> 02:10:19.288
"'distraction,

02:10:19.288 --> 02:10:21.598
"'uglification, and derision.'

02:10:22.108 --> 02:10:24.088
"'I never heard of

02:10:24.088 --> 02:10:25.148
"'uglification,'

02:10:25.148 --> 02:10:26.608
"'Alice ventured to say.

02:10:26.958 --> 02:10:28.268
"'What is it?'

02:10:28.268 --> 02:10:31.268
"'The Griffin lifted up both its paws in surprise.

02:10:31.568 --> 02:10:32.428
"'What?

02:10:32.708 --> 02:10:34.488
"'Never heard of uglifying?'

02:10:34.488 --> 02:10:35.728
"'It exclaimed.

02:10:35.948 --> 02:10:39.388
"'You know what to beautify is, I suppose.'

02:10:39.388 --> 02:10:40.648
"'Yes,'

02:10:40.648 --> 02:10:41.948
"'said Alice doubtfully.

02:10:41.948 --> 02:10:44.688
"'It means to make

02:10:45.288 --> 02:10:47.148
"'anything prettier.'

02:10:47.148 --> 02:10:49.388
"'Well, then,' the Griffin went on,

02:10:49.388 --> 02:10:51.548
"'if you don't know what to uglify is,

02:10:51.548 --> 02:10:53.148
"'you are a simpleton.'

02:10:54.028 --> 02:10:55.708
"'Alice did not feel encouraged

02:10:55.708 --> 02:10:57.828
"'to ask any more questions about it,

02:10:57.828 --> 02:10:59.368
"'so she turned to the Mock Turtle

02:10:59.368 --> 02:10:59.968
"'and said,

02:11:00.248 --> 02:11:02.288
"'What else had you to learn?'

02:11:03.048 --> 02:11:04.848
"'Well, there was mystery,'

02:11:04.848 --> 02:11:06.388
"'the Mock Turtle replied,

02:11:06.868 --> 02:11:09.088
"'counting off the subjects on his flappers.

02:11:10.248 --> 02:11:11.928
"'Mystery ancient and modern

02:11:11.928 --> 02:11:13.228
"'with seaography,

02:11:13.728 --> 02:11:14.828
"'then drawing.

02:11:14.828 --> 02:11:17.588
"'The Drawling Master was an old

02:11:17.588 --> 02:11:20.048
"'conger eel that used to come once a week.

02:11:20.288 --> 02:11:22.128
"'He taught us drawing,

02:11:22.908 --> 02:11:23.528
"'stretching,

02:11:23.628 --> 02:11:25.058
"'and fainting in coils.'

02:11:25.828 --> 02:11:27.788
"'What was that like?'

02:11:27.788 --> 02:11:28.588
"'said Alice.

02:11:28.768 --> 02:11:31.148
"'Well, I can't show it you myself,'

02:11:31.148 --> 02:11:32.408
"'the Mock Turtle said.

02:11:32.428 --> 02:11:33.408
"'I'm too stiff,

02:11:33.888 --> 02:11:36.068
"'and the Griffin never learned it.'

02:11:36.828 --> 02:11:38.188
"'Hadn't time,' said the Griffin.

02:11:38.288 --> 02:11:40.628
"'I went to the Classics Master, though.

02:11:40.648 --> 02:11:43.088
"'He was an old crab, he was.

02:11:43.088 --> 02:11:45.368
"'I never went to him,'

02:11:45.368 --> 02:11:47.188
"'the Mock Turtle said with a sigh.

02:11:47.328 --> 02:11:49.328
"'He taught laughing and grief,

02:11:49.408 --> 02:11:50.928
"'they used to say.'

02:11:50.928 --> 02:11:53.468
"'So he did, so he did,'

02:11:53.468 --> 02:11:55.468
"'said the Griffin, sighing in his turn,

02:11:55.768 --> 02:11:57.568
"'and both creatures hid their faces

02:11:57.568 --> 02:11:58.408
"'in their paws.

02:12:00.008 --> 02:12:01.988
"'And how many hours a day

02:12:01.988 --> 02:12:03.528
"'did you do lessons?'

02:12:03.528 --> 02:12:05.028
"'said Alice in a hurry

02:12:05.028 --> 02:12:06.088
"'to change the subject.

02:12:06.288 --> 02:12:08.308
"'Ten hours the first day,'

02:12:08.308 --> 02:12:09.388
"'said the Mock Turtle.

02:12:09.388 --> 02:12:11.708
"'Nine the next, and so on.'

02:12:11.708 --> 02:12:13.528
"'What a curious plan!'

02:12:13.528 --> 02:12:14.668
"'exclamed Alice.

02:12:15.468 --> 02:12:17.728
"'That's the reason they're called lessons,'

02:12:17.728 --> 02:12:19.208
"'the Griffin remarked,

02:12:19.208 --> 02:12:21.248
"'because they lesson from day to day.

02:12:21.868 --> 02:12:24.228
"'This was quite a new idea to Alice,

02:12:24.268 --> 02:12:25.608
"'and she thought it over a little

02:12:25.608 --> 02:12:27.268
"'before she made her next remark.

02:12:28.408 --> 02:12:30.108
"'Then the eleventh day

02:12:30.108 --> 02:12:31.808
"'must have been a holiday.'

02:12:31.808 --> 02:12:33.868
"'Of course it was,'

02:12:33.868 --> 02:12:35.008
"'said the Mock Turtle.

02:12:35.588 --> 02:12:37.568
"'And how did you manage on the twelfth?'

02:12:37.568 --> 02:12:39.578
"'Alice went on eagerly.

02:12:40.648 --> 02:12:42.468
"'That's enough about lessons,'

02:12:42.468 --> 02:12:43.508
the Griffin interrupted

02:12:43.508 --> 02:12:45.128
in a very decided tone.

02:12:45.448 --> 02:12:47.698
"'Tell her something about the games now.'

02:13:23.405 --> 02:13:28.025
The Lobster Quadrille.

02:13:29.965 --> 02:13:37.425
The mock turtle sighed deeply and drew the back of one flapper across his eyes.

02:13:37.425 --> 02:13:48.645
He looked at Alice and tried to speak, but for a minute or two, sobs choked his voice.

02:13:50.085 --> 02:14:00.805
Same as if he had a bone in his throat, said the griffon, and it set to work shaking him and punching him in the back.

02:14:00.805 --> 02:14:13.025
At last, the mock turtle recovered his voice, and with tears running down his cheeks, he went on again.

02:14:14.705 --> 02:14:19.525
You may not have lived much under the sea.

02:14:20.805 --> 02:14:22.305
I haven't, said Alice.

02:14:23.805 --> 02:14:29.185
And perhaps you were never even introduced to a lobster.

02:14:30.785 --> 02:14:40.945
Alice began to say, I once tasted, but checked herself hastily and said, no, never.

02:14:42.105 --> 02:14:50.465
So you can have no idea what a delightful thing a lobster quadrille is.

02:14:52.105 --> 02:14:53.765
No, indeed, said Alice.

02:14:54.825 --> 02:14:57.425
What sort of a dance is it?

02:14:58.465 --> 02:15:06.305
Why, said the griffon, you first farm into a line along the seashore.

02:15:07.305 --> 02:15:10.325
Two lines, cried the mock turtle.

02:15:10.845 --> 02:15:15.025
Seals, turtles, salmon, and so on.

02:15:15.525 --> 02:15:20.485
Then, when you've cleared all the jellyfish out of the way.

02:15:22.585 --> 02:15:27.645
That generally takes some time, interrupted the griffon.

02:15:29.285 --> 02:15:30.825
You advanced twice.

02:15:31.905 --> 02:15:36.945
Each with a lobster as a partner, cried the griffon.

02:15:37.925 --> 02:15:44.825
Of course, the mock turtle said, advanced twice, set to partners.

02:15:45.965 --> 02:15:52.085
Change lobsters and retire in the same order, continued the griffon.

02:15:52.945 --> 02:15:56.825
Then, you know, the mock turtle went on.

02:15:56.825 --> 02:16:05.905
You throw the, the lobsters, shouted the griffon with a bound into the air.

02:16:06.445 --> 02:16:10.585
As far out to sea as you can.

02:16:12.265 --> 02:16:16.925
Swim after them, screamed the griffon.

02:16:17.225 --> 02:16:22.485
Turn a somersault in the sea, cried the mock turtle.

02:16:22.485 --> 02:16:25.485
Capering wildly about.

02:16:28.225 --> 02:16:33.045
Change lobsters again, yelled the griffon at the top of his voice.

02:16:33.765 --> 02:16:35.325
Back to land again.

02:16:35.905 --> 02:16:42.465
And that's all the first figure, said the mock turtle, suddenly dropping his voice.

02:16:43.445 --> 02:16:50.445
And the two creatures, who had been jumping about like mad things all this time.

02:16:50.445 --> 02:16:55.345
Sat down again, very sadly and quietly.

02:16:56.565 --> 02:16:58.205
And looked at Alice.

02:17:00.085 --> 02:17:05.665
It must be a very pretty dance, said Alice timidly.

02:17:07.325 --> 02:17:11.965
Would you like to see a little of it? said the mock turtle.

02:17:12.985 --> 02:17:16.705
Very much indeed, said Alice.

02:17:17.705 --> 02:17:24.885
Come, let's try the first figure, said the mock turtle to the griffon.

02:17:25.725 --> 02:17:28.965
We can do without lobsters, you know.

02:17:30.105 --> 02:17:31.625
Which shall sing?

02:17:33.125 --> 02:17:37.525
Oh, you sing, said the griffon.

02:17:38.205 --> 02:17:40.745
I've forgotten the words.

02:17:40.745 --> 02:17:48.225
So they began solemnly dancing around and round Alice.

02:17:49.245 --> 02:17:55.065
Every now and then treading on her toes when they passed too close.

02:17:55.865 --> 02:17:59.805
And waving their forepaws to mark the time.

02:18:00.765 --> 02:18:06.885
While the mock turtle sang this very slowly and sadly.

02:18:08.965 --> 02:18:15.705
Will you walk a little faster? said a whiting to a snail.

02:18:16.885 --> 02:18:19.945
There's a porpoise close behind us.

02:18:20.425 --> 02:18:23.245
And he's treading on my tail.

02:18:24.405 --> 02:18:30.145
See how eagerly the lobsters and the turtles all advance.

02:18:31.165 --> 02:18:33.385
They are waiting on the shingle.

02:18:33.385 --> 02:18:37.005
Will you come and join the dance?

02:18:38.145 --> 02:18:43.885
Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, will you join the dance?

02:18:44.825 --> 02:18:50.465
Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, won't you join the dance?

02:18:51.185 --> 02:18:57.665
You can really have no notion how delightful it will be.

02:18:58.505 --> 02:19:01.645
When they take us up and throw us.

02:19:01.645 --> 02:19:05.825
With the lobsters out to sea.

02:19:07.745 --> 02:19:12.445
But the snail replied, too far, too far.

02:19:13.005 --> 02:19:16.125
And gave a look, a scance.

02:19:16.845 --> 02:19:19.805
Said he thanked the whiting kindly.

02:19:20.765 --> 02:19:23.505
But he would not join the dance.

02:19:24.625 --> 02:19:28.945
Would not, could not, would not, could not.

02:19:28.945 --> 02:19:31.665
Would not join the dance.

02:19:32.525 --> 02:19:35.865
Would not, could not, would not, could not.

02:19:36.265 --> 02:19:38.265
Could not join the dance.

02:19:39.285 --> 02:19:42.305
What matters it how far we go?

02:19:43.045 --> 02:19:45.245
His scaly friend replied.

02:19:46.305 --> 02:19:48.725
There is another shore you know.

02:19:49.525 --> 02:19:50.865
Upon the other side.

02:19:51.965 --> 02:19:54.105
The further off from England.

02:19:54.825 --> 02:19:56.705
The nearer is to France.

02:19:57.625 --> 02:20:01.645
Then turn not pale, beloved snail.

02:20:02.465 --> 02:20:04.465
But come and join the dance.

02:20:05.585 --> 02:20:12.125
Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, will you join the dance?

02:20:13.325 --> 02:20:19.245
Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, won't you join the dance?

02:20:21.105 --> 02:20:22.585
Thank you.

02:20:22.585 --> 02:20:27.305
It's a very interesting dance to watch, said Alice.

02:20:28.205 --> 02:20:31.825
Feeling very glad that it was over at last.

02:20:32.945 --> 02:20:38.025
And I do so like that curious song about the whiting.

02:20:39.685 --> 02:20:43.345
Oh, as to the whiting, said the mock turtle.

02:20:44.225 --> 02:20:46.885
They, you've seen them, of course.

02:20:48.265 --> 02:20:49.745
Yes, said Alice.

02:20:49.745 --> 02:20:52.345
I've often seen them at din.

02:20:53.485 --> 02:20:56.125
She checked herself hastily.

02:20:57.465 --> 02:21:02.965
I don't know where din may be, said the mock turtle.

02:21:03.765 --> 02:21:10.265
But if you've seen them so often, of course you know what they're like.

02:21:11.685 --> 02:21:15.645
I believe so, Alice replied thoughtfully.

02:21:15.645 --> 02:21:19.185
They have their tails in their mouths.

02:21:19.805 --> 02:21:22.685
And they're all over crumbs.

02:21:24.645 --> 02:21:29.445
You're wrong about the crumbs, said the mock turtle.

02:21:30.245 --> 02:21:34.405
Crumbs would all wash off in the sea.

02:21:35.665 --> 02:21:39.165
But they have their tails in their mouths.

02:21:39.885 --> 02:21:46.785
And the reason is, here the mock turtle yawned and shut his eyes.

02:21:48.125 --> 02:21:52.825
Tell her about the reason and all that, he said to the griffon.

02:21:54.065 --> 02:22:02.245
The reason is, said the griffon, that they would go with the lobsters to the dance.

02:22:02.925 --> 02:22:06.465
So they got thrown out to sea.

02:22:06.465 --> 02:22:10.785
So they had to fall a long way.

02:22:11.185 --> 02:22:15.345
So they got their tails fast in their mouths.

02:22:15.985 --> 02:22:18.425
So they couldn't get them out again.

02:22:19.425 --> 02:22:20.285
That's all.

02:22:22.365 --> 02:22:24.405
Thank you, said Alice.

02:22:25.505 --> 02:22:27.025
It's very interesting.

02:22:28.105 --> 02:22:31.605
I never knew so much about a whiting before.

02:22:32.645 --> 02:22:39.025
I can tell you more than that if you like, said the griffon.

02:22:39.925 --> 02:22:43.025
Do you know why it's called a whiting?

02:22:44.965 --> 02:22:47.665
I never thought about it, said Alice.

02:22:48.405 --> 02:22:49.025
Why?

02:22:50.465 --> 02:22:59.365
It does the boots and shoes, the griffon replied very solemnly.

02:22:59.365 --> 02:23:02.505
Alice was thoroughly puzzled.

02:23:04.025 --> 02:23:10.125
Does the boots and shoes, she repeated in a wondering tone.

02:23:11.045 --> 02:23:15.925
Why, what are your shoes done with, said the griffon?

02:23:16.665 --> 02:23:20.785
I mean, what makes them so shiny?

02:23:22.065 --> 02:23:30.845
Alice looked down at them and considered a little before she gave her answer.

02:23:32.265 --> 02:23:36.225
They're done with blacking, I believe.

02:23:38.185 --> 02:23:48.565
Boots and shoes under the sea, the griffon went on in a deep voice, are done with whiting.

02:23:48.565 --> 02:23:51.565
Now you know.

02:23:53.725 --> 02:23:59.805
And what are they made of, Alice asked in a tone of great curiosity.

02:24:01.325 --> 02:24:07.835
Souls and eels, of course, the griffon replied rather impatiently.

02:24:09.265 --> 02:24:12.845
Any shrimp could have told you that.

02:24:15.265 --> 02:24:22.465
If I'd been the whiting, said Alice, whose thoughts were still running on the song,

02:24:23.645 --> 02:24:32.025
I'd have said to the porpoise, keep back, please, we don't want you with us.

02:24:32.905 --> 02:24:39.025
They were obliged to have him with them, the mock turtle said.

02:24:39.025 --> 02:24:44.905
No wise fish would go anywhere without a porpoise.

02:24:46.065 --> 02:24:51.885
Wouldn't it really, said Alice in a tone of great surprise.

02:24:52.925 --> 02:24:56.405
Of course not, said the mock turtle.

02:24:56.405 --> 02:25:09.645
Why, if a fish came to me and told me he was going on a journey, I would say, with what porpoise?

02:25:11.225 --> 02:25:15.685
Don't you mean purpose, said Alice?

02:25:16.945 --> 02:25:23.825
I mean what I say, the mock turtle replied in an offended tone.

02:25:23.825 --> 02:25:31.405
And the griffon added, come, let's hear some of your adventures.

02:25:32.925 --> 02:25:40.665
I could tell you my adventures beginning from this morning, said Alice a little timidly.

02:25:41.465 --> 02:25:51.425
But it's no use going back to yesterday, because I was a different person then.

02:25:52.945 --> 02:25:57.565
Explain all that, said the mock turtle.

02:25:58.905 --> 02:26:05.765
No, no, the adventures first, said the griffon in an impatient tone.

02:26:07.005 --> 02:26:11.165
Explanations take such a dreadful time.

02:26:12.985 --> 02:26:21.085
So Alice began telling them her adventures from the time when she first saw the white rabbit.

02:26:22.405 --> 02:26:26.745
She was a little nervous about it just at first.

02:26:27.485 --> 02:26:38.505
The two creatures got so close to her, one on each side, and opened their eyes and mouths so very wide.

02:26:38.505 --> 02:26:42.865
But she gained courage as she went on.

02:26:44.185 --> 02:26:51.005
Her listeners were perfectly quiet, till she got to the part about her repeating,

02:26:52.165 --> 02:26:59.965
You are old, Father William, to the caterpillar, and the words all coming different.

02:26:59.965 --> 02:27:08.065
And then the mock turtle drew a long breath and said, That's very curious.

02:27:09.885 --> 02:27:16.425
It's all about as curious as it can be, said the griffon.

02:27:17.825 --> 02:27:23.145
It all came different, the mock turtle repeated thoughtfully.

02:27:24.145 --> 02:27:29.785
I should like to hear her try and repeat something now.

02:27:30.905 --> 02:27:32.525
Tell her to begin.

02:27:33.925 --> 02:27:41.145
He looked at the griffon as if he thought it had some kind of authority over Alice.

02:27:43.085 --> 02:27:45.165
Stand up and repeat.

02:27:46.165 --> 02:27:51.065
Tis the voice of the sluggard, said the griffon.

02:27:52.565 --> 02:28:00.285
How the creatures order one about and make one repeat lessons, thought Alice.

02:28:01.305 --> 02:28:04.485
I might as well be at school at once.

02:28:05.945 --> 02:28:10.505
However, she got up and began to repeat it.

02:28:11.145 --> 02:28:18.185
But her head was so full of the lobster quadrille that she hardly knew what she was saying.

02:28:18.185 --> 02:28:23.305
And the words came very queer indeed.

02:28:25.345 --> 02:28:29.145
Tis the voice of the lobster, I heard him declare.

02:28:29.805 --> 02:28:31.905
You have baked me too brown.

02:28:32.685 --> 02:28:34.805
I must sugar my hair.

02:28:36.005 --> 02:28:47.265
As a duck with its eyelids, so he with his nose, trims his belt and his buttons and turns out his toes.

02:28:47.265 --> 02:28:58.325
When the sands are all dry, he is gay as a lark and will talk in contemptuous tones of the shark.

02:28:59.205 --> 02:29:09.085
But when the tide rises and sharks are around, his voice has a timid and tremulous sound.

02:29:11.485 --> 02:29:17.885
That's different from what I used to say when I was a child, said the griffon.

02:29:18.765 --> 02:29:22.845
Well, I never heard it before, said the mock turtle.

02:29:23.665 --> 02:29:26.865
But it sounds uncommon nonsense.

02:29:28.665 --> 02:29:29.745
Alice said nothing.

02:29:29.745 --> 02:29:40.245
She had sat down with her face in her hands, wondering if anything would ever happen in a natural way again.

02:29:41.505 --> 02:29:46.385
I should like to have it explained, said the mock turtle.

02:29:47.345 --> 02:29:51.505
She can't explain it, said the griffon hastily.

02:29:52.425 --> 02:29:54.585
Go on with the next verse.

02:29:55.585 --> 02:30:01.305
But about his toes, the mock turtle persisted.

02:30:01.705 --> 02:30:06.665
How could he turn them out with his nose, you know?

02:30:08.325 --> 02:30:19.565
It's the first position in dancing, Alice said, but was dreadfully puzzled by the whole thing and longed to change the subject.

02:30:20.565 --> 02:30:25.545
Go on with the next verse, the griffon repeated impatiently.

02:30:26.025 --> 02:30:30.305
It begins, I passed by his garden.

02:30:32.665 --> 02:30:40.985
Alice did not dare to disobey, though she felt sure it would all come wrong.

02:30:41.405 --> 02:30:45.145
And she went on in a trembling voice.

02:30:46.145 --> 02:30:57.665
I passed by his garden and marked with one eye how the owl and the panther were sharing pie.

02:30:58.965 --> 02:31:09.945
The panther took pie crust and gravy and meat, while the owl had the dish as its share of the treat.

02:31:09.945 --> 02:31:20.265
When the pie was all finished, the owl, as a boon, was kindly permitted to pocket the spoon,

02:31:21.245 --> 02:31:29.725
while the panther received knife and fork with a growl and concluded the banquet.

02:31:31.325 --> 02:31:38.705
What is the use of repeating all that stuff, the mock turtle interrupted.

02:31:38.705 --> 02:31:48.785
If you don't explain it as you go on, it's by far the most confusing thing I ever heard.

02:31:49.665 --> 02:31:59.705
Yes, I think you'd better leave off, said the griffon, and Alice was only too glad to do so.

02:32:01.725 --> 02:32:04.985
Shall we try another figure of the lobster quadrille?

02:32:04.985 --> 02:32:12.505
The griffon went on, or would you like the mock turtle to sing you a song?

02:32:13.725 --> 02:32:21.485
Oh, a song, please, if the mock turtle would be so kind, Alice replied,

02:32:22.245 --> 02:32:32.565
so eagerly that the griffon said in a rather offended tone, hmm, no accounting for tastes.

02:32:32.565 --> 02:32:37.885
Sing her turtle soup, will you, old fellow?

02:32:39.345 --> 02:32:50.365
The mock turtle sighed deeply and began, in a voice sometimes choked with sobs, to sing this.

02:32:52.425 --> 02:33:09.025
Beautiful soup, so rich and green, waiting in a hot tureen, who for such dainties would not stoop?

02:33:10.125 --> 02:33:19.865
Soup of the evening, beautiful soup, soup of the evening, beautiful soup,

02:33:22.705 --> 02:33:42.585
beautiful soup, beautiful soup, soup of the evening, beautiful, beautiful soup,

02:33:44.305 --> 02:33:54.425
beautiful soup, who cares for fish, game, or any other dish?

02:33:55.485 --> 02:34:09.425
Who would not give all else for two, penny worth only of beautiful soup, penny worth only of beautiful soup,

02:34:09.425 --> 02:34:27.325
beautiful soup, beautiful soup, soup of the evening, beautiful, beautiful soup.

02:34:29.665 --> 02:34:37.345
Chorus again, cried the griffon, and the mock turtle had just begun to repeat it,

02:34:37.725 --> 02:34:44.105
when a cry of the trials beginning was heard in the distance.

02:34:44.865 --> 02:34:56.005
Come on, cried the griffon, and taking Alice by the hand, it hurried off without waiting for the end of the song.

02:34:57.585 --> 02:35:09.865
What trial is it? Alice panted as she ran, but the griffon only answered, come on, and ran the faster,

02:35:10.605 --> 02:35:19.585
while more and more faintly came, carried on the breeze that followed them, the melancholy words.

02:35:20.585 --> 02:35:30.825
Soup of the evening, beautiful, beautiful soup.

02:36:03.785 --> 02:36:04.265
XI.

02:36:04.805 --> 02:36:08.805
The King and Queen of Hearts were seated on their throne when they arrived, with a great

02:36:08.805 --> 02:36:13.745
crowd assembled about them, all sorts of little birds and beasts, as well as a whole pack

02:36:13.745 --> 02:36:18.565
of cards. The knave was standing before them in chains, with a soldier on each side to

02:36:18.565 --> 02:36:23.705
guard him, and near the king was the white rabbit, with a trumpet in one hand and a scroll

02:36:23.705 --> 02:36:29.105
of parchment in the other. In the very middle of the court was a table, with a large dish

02:36:29.105 --> 02:36:33.685
of tarts upon it. They looked so good that it made Alice quite hungry to look at them.

02:36:33.685 --> 02:36:39.565
I wish they'd get the trial done, she thought, and hand round the refreshments. But there seemed

02:36:39.565 --> 02:36:44.505
to be no chance of this, so she began looking at everything about her to pass away the time.

02:36:45.885 --> 02:36:49.985
Alice had never been in a court of justice before, but she had read about them in books,

02:36:50.285 --> 02:36:54.005
and she was quite pleased to find that she knew the name of nearly everything there.

02:36:54.565 --> 02:36:57.745
That's the judge, she said to herself, because of his great wig.

02:36:59.145 --> 02:37:04.585
The judge, by the way, was the king, and as he wore his crown over the wig, he did not look at

02:37:04.585 --> 02:37:10.505
all comfortable, and it was certainly not becoming. And that's the jury box, thought Alice. And those

02:37:10.505 --> 02:37:15.445
twelve creatures—she was obliged to say creatures, you see, because some of them were animals and

02:37:15.445 --> 02:37:21.205
some were birds—I suppose they are the jurors. She said this last word two or three times over

02:37:21.205 --> 02:37:26.345
to herself, being rather proud of it, for she thought, and rightly too, that very few little

02:37:26.345 --> 02:37:32.165
girls of her age knew the meaning of it at all. However, jury men would have done just as well.

02:37:33.285 --> 02:37:36.485
The twelve jurors were all writing very busily on slates.

02:37:36.885 --> 02:37:39.585
What are they doing? Alice whispered to the griffon.

02:37:40.105 --> 02:37:43.505
They can't have anything to put down yet before the trial's begun.

02:37:44.665 --> 02:37:47.765
They're putting down their names, the griffon whispered in reply,

02:37:48.325 --> 02:37:51.145
for fear that they should forget them before the end of the trial.

02:37:52.725 --> 02:37:57.905
Stupid things! Alice began in a loud, indignant voice, but she stopped hastily, for the white

02:37:57.905 --> 02:38:02.465
rabbit cried out, Silence in the court! And the king put on his spectacles and looked anxiously

02:38:02.465 --> 02:38:08.405
round to make out who was talking. Alice could see, as well as if she were looking over their

02:38:08.405 --> 02:38:13.105
shoulders, that all the jurors were writing down stupid things on their slates, and she

02:38:13.105 --> 02:38:17.865
could even make out that one of them didn't know how to spell stupid, and that he had to ask his

02:38:17.865 --> 02:38:23.365
neighbor to tell him. A nice muddle their slates will be in before the trial's over, thought Alice.

02:38:25.145 --> 02:38:29.645
One of the jurors had a pencil that squeaked. This, of course, Alice could not stand,

02:38:30.005 --> 02:38:34.525
and she went round the court and got behind him and very soon found an opportunity of taking it

02:38:34.525 --> 02:38:40.285
away. She did it so quickly that the poor little juror, it was Bill the Lizard, could not make out

02:38:40.285 --> 02:38:45.285
at all what had become of it, so, after hunting all about for it, he was obliged to write with

02:38:45.285 --> 02:38:50.245
finger for the rest of the day, and this was of very little use, as it left no mark on the slate.

02:38:52.145 --> 02:38:57.885
Harold, read the accusation, said the king. On this the white rabbit blew three blasts on

02:38:57.885 --> 02:39:01.565
the trumpet, and then enrolled the parchment scroll, and read as follows.

02:39:02.505 --> 02:39:06.085
The queen of hearts, she made some tarts, all on a summer day.

02:39:06.405 --> 02:39:10.045
The knave of hearts, he stole those tarts, and took them quite away.

02:39:11.265 --> 02:39:13.785
Consider your verdict, the king said to the jury.

02:39:14.185 --> 02:39:19.225
Not yet, not yet, the rabbit hastily interrupted. There's a great deal to come before that.

02:39:20.265 --> 02:39:24.685
Call the first witness, said the king, and the white rabbit blew three blasts on the trumpet,

02:39:24.805 --> 02:39:26.525
and called out, First witness!

02:39:27.745 --> 02:39:32.465
The first witness was the hatter. He came in with a tea cup in one hand,

02:39:32.525 --> 02:39:37.965
and a piece of bread and butter in the other. I beg pardon, your majesty, he began, for bringing

02:39:37.965 --> 02:39:41.545
his in, but I hadn't quite finished my tea when I was sent for.

02:39:42.505 --> 02:39:46.105
You ought to have finished, said the king. When did you begin?

02:39:46.725 --> 02:39:49.705
The hatter looked at the march hare, who had followed him into the court,

02:39:49.965 --> 02:39:51.125
arm in arm with the door-mouse.

02:39:52.185 --> 02:39:54.505
Fourteenth of March, I think it was, he said.

02:39:54.905 --> 02:39:58.205
Fifteenth, said the march hare. Sixteenth, added the door-mouse.

02:39:59.005 --> 02:40:03.825
Write that down, the king said to the jury, and the jury eagerly wrote down all three dates on

02:40:03.825 --> 02:40:07.765
their slates, and then added them up, and reduced the answer to shillings and pence.

02:40:08.625 --> 02:40:12.905
Take off your hat, the king said to the hatter. It isn't mine, said the hatter.

02:40:13.405 --> 02:40:18.085
Stolen, the king exclaimed, turning to the jury, who instantly made a memorandum of the fact.

02:40:18.725 --> 02:40:24.205
I keep them to sell, the hatter added as an explanation. I've none of my own. I'm a hatter.

02:40:25.265 --> 02:40:30.205
Here the queen put on her spectacles, and began staring at the hatter, who turned pale and fidgeted.

02:40:31.245 --> 02:40:35.845
Give your evidence, said the king, and don't be nervous, or I'll have you executed on the spot.

02:40:36.585 --> 02:40:42.005
This did not seem to encourage the witness at all. He kept shifting from one foot to the other,

02:40:42.085 --> 02:40:46.745
looking uneasily at the queen, and in his confusion he bit a large piece out of his

02:40:46.745 --> 02:40:53.085
teacup instead of the bread and butter. Just at this moment, Alice felt a very curious

02:40:53.085 --> 02:40:58.405
sensation, which puzzled her a good deal until she made out what it was. She was beginning to

02:40:58.405 --> 02:41:02.985
grow larger again, and she thought at first she would get up and leave the court, but on second

02:41:02.985 --> 02:41:07.165
she decided to remain where she was as long as there was room for her.

02:41:08.345 --> 02:41:11.785
I wish you wouldn't squeeze so, said the doormouse, who was sitting next to her.

02:41:11.925 --> 02:41:13.285
I can hardly breathe.

02:41:13.965 --> 02:41:17.125
I can't help it, said Alice very meekly. I'm growing.

02:41:17.845 --> 02:41:20.085
You've no right to grow here, said the doormouse.

02:41:20.605 --> 02:41:24.985
Don't talk nonsense, said Alice more boldly. You know you're growing too.

02:41:25.945 --> 02:41:30.465
Yes, but I grow at a reasonable pace, said the doormouse, not in that ridiculous fashion.

02:41:31.005 --> 02:41:34.605
And he got up very sulkily and crossed over to the other side of the court.

02:41:36.245 --> 02:41:39.365
All this time the queen had never left off staring at the hatter,

02:41:39.645 --> 02:41:44.085
and just as the doormouse crossed the court, she said to one of the officers of the court,

02:41:44.705 --> 02:41:47.265
Bring me the list to the singers in the last concert,

02:41:47.565 --> 02:41:51.365
on which the wretched hatter trembled so that he shook both his shoes off.

02:41:52.125 --> 02:41:55.925
Give you evidence, the king repeated angrily, or I'll have you executed,

02:41:56.005 --> 02:41:57.505
whether you're novice or not.

02:41:58.585 --> 02:42:02.465
I'm a poor man, your majesty, the hatter began in a trembling voice,

02:42:02.665 --> 02:42:06.485
and I hadn't begun my tea. Not above a week or so.

02:42:06.925 --> 02:42:10.725
And what with the bread and butter getting so thin, and the twinkling of the tea.

02:42:11.465 --> 02:42:13.545
The twinkling of the what, said the king?

02:42:13.945 --> 02:42:16.285
It begun with the tea, the hatter replied.

02:42:17.105 --> 02:42:20.085
Of course twinkling begins with the tea, said the king sharply.

02:42:20.585 --> 02:42:22.545
Do take me for a dunce. Go on.

02:42:23.425 --> 02:42:27.905
I'm a poor man, the hatter went on, and most things twinkled after that,

02:42:28.005 --> 02:42:29.605
only the march hare said.

02:42:29.945 --> 02:42:32.525
I didn't, the march hare interrupted in a great hurry.

02:42:32.805 --> 02:42:33.985
You did, said the hatter.

02:42:34.245 --> 02:42:35.905
I deny it, said the march hare.

02:42:36.525 --> 02:42:39.025
He denies it, said the king. Leave out that part.

02:42:40.265 --> 02:42:43.365
Well, at any rate, the doormouse said, the hatter went on,

02:42:43.445 --> 02:42:46.085
looking anxiously round to see if he would deny it too,

02:42:46.465 --> 02:42:49.105
but the doormouse denied nothing, being fast asleep.

02:42:49.905 --> 02:42:53.565
After that, continued the hatter, I cut some more bread and butter.

02:42:54.245 --> 02:42:56.925
But what did the doormouse say, one of the jury asked?

02:42:57.225 --> 02:42:59.305
That I can't remember, said the hatter.

02:43:00.185 --> 02:43:03.745
You must remember, remarked the king, or I'll have you executed.

02:43:04.605 --> 02:43:07.365
The miserable hatter dropped his teacup and bread and butter,

02:43:07.445 --> 02:43:08.585
and went down on one knee.

02:43:09.045 --> 02:43:11.385
I'm a poor man, your majesty, he began.

02:43:11.865 --> 02:43:14.145
You're a very poor speaker, said the king.

02:43:14.885 --> 02:43:16.505
Here one of the guinea pigs cheered,

02:43:16.505 --> 02:43:19.245
and was immediately suppressed by the officers of the court.

02:43:20.025 --> 02:43:23.565
As that is rather a hard word, I will just explain to you how it was done.

02:43:23.765 --> 02:43:26.805
They had a large canvas bag, which tied up at the mouth with strings.

02:43:27.225 --> 02:43:30.585
Into this they slipped the guinea pig, head first, and then sat upon it.

02:43:31.565 --> 02:43:33.745
I'm glad I've seen that done, thought Alice.

02:43:34.045 --> 02:43:36.845
I've so often read in the newspapers, at the end of trials,

02:43:37.325 --> 02:43:38.625
there were some attempts at applause,

02:43:38.705 --> 02:43:41.265
which was immediately suppressed by the officers of the court,

02:43:41.265 --> 02:43:43.645
and I never understood what it meant till now.

02:43:44.865 --> 02:43:48.465
If that's all you know about it, you may stand down, continued the king.

02:43:49.305 --> 02:43:51.085
I can't go no lower, said the hatter.

02:43:51.285 --> 02:43:52.725
I'm on the floor as it is.

02:43:53.205 --> 02:43:55.365
Then you may sit down, the king replied.

02:43:55.745 --> 02:43:57.965
Here the other guinea pig cheered, and was suppressed.

02:43:59.205 --> 02:44:01.165
Come, that finished the guinea pigs, thought Alice.

02:44:01.285 --> 02:44:02.405
Now we shall get on better.

02:44:03.785 --> 02:44:05.765
I'd rather finish my tea, said the hatter,

02:44:05.905 --> 02:44:08.765
with an anxious look at the queen, who was reading the list of singers.

02:44:09.165 --> 02:44:12.425
You may go, said the king, and the hatter hurriedly left the court,

02:44:12.425 --> 02:44:14.605
without even waiting to put his shoes on.

02:44:14.965 --> 02:44:18.925
And just take his head off outside, the queen added to one of the officers,

02:44:19.285 --> 02:44:22.125
but the hatter was out of sight before the officer could get to the door.

02:44:23.305 --> 02:44:25.385
Call the next witness, said the king.

02:44:26.165 --> 02:44:28.265
The next witness was the duchess's cook.

02:44:28.805 --> 02:44:31.965
She carried the pepper box in her hand, and Alice guessed who it was,

02:44:32.025 --> 02:44:35.445
even before she got into the court, by the way the people near the door

02:44:35.445 --> 02:44:36.925
began sneezing all at once.

02:44:37.965 --> 02:44:39.665
Give your evidence, said the king.

02:44:40.665 --> 02:44:41.825
Sont, said the cook.

02:44:43.145 --> 02:44:46.505
The king looked anxiously at the white rabbit, who said in a low voice,

02:44:47.285 --> 02:44:49.885
Your majesty must cross-examine this witness.

02:44:51.045 --> 02:44:54.405
Well, if I must, I must, the king said, with a melancholy air.

02:44:54.785 --> 02:44:57.085
And after folding his arms and frowning at the cook,

02:44:57.185 --> 02:45:00.245
till his eyes were nearly out of sight, he said in a deep voice,

02:45:00.945 --> 02:45:02.505
What are those hearts made of?

02:45:03.665 --> 02:45:05.445
Peppa mostly, said the cook.

02:45:05.945 --> 02:45:08.025
Treacle, said a sleepy voice behind her.

02:45:08.745 --> 02:45:11.365
Call that door-mouse, the queen shrieked out.

02:45:11.705 --> 02:45:12.885
Behead that door-mouse!

02:45:13.165 --> 02:45:14.785
Turn that door-mouse out of court!

02:45:15.105 --> 02:45:15.885
Suppress him!

02:45:16.045 --> 02:45:16.665
Pinch him!

02:45:16.945 --> 02:45:18.345
Off with his whiskers!

02:45:19.625 --> 02:45:21.985
For some minutes the whole court was in confusion,

02:45:22.105 --> 02:45:23.565
getting the door-mouse turned out,

02:45:23.705 --> 02:45:26.745
and by the time they had settled down again, the cook had disappeared.

02:45:27.825 --> 02:45:30.525
Never mind, said the king, with an air of great relief.

02:45:30.765 --> 02:45:34.485
Call the next witness, and he added in an undertone to the queen.

02:45:34.925 --> 02:45:37.865
Really, my dear, you must cross-examine the next witness,

02:45:37.865 --> 02:45:39.625
it quite makes my forehead ache.

02:45:41.125 --> 02:45:43.645
Alice watched the white rabbit as he fumbled over the list,

02:45:43.785 --> 02:45:46.745
feeling very curious to see what the next witness would be like.

02:45:47.205 --> 02:45:50.225
For they haven't gotten much evidence yet, she said to herself.

02:45:51.045 --> 02:45:53.405
Imagine her surprise when the white rabbit read out,

02:45:53.405 --> 02:45:55.465
at the top of his shrill little voice, the name

02:45:56.445 --> 02:45:56.905
Alice!

02:46:17.517 --> 02:46:18.877
Alice's Evidence

02:46:19.617 --> 02:46:26.377
Here cried Alice, quite forgetting in the flurry of the moment how large she had grown in the last few minutes.

02:46:26.377 --> 02:46:31.797
And she jumped up in such a hurry that she tipped over the jury box with the edge of her skirt,

02:46:32.237 --> 02:46:35.077
upsetting all the jury men onto the heads of the crowd below.

02:46:35.677 --> 02:46:37.777
And there they lay, sprawling about,

02:46:38.177 --> 02:46:42.777
reminding her very much of a globe of goldfish she had accidentally upset the week before.

02:46:43.597 --> 02:46:46.937
Oh, I beg your pardon, she exclaimed in a tone of great dismay,

02:46:47.377 --> 02:46:49.877
and began picking them up again as quickly as she could,

02:46:50.397 --> 02:46:52.997
for the accident of the goldfish kept running in her head.

02:46:52.997 --> 02:46:59.637
And she had a vague sort of idea that they must be collected at once and put back into the jury box, or they would die.

02:47:00.777 --> 02:47:04.537
The trial cannot proceed, said the King in a very grave voice,

02:47:04.877 --> 02:47:11.037
until all of the jury men are back in their proper places, all, he repeated with great emphasis,

02:47:11.437 --> 02:47:14.457
looking hard at Alice, as he said so.

02:47:16.537 --> 02:47:21.877
Alice looked at the jury box and saw that, in her haste, she had put the lizard in head downwards,

02:47:21.877 --> 02:47:27.337
and the poor little thing was waving its tail about in a melancholy way, being quite unable to move.

02:47:28.537 --> 02:47:30.677
She soon got it out again and put it right.

02:47:31.417 --> 02:47:34.017
Not that it signifies much, she said to herself,

02:47:34.457 --> 02:47:37.857
I should think it would be quite as much use in the trial one way up as the other.

02:47:39.277 --> 02:47:43.097
As soon as the jury had a little recovered from the shock of being upset,

02:47:43.677 --> 02:47:46.637
and their slates and pencils had been found and handed back to them,

02:47:46.637 --> 02:47:51.317
they set to work very diligently to write out a history of the accident,

02:47:51.917 --> 02:47:56.877
all except the lizard, who seemed too much overcome to do anything but sit with its mouth open,

02:47:57.357 --> 02:47:59.197
gazing up into the roof of the court.

02:48:00.257 --> 02:48:03.537
What do you know about this business? the King said to Alice.

02:48:04.497 --> 02:48:06.117
Nothing, said Alice.

02:48:06.857 --> 02:48:09.437
Nothing whatever, persisted the King.

02:48:10.037 --> 02:48:12.017
Nothing whatever, said Alice.

02:48:12.757 --> 02:48:15.497
That's very important, the King said, turning to the jury.

02:48:15.497 --> 02:48:20.237
They were just beginning to write this down on their slates when the white rabbit interrupted,

02:48:20.957 --> 02:48:25.217
Unimportant, Your Majesty means, of course, he said in a very respectful tone,

02:48:25.417 --> 02:48:28.517
but frowning and making faces at him as he spoke.

02:48:30.017 --> 02:48:33.297
Unimportant, of course, I meant, the King hastily said,

02:48:33.857 --> 02:48:38.497
and went on to himself in an undertone, important, unimportant, unimportant, important,

02:48:39.317 --> 02:48:41.957
as if he was trying which word sounded best.

02:48:43.177 --> 02:48:47.677
Some of the jury wrote it down, important, and some unimportant.

02:48:48.477 --> 02:48:51.617
Alice could see this as she was near enough to look over their slates,

02:48:51.957 --> 02:48:54.777
but it doesn't matter a bit, she thought to herself.

02:48:56.237 --> 02:49:00.097
At this moment the King, who had been for some time busily writing in his notebook,

02:49:00.457 --> 02:49:04.777
cackled out, silence, and read out from his book, Rule 42,

02:49:05.457 --> 02:49:08.597
all persons more than a mile high to leave the court.

02:49:10.197 --> 02:49:11.477
Everybody looked at Alice.

02:49:12.357 --> 02:49:13.977
I'm not a mile high, said Alice.

02:49:14.657 --> 02:49:15.557
You are, said the King.

02:49:15.917 --> 02:49:18.117
Nearly two miles high, added the Queen.

02:49:18.717 --> 02:49:20.617
Well, I shan't go at any rate, said Alice.

02:49:20.837 --> 02:49:22.757
Besides, that's not a regular rule.

02:49:23.077 --> 02:49:24.557
You invented it just now.

02:49:25.877 --> 02:49:28.137
It's the oldest rule in the book, said the King.

02:49:29.117 --> 02:49:31.677
Then it ought to be number one, said Alice.

02:49:32.857 --> 02:49:35.157
The King turned pale and shut his notebook hastily.

02:49:35.157 --> 02:49:40.017
Consider your verdict, he said to the jury in a low, trembling voice.

02:49:40.657 --> 02:49:43.037
There's more evidence to come yet, please your majesty,

02:49:43.497 --> 02:49:45.397
said the White Rabbit, jumping up in a great hurry.

02:49:45.737 --> 02:49:47.557
This paper has just been picked up.

02:49:48.517 --> 02:49:50.017
What's in it, said the Queen.

02:49:50.757 --> 02:49:52.837
I haven't opened it yet, said the White Rabbit,

02:49:53.117 --> 02:49:58.037
but it seems to be a letter written by the prisoner to, to somebody.

02:49:59.237 --> 02:50:02.437
It must have been that, said the King, unless it was written to nobody,

02:50:03.037 --> 02:50:04.317
which isn't usual, you know.

02:50:05.117 --> 02:50:08.377
Who is it directed to, said one of the jury men.

02:50:09.157 --> 02:50:11.357
It isn't directed at all, said the White Letter.

02:50:11.457 --> 02:50:14.337
In fact, there's nothing written on the outside.

02:50:15.357 --> 02:50:17.457
He unfolded the paper as he spoke and added,

02:50:17.757 --> 02:50:20.977
it isn't a letter after all, it's a set of verses.

02:50:22.997 --> 02:50:26.817
Are they in the prisoner's handwriting, asked another of the jury men.

02:50:27.717 --> 02:50:32.417
No, they're not, said the White Rabbit, and that's the queerest thing about it.

02:50:33.097 --> 02:50:34.757
The jury all looked puzzled.

02:50:35.857 --> 02:50:38.417
He must have imitated somebody else's hand, said the King.

02:50:39.057 --> 02:50:40.657
The jury all brightened up again.

02:50:41.157 --> 02:50:43.577
Please your majesty, said the knave, I didn't write it,

02:50:43.677 --> 02:50:45.057
and they can't prove I did.

02:50:45.457 --> 02:50:47.197
There's no name signed at the end.

02:50:48.417 --> 02:50:52.357
If you didn't sign it, said the King, that only makes the matter worse.

02:50:52.777 --> 02:50:54.197
You must have meant some mischief,

02:50:54.377 --> 02:50:56.897
or else you'd have signed your name like an honest man.

02:50:58.017 --> 02:50:59.877
There was a general clapping of hands at this.

02:50:59.877 --> 02:51:03.257
It was the first really clever thing the King had said that day.

02:51:03.997 --> 02:51:06.397
That proves his guilt, said the Queen.

02:51:07.277 --> 02:51:09.557
It proves nothing of the sort, said Alice.

02:51:09.877 --> 02:51:12.157
Why, you don't even know what they're about.

02:51:13.317 --> 02:51:15.077
Read them, said the King.

02:51:16.257 --> 02:51:17.917
The White Rabbit put on his spectacles.

02:51:18.717 --> 02:51:21.537
Where shall I begin, please your majesty, he asked.

02:51:22.197 --> 02:51:25.417
Begin at the beginning, the King said gravely,

02:51:25.657 --> 02:51:28.397
and go on till you come to the end, then stop.

02:51:29.397 --> 02:51:31.997
These were the verses the White Rabbit read.

02:51:33.357 --> 02:51:36.877
They told me you had been to her, and mentioned me to him.

02:51:37.317 --> 02:51:40.337
She gave me a good character, but said I could not swim.

02:51:41.617 --> 02:51:44.777
He sent them word I had not gone, we know it to be true.

02:51:45.037 --> 02:51:48.357
If she would push the matter on, what would become of you?

02:51:49.297 --> 02:51:53.617
I gave her one, they gave him two, you gave us three or more.

02:51:54.197 --> 02:51:58.017
They all returned from him to you, though they were mine before.

02:51:59.157 --> 02:52:03.257
If I or she should chance to be involved in this affair,

02:52:03.757 --> 02:52:08.237
he trusts to you to set them free exactly as we were.

02:52:09.977 --> 02:52:13.257
My notion was that you had been, before she had this fit,

02:52:13.677 --> 02:52:18.337
an obstacle that came between him and ourselves and it.

02:52:19.937 --> 02:52:23.497
Don't let him know she liked them best, for this must ever be

02:52:23.497 --> 02:52:28.537
a secret kept from all the rest between yourself and me.

02:52:30.197 --> 02:52:32.477
That's the most important piece of evidence we've heard yet,

02:52:32.577 --> 02:52:33.817
said the King, rubbing his hands.

02:52:34.177 --> 02:52:38.377
And now let the jury, if any one of them can explain it, said Alice.

02:52:39.157 --> 02:52:41.157
She had grown so large in the last few minutes

02:52:41.157 --> 02:52:43.437
that she wasn't a bit afraid of interrupting him.

02:52:43.797 --> 02:52:44.937
I'll give him sixpence.

02:52:45.337 --> 02:52:47.737
I don't believe there's an atom of meaning in it.

02:52:48.857 --> 02:52:50.937
The jury all wrote this down on their slates.

02:52:50.937 --> 02:52:53.877
She doesn't believe there's an atom of meaning in it.

02:52:54.417 --> 02:52:56.337
But none of them attempted to explain the paper.

02:52:57.477 --> 02:52:59.297
If there's no meaning in it, said the King,

02:52:59.737 --> 02:53:03.417
that saves a world of trouble, you know, as we needn't try to find any.

02:53:04.377 --> 02:53:08.217
And yes, I don't know, he went on, spreading out the verses on his knee

02:53:08.217 --> 02:53:10.377
and looking at them all with one eye.

02:53:11.017 --> 02:53:13.517
I seem to see some meaning in them, after all.

02:53:14.177 --> 02:53:15.677
Said I could not swim.

02:53:16.417 --> 02:53:19.577
You can't swim, can you? he added, turning to the knave.

02:53:19.577 --> 02:53:21.757
The knave shook his head sadly.

02:53:22.077 --> 02:53:23.417
Do I look like it? he said,

02:53:23.717 --> 02:53:26.777
which he certainly did not, being made entirely of cardboard.

02:53:28.137 --> 02:53:29.777
All right so far, said the King.

02:53:30.357 --> 02:53:32.437
And he went on muttering over the verses to himself.

02:53:33.177 --> 02:53:34.617
We know it to be true.

02:53:34.757 --> 02:53:36.137
That's the jury, of course.

02:53:36.577 --> 02:53:39.317
I gave her one. They gave him two.

02:53:39.617 --> 02:53:43.017
Why, that must be what he did with the tarts, you know.

02:53:44.017 --> 02:53:47.017
But it goes on. They all returned from him to you, said Alice.

02:53:47.777 --> 02:53:50.917
Why, there they are, said the King triumphantly,

02:53:51.057 --> 02:53:52.657
pointing to the tarts on the table.

02:53:53.057 --> 02:53:54.717
Nothing can be clearer than that.

02:53:55.117 --> 02:53:57.697
Then again, before she had this fit.

02:53:58.757 --> 02:54:01.817
You never had fits, my dear, I think, he said to the Queen.

02:54:02.597 --> 02:54:04.017
Never, said the Queen furiously,

02:54:04.997 --> 02:54:06.957
throwing an inkstand at the lizard as she spoke.

02:54:07.877 --> 02:54:12.037
The unfortunate little Bill had left off writing on his slate with one finger,

02:54:12.317 --> 02:54:13.617
as he found it made no mark.

02:54:13.617 --> 02:54:17.837
But he now hastily began again using the ink that was trickling down his face,

02:54:18.377 --> 02:54:19.317
as long as it lasted.

02:54:20.857 --> 02:54:23.257
Then the words don't fit you, said the King,

02:54:23.337 --> 02:54:24.957
looking round the court with a smile.

02:54:26.317 --> 02:54:27.537
There was a dead silence.

02:54:29.157 --> 02:54:32.917
It's a pun, the King added in offended tone, and everybody laughed.

02:54:33.597 --> 02:54:35.917
Let the jury consider their verdict, the King said,

02:54:35.977 --> 02:54:37.957
for about the twentieth time that day.

02:54:38.357 --> 02:54:42.377
No, no, said the Queen, sentence first, verdict afterwards.

02:54:43.297 --> 02:54:45.717
Stuff a nonsense, said Alice loudly.

02:54:46.057 --> 02:54:48.697
The idea of having the sentence first.

02:54:49.537 --> 02:54:52.597
Hold your tongue, said the Queen, turning purple.

02:54:53.477 --> 02:54:55.617
I won't, said Alice.

02:54:56.337 --> 02:54:59.797
Off with her head, the Queen shouted at the top of her voice.

02:55:00.877 --> 02:55:01.577
Nobody moved.

02:55:02.297 --> 02:55:03.997
Who cares for you, said Alice.

02:55:04.297 --> 02:55:06.157
She had grown to her full size by this time.

02:55:06.457 --> 02:55:08.257
You're nothing but a pack of cards.

02:55:09.197 --> 02:55:13.357
At this the whole pack rose up into the air and came flying down upon her.

02:55:14.057 --> 02:55:16.897
She gave a little scream, half of fright and half of anger,

02:55:17.117 --> 02:55:20.257
and tried to beat them off, and found herself lying on the bank,

02:55:20.577 --> 02:55:22.457
with her head in the lap of her sister,

02:55:22.837 --> 02:55:27.757
who was gently brushing away some dead leaves that had fluttered down from the tree upon her face.

02:55:28.857 --> 02:55:30.957
Wake up, Alice dear, said her sister.

02:55:31.337 --> 02:55:33.317
Why, what a long sleep you've had.

02:55:34.677 --> 02:55:37.417
Oh, I've had such a curious dream, said Alice.

02:55:37.417 --> 02:55:41.317
And she told her sister, as well as she could remember them,

02:55:41.777 --> 02:55:45.257
all these strange adventures of hers that you have just been reading about.

02:55:46.177 --> 02:55:48.837
And when she had finished, her sister kissed her and said,

02:55:49.337 --> 02:55:51.637
it was a curious dream dear, certainly.

02:55:52.197 --> 02:55:54.537
But now run into your tea, it's getting late.

02:55:56.257 --> 02:56:00.497
So Alice got up and ran off, thinking while she ran, as well she might,

02:56:00.917 --> 02:56:02.777
what a wonderful dream it had been.

02:56:03.677 --> 02:56:07.977
But her sister sat still, just as she left her,

02:56:08.317 --> 02:56:12.037
leaning her head on her hand, watching the setting sun,

02:56:12.517 --> 02:56:15.937
and thinking of little Alice and all her wonderful adventures,

02:56:16.797 --> 02:56:19.477
till she too began dreaming, after a fashion.

02:56:20.377 --> 02:56:21.477
And this was her dream.

02:56:23.137 --> 02:56:25.297
First she dreamed of little Alice herself,

02:56:25.677 --> 02:56:28.537
and once again the tiny hands were clasped upon her knee,

02:56:28.797 --> 02:56:31.337
and the bright, eager eyes were looking up into hers,

02:56:31.337 --> 02:56:34.257
and she could hear the very tones of her voice,

02:56:34.857 --> 02:56:36.877
and see that queer little toss of her head,

02:56:37.197 --> 02:56:40.417
to keep back the wandering hair that would always get into her eyes.

02:56:41.277 --> 02:56:44.117
And still, as she listened, or seemed to listen,

02:56:44.937 --> 02:56:47.017
the whole place around her became alive,

02:56:47.397 --> 02:56:50.037
the strange creatures of her little sister's dream.

02:56:51.057 --> 02:56:54.857
The long grass rustled at her feet, as the white rabbit hurried by.

02:56:55.517 --> 02:56:58.417
The frightened mouse splashed his way through the neighbouring pool.

02:56:58.417 --> 02:57:00.897
She could hear the rattle of the teacups,

02:57:00.977 --> 02:57:03.977
as the March Hare and his friends shared their never-ending meal,

02:57:04.257 --> 02:57:09.277
and the shrill voice of the Queen ordering off her unfortunate guests to execution.

02:57:10.297 --> 02:57:13.377
Once more the pig baby was sneezing on the Duchess's knee,

02:57:13.777 --> 02:57:15.857
while plates and dishes crashed around it.

02:57:16.137 --> 02:57:17.937
Once more the shriek of the griffon,

02:57:18.397 --> 02:57:20.597
the squealing of the lizard's slate pencil,

02:57:21.137 --> 02:57:24.197
and the choking of the suppressed guinea pigs filled with the air,

02:57:24.577 --> 02:57:27.877
mixed up with the distant sobs of the miserable mock turtle.

02:57:28.597 --> 02:57:33.557
So she sat on, with closed eyes, and half believed herself in wonderland,

02:57:34.157 --> 02:57:36.557
though she knew she had but to open them again,

02:57:36.817 --> 02:57:38.897
and all would change to dull reality.

02:57:39.817 --> 02:57:41.817
The grass would be only rustling in the wind,

02:57:42.097 --> 02:57:44.557
and the pool rippling to the waving of the reeds.

02:57:45.197 --> 02:57:47.957
The rattling teacups would change to tinkling sheep bells,

02:57:48.357 --> 02:57:51.317
and the Queen's shrill cries to the voice of the shepherd boy.

02:57:52.057 --> 02:57:55.037
And the sneeze of the baby, the shriek of the griffon,

02:57:55.037 --> 02:57:58.377
and all the other queer noises would change, she knew,

02:57:58.817 --> 02:58:02.237
to the confused clamour of the busy farmyard,

02:58:02.557 --> 02:58:04.277
while the lowing of the cattle in the distance

02:58:04.277 --> 02:58:07.457
would take the place of the mock turtle's heavy sobs.

02:58:08.397 --> 02:58:11.097
Lastly, she pictured to herself

02:58:11.097 --> 02:58:15.017
how this same little sister of hers would, in the after time,

02:58:15.637 --> 02:58:17.077
be herself a grown woman,

02:58:17.617 --> 02:58:20.417
and how she would keep through all her wiper years

02:58:20.417 --> 02:58:22.597
the simple and loving heart of her childhood,

02:58:22.597 --> 02:58:25.737
and how she would gather about her other little children

02:58:25.737 --> 02:58:29.697
and make their eyes bright and eager with many a strange tale,

02:58:30.497 --> 02:58:33.417
perhaps even with the dream of wonderland of long ago,

02:58:34.157 --> 02:58:37.557
and how she would feel with all their simple sorrows,

02:58:38.317 --> 02:58:41.417
and find a pleasure in all their simple joys,

02:58:42.077 --> 02:58:43.797
remembering her own child life,

02:58:44.577 --> 02:58:46.597
and the happy summer days.

02:58:46.597 --> 02:58:51.297
This is the end of Alice's Adventures in Wonderland.
